<1ST_LINE>r i AM-DominicanRepublic 1stLd-Writethru a0817 02-26 0465</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dominican Republic, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0817,0474</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>President Says Army Will Quell Disturbances; 3 Dead</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 3 grafs for 4th pvs: `The protests ...' to UPDATE with
Sanchez Ramirez strike settled. Pickup 5th pvs: `In Azua ...'
DELETES grafs 9-10 pvs: `Unrest began ...' to CONFORM</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto SD1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RUDDY GONZALEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTO DOMINGO, Dominican Republic (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Joaquin
Balaguer said Thursday he will call out the army if necessary to
quell disturbances that cost three lives in two days.
   Balaguer also asked for his entire Cabinet's resignation, saying
it had to be ``restructured to respond to the present
circumstances.''
   In the central and northeastern provinces, police battled
demonstrators who blocked the main avenues in the cities and threw
rocks at police and commercial establishments.
   Late Thursday, authorities said a 72-hour strike had ended in
east-central Sanchez Ramirez province, where protests started 11
years ago. Peasants there demonstrated against alleged cyanide and
sulfur contamination of rivers from a state-owned gold mine.
   Earlier, company officials denied any contamination existed but
said that up to 130 families would be moved to a farm inside the
province away from the mine.
   The protests, which grew to include other issues, have been the
worst since Balaguer took office 1{ years ago in this Caribbean
island nation of more than 6.5 million people.
   In Azua, 75 miles west of the capital city of Santo Domingo,
protesters detonated homemade bombs and burned tires in some areas,
but police said most of the town was under control.
   A 15-year-old newspaper vendor shot in Azua on Wednesday was
reported to have died. Two other people were killed Wednesday.
   More than a dozen people have been reported wounded by gunfire
and an undetermined number have been arrested in the eight
provinces affected by the unrest.
   Much of the country's commercial activity has been paralyzed and
schools remained closed.
   The protests spread to other parts of the country, where
residents demanded capital improvements and government action to
control inflation estimated at about 30 percent annually.
   Balaguer went on television to deliver his message from the
National Palace shortly after midnight Wednesday. He said the
government would tolerate public protests as long as they were
peaceful but would not accept acts of vandalism and violence.
   ``If the circumstances demand it ... we will confront these
demonstrations and use all the military and physical power the
state has to stop them,'' he said.
   He added, however, that his government would not repeat the
events in 1984, when soldiers shot and killed almost 100 people
demonstrating against price increases.
   ``We won't have a slaughter like the one April 23, 24 and 25,
1984,'' he said.
   There was no word on whether the Cabinet had submitted its
resignation and no replacements were announced.
</TEXT>
