<1ST_LINE>u a AM-SFBudget     02-26 0305</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-SF Budget,0313</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mayor Calls For Drastic Measures To Cope With $172 Million Deficit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mayor Art Agnos on Friday said the city
faces a whopping $172 million budget deficit next year that will
require layoffs, ``painful'' cuts in service and possibly tax
increases and fare hikes.
   ``This is the worst budget crisis in the modern history of San
Francisco,'' declared Agnos, who was inaugurated in January.
   ``To close this kind of gap, we have to consider big cuts _
things like closing hospital wards, clinics and mental health
programs, freezing city employee pay, shutting branch libraries and
cutting back bus runs,'' he said.
   Agnos, flanked by his fiscal advisers, said at a news conference
that the latest, revised budget analysis indicates the city faces a
$172.4 million deficit, nearly $100 million more than was forecast
in November.
   ``At the same time we were contemplating these kinds of painful
service cuts, we could be asking citizens to put up with higher
Muni fares, parking rate hikes, added business levies and increased
fees for city services,'' Agnos said.
   The mayor said the $172.4 million deficit is the equivalent of
more than 5,000 city jobs. He offered no specific targets in regard
to layoffs.
   The more than doubling of the deficit was blamed largely on an
estimated drop in revenue of $28 million; $40 million in judgments
against the city from employee litigation, and rising costs of
employee health benefits and other programs.
   ``There is no easy way out of this problem,'' the mayor said.
``Everyone in this city is going to have to bear some pain to get
our fiscal house back in order.''
   Agnos stopped short of blaming his predecessor, Dianne
Feinstein, for the financial crisis but said the city's surplus of
$150 million in 1982-83 ``has dropped to ground zero.''
</TEXT>
