<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Vatican-Budget     02-26 0308</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Vatican-Budget,310</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Vatican Opens Books In Effort To Raise Money</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Vatican revealed its financial statement
for the first time in history Thursday, disclosing that the
administrative headquarters for the world's 840 million Roman
Catholics ran an operating deficit of $56.7 million in 1986, The
Washington Post reported in Friday's editions.
   The statement was made public by the Washington-based National
Conference of Catholic Bishops, ending centuries of secrecy.
   Cardinal John Krol said a 15-man council of cardinals on which
he sits decided last October to release the information in the hope
such openness would stimulate the faithful to contribute more to
the church.
   The deficit was met by taking $32 million from Peter's pence,
the Vatican's annual worldwide collection intended for charitable
purposes, and $24.7 million more from the fund's reserve, the Post
said.
   The Peter's pence collection for the first nine months of 1987
totaled $35.8 million, an increase attributed at least in part to
repeated pleas for help, the newspaper said.
   The document revealed that Vatican expenses in 1986 totaled
nearly $114 million, with the largest chunk, $58 million, spent for
personnel. That included $50.6 million for the Vatican's 2,395
employees and $7.3 million for pension payments to 885 retirees.
   Other major expenses included $11.7 million for publishing, $11
million in expenditures related to investments, $10.4 million for
equipment and operating costs of Vatican Radio and $9.7 million for
administrative expenses ranging from stationery to the costs of
worldwide synods of bishops.
   Operating income comes from investments, publishing, endowments
and Vatican Radio's sale of tapes of papal speeches and radio
programs.
   ``We need complete accounting,'' Krol told U.S. bishops at their
annual meeting here last fall. ``It's the only way to go.''
   Krol retird last month as head of the Philadelphia archdiocese
but continues to head special fund-raising efforts for the church.
</TEXT>
