<1ST_LINE>u a AM-HelicopterCrash 7thLd-Writethru a0880 02-26 0700</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Helicopter Crash, 7th Ld - Writethru, a0880,0716</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Military Copter Catches Fires and Crashes; Nine Killed</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES death toll to nine, with nine injured and 18 aboard.
PICKS UP 8th graf pvs, `The cause ...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JEFF AWALT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICO, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Army helicopter caught fire and crashed
in a pasture Thursday, killing nine soldiers and seriously burning
nine, authorities said.
   Two soldiers fell 35 feet after leaping from the burning
twin-rotor CH-47D Chinook as it hurtled toward the ground about 50
miles from Fort Worth, said state Department of Public Safety Sgt.
Robert Rankin. One of the soldiers died.
   The other soldier said that a fire had broken out at the back of
the helicopter based at Fort Sill, Okla., and that those aboard had
tried to move to the front to get away from the flames, according
to Rankin.
   ``We do have some witnesses who said they saw parts falling off
back toward Chico (several miles away), and some of the witnesses
said it was on fire before impact,'' he said.
   Nine soldiers were killed and nine injured, said Fort Hood
spokesman Lt. Col. Michael Miller. Eighteen people were aboard,
said Rick Brink, a Fort Sill spokesman. The injured were listed in
serious and critical condition.
   Many of the soldiers suffered third-degree burns, some over
their entire bodies; others were wrapped in body bags after
firefighters extinguished the grass fire, authorities said.
   Seven soldiers died at the scene of the afternoon crash, which
sparked a grass fire, said Lt. Brad Schuldt of Carswell Air Force
Base. Another soldier died at Parkland Memorial Hospital, said
administrator Paula Sears.
   A ninth soldier died at Bridgeport Hospital, said Justice of the
Peace Dawayne Kennedy.
   The cause of the crash was not immediately known. A team of
investigators from Fort Rucker, Ala., was en route Thursday night,
said Col. Herbert Blanks.
   In 1985, the Army grounded its entire fleet of 63 of the giant
CH-47D helicopters after an accident in Honduras injured eight
soldiers. The order was lifted after a month and a half.
   Wendell Berry, a farmer, said he saw the copter skid about 75
yards before breaking apart in flames Thursday. He said he tried to
fight the flames with a fire extinguisher and helped douse burning
bodies scattered about the wreckage.
   ``We put a lot of fire (on people) out,'' Berry said. ``We
couldn't do very much but get 'em out of the way. We actually could
do very little. Nobody could really do anything.''
   ``One was up walking around, the rest were out on ground. I cut
the pilot or the assistant pilot. I cut his seatbelt loose,'' he
added. ``He was wanting me to cut him out of there and I did that.
He was conscious talking to me.''
   The copter was returning to Fort Sill from Fort Hood in central
Texas with five soldiers from Fort Sill and 12 from Fort Hood
aboard, said Capt. Tim Vane of Fort Hood. The Chinook can carry
more than 33 combat-equipped soldiers.
   Winford McDaniel, supervisor of a rock-crushing business two
miles from the crash site, said a large part fell from the copter
and landed near the plant.
   ``It looks like an exhaust pipe,'' he said. ``It's a round piece
about three feet long and three feet across.''
   ``I was driving west of Chico and saw smoke coming out of the
helicopter and knew it was going to crash,'' said James St. John.
``I drove out there and it had already crashed. I seen it when it
was going down, but not when it crashed.''
   The CH-47D is a modernized version of the earlier models of the
Chinook, which for years has been a part of the Army inventory.
   In the Honduras accident, a transmission bearing failed on a
CH-47D taxiing to a refueling depot. The failure caused one of the
copter's main rotors to stop turning; the other rotor began hitting
it and the helicopter tore itself apart.
   The Chinooks's main rotors mesh as they turn, and therefore must
be synchronized.
   Eight soldiers were killed in April 1986 when a CH-47 and
another helicopter collided at Hunter Army Airfield in Georgia.
</TEXT>
