<FILEID>AP-NR-02-26-88 0340EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Profile-Noriega     02-26 0423</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Profile-Noriega,0434</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Noriega Characterized As Shrewd, Wily Politician</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Similar version in Friday AMs report.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega is a
shrewd, tough politician who has shown he can hold on tightly to
his position as the de facto ruler of Panama.
   Supporters call Noriega, in English, ``The Man,'' a takeoff on
his initials. Critics call him, in Spanish, ``Cara de Pina'' or
``Pineapple Face,'' because of his pocked and jowly visage.
   The United States calls him a fugitive from justice, a man who
put himself and his country up for sale to drug traffickers and
made millions of dollars in the process.
   Indictments returned by federal grand juries in Miami and Tampa,
Fla., on Feb. 5 accuse Noriega of using his position as the
commander of the Defense Forces to permit Colombian drug
traffickers to make Panama a base for smuggling cocaine and
marijuana into the United States.
   Noriega was born into poverty and raised by foster parents from
the age of 5.
   Details of Noriega's early life are scarce and even his birthday
is in dispute. His official biography lists his age as 50, but high
school records put it at 54.
   After attending a military college in Peru on a scholarship,
Noriega entered the Panamanian National Guard in 1962 as a
lieutenant. He quickly became acquainted with a rising young
officer named Omar Torrijos.
   Torrijos took power in Panama in a 1968 coup and less than a
year later named Noriega, then an obscure major in charge of the
country's northernmost province, as his chief of intelligence with
the rank of lieutenant colonel.
   In his new position, Noriega began collecting dossiers on
everyone who counted in Panama, friends and enemies alike. He also
had jurisdiction over the country's customs and immigration
departments, long a source of funds for the military.
   When Torrijos died in an unexplained airplane crash in 1981,
Noriega was well placed to shoulder his way to the top command
ahead of several more senior officers. It took him two years.
   Panama has been rocked by protests since last June, when
Noriega's recently retired second in command publicly charged the
general with drug trafficking, electoral fraud and the
assassination of a political opponent.
   Noriega also has been accused of having his finger in a wide
variety of other enterprises, some legal and others operating on
the fringes of the law. They are said to include duty free liquor
stores, maritime services, banks, gambling casinos, newspapers, a
television station and 12 radio stations.
</TEXT>
