<DOCNO> AP880226-0015 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-26-88 0330EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Dole-South Bjt   02-26 0880</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dole-South, Bjt,850</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dole, Lagging In South, Hopes Popular Vote In Region Won't Decide
The Race</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONALD M. ROTHBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bob Dole wants to believe that the key
southern test in the Republican presidential race will occur not on
Super Tuesday, but next August in New Orleans.
   That's a strategy heavily dependent on a strong assist from Pat
Robertson, who has the potential to muddy the outcome on March 8,
when 20 states, most of them Southern and border states, will hold
Republican primaries or caucuses.
   ``I've got a feeling we may be headed all the way to New
Orleans,'' the Kansas senator says at every campaign stop in the
South, referring to the Republican National Convention next August.
   Dole may just be whistling ``Dixie'' as he tries to negotiate an
electoral minefield that appears to favor Vice President George
Bush.
   There were two key events. The first was New Hampshire where a
Dole victory would have completely altered the picture in the South
where Bush has a strong organization and benefits from President
Reagan's popularity.
   But the Kansas senator, a big winner in Iowa, fell short in New
Hampshire and had to devise a strategy based on the assumption that
Bush will be the big popular vote winner on Super Tuesday.
   The next test that could change the current outlook for March 8
is the South Carolina Republican primary that occurs three days
before Super Tuesday.
   ``The name of the game now is delegates,'' was the cry from Dole
aides.
   Eddie Mahe, a Republican political consultant not involved with
any presidential campaign, agreed with that approach.
   ``If I was advising any of these people, I would say, `Don't
worry about the next day's headline (about who carried the popular
vote in how many Super Tuesday states), worry about the following
day's delegate-count story, that's the story that counts,''' he
said.
   ``It's going to be relatively difficult for the Bush forces to
come out with much more than a bare majority at best, the other
delegates being split between Robertson and Dole,'' said Dole
adviser David Keene, as the Dole entourage flew South after his
victories in the South Dakota primary and Minnesota caucuses on
Tuesday.
   Within 24 hours, however, Keene and Donald Devine, another
senior campaign adviser, were fired in a dispute with campaign
manager William Brock, the former Tennessee senator and secretary
of labor.
   But the strategy outlined by Keene still appeared to offer the
clearest hope for Dole to survive until the campaign moves back to
the Midwest where he has trounced Bush in three states.
   Bush and former television evangelist Robertson look like the
most formidable competitors in the South, an assessment Dole and
his advisers do not dispute.
   In addition to the Southern and border states voting on Super
Tuesday, the schedule includes balloting in Massachusetts, Rhode
Island, Nevada, Oklahoma and Washington.
   Keene named North Carolina, Oklahoma, Missouri, Washington and
``possibly Florida'' as the states Dole had the best chance to win
on Super Tuesday. That's not a very long list.
   But most states elect their delegates by congressional districts
and can be viewed as a series of district elections. That means it
is possible that while Bush would easily carry the popular vote,
his rivals would carry a lot of districts and their delegates.
   South Carolina stands alone on March 5 and it is open to every
registered voter. In addition, the Democrats don't hold caucuses
until a week later, so there is no Democratic contest to distract
voters from the GOP primary.
   Mahe said a lot of Republicans don't see a lot of difference
between Bush and Dole and also are very concerned about the
possibility of Robertson emerging as the nominee.
   A Robertson victory in South Carolina could have a major impact
on those voters.
   ``People who genuinely have a sense of concern, whether they
should or they shouldn't about Pat Robertson, who saw George Bush
lose again to Pat Robertson in South Carolina where he had the
governor going for him, seemingly everything going for him, they
might say, well, maybe we ought to go with Bob Dole,'' said Mahe.
   The same logic says that a Bush victory in South Carolina could
open the gates for a big Super Tuesday win for the vice president.
   Dole has South Carolina Sen. Strom Thurmond on his side and also
supports legislation to limit textile imports, a popular stand in a
state where 45 percent of the jobs are in the textile industry.
Bush opposes the bill.
   Dole has a similar advantage on a highly visible issue in
Louisiana where the Kansan supports an oil import fee while Bush
opposes it. Glen Beauerman, Dole's campaign manager in Louisiana,
said surveys say 70 percent of people in the oil and gas producing
state support an import fee.
   But it's the Robertson factor rather than issues that could keep
Bush from harvesting enough Super Tuesday delegates to make him
unstoppable.
   ``Up and down East Texas Pat Robertson is a real threat in a lot
of districts,'' said Mahe. ``But there's enough Bush-type people in
those districts for George to win all of them if they turn out and
vote. They have not been turning out in very good numbers.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
