<1ST_LINE>r a PM-USDefector     02-26 0494</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-US Defector,0508</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Army Private Convicted Of Being AWOL, Gets Bad Conduct Discharge</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NICHOLAS G. KATSARELAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FORT DIX, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A U.S. soldier was acquitted of desertion
and given a bad conduct discharge for fleeing his West German base
to live in the Soviet Union, shocking prosecutors who had expected
him to do prison time.
   Courtroom spectators, mostly military personnel, gasped when
presiding judge Col. Earl Pauley ordered Pfc. Wade E. Roberts, 22,
of Riverside, Calif., released from military custody Thursday.
   ``I feel great!'' Roberts said after he was convicted of a
lesser charge of being absent without leave and given a bad conduct
discharge.
   Roberts, described by a superior as ``the most reprehensible,
casual soldier'' in his command but as ``confused'' by his
attorneys, said he will live in West Germany with his wife, Petra
Neumann, and their 3-month-old son.
   The military pressed hard for a conviction of desertion during
the 1{-day courtmartial at Fort Dix. That offense carries a maximum
penalty of a dishonorable discharge and three years' imprisonment.
   ``I'm shocked,'' said Capt. Daniel Shaver, chief military
attorney. He said the Army expected Roberts to be sentenced to the
maximum AWOL penalty of a dishonorable discharge and one year's
imprisonment.
   When the sentence was read, Roberts and his attorneys broke into
wide grins, and the soldier and his wife embraced and kissed.
Shaver's jaw dropped, and he stared at the judge.
   To prove desertion, the Army had to demonstrate that when
Roberts left his base at Giessen, West Germany, last February, he
never intended to return to the Army.
   The prosecution produced a half-dozen witnesses in an effort to
show Roberts didn't like the Army, talked about leaving, didn't get
along with his superiors and had disciplinary problems.
   But Roberts' attorneys argued their client fled his unit because
was harassed by his superiors for, among other things, dating Ms.
Neumann because she was German.
   When he took the stand Thursday, Roberts told how one of his
sergeants told him to stay away from German women. Roberts said he
``panicked'' because he didn't want to leave Ms. Neumann, and
scaled a fence at the base.
   When they went to the Soviet Union, they were put to work on a
snake farm, but quickly became disenchanted with Soviet life.
   After getting Soviet approval, Roberts and his wife flew to
Frankfurt, West Germany, on Nov. 4 and was told by a U.S. embassy
official to turn himself over to the military the next day. Before
he could, however, he was arrested by the Army.
   Roberts' civilian attorney, Ronald Kuby, asked for lenient
treatment. ``Private Wade Roberts is not cut out for the Army. He
doesn't need the Army. The Army doesn't need him,'' Kuby said.
   Roberts returned to the Philadelphia Naval Yard brig, where he
has been held for the past several months, to pick up his
belongings, and went to an undisclosed location with Ms. Neumann,
officials said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
