<FILEID>AP-NR-02-26-88 0417EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Pesticides-Groundwater     02-26 0759</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Pesticides-Groundwater,750</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>EPA Proposes Giving States More Leeway to Permit Chemical Use</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GUY DARST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Reagan administration is proposing that
states with approved groundwater protection plans be given
discretion to permit use of some pesticides that otherwise would be
banned.
   The proposal was unveiled Thursday in the form of a draft
strategy released for public comment.
   Groundwater provides drinking water for half the U.S. population
and for 97 percent of people living in rural areas. EPA says it
expects to complete a survey in 1990 on the extent of contamination.
   EPA licenses new pesticides, and is gradually re-licensing all
the old ones. As it makes those licensing decisions, it tries to
take into account the chemical's ability to leach into groundwater
_ which can depend on many things, including soil permeability and
application method.
   EPA expects to ban the use of some chemicals in specific states
or counties, while allowing use in others. The new strategy is
designed to allow states facing such bans to overturn them provided
they show that groundwater supplies will not be contaminated
significantly.
   John A. Moore, EPA's assistant administrator for pesticides and
toxic substances, said the agency's ``ability to do something at
these levels (counties and below) is not good.''
   States with plans could employ geological, land use, crop
pattern and water data to justify decisions that would run counter
to EPA determinations.
   ``Where found appropriate, EPA would consider modifying the
federal registration to accommodate the state program,'' the agency
said.
   In making decisions, both EPA and the states would use current
drinking water standards, where they exist, for chemicals that
don't cause cancer. For carcinogens, the agency would permit
contamination to a level that would mean a one-in-a-million chance
of cancer over a lifetime.
   If there are no drinking water standards _ only six have been
established for pesticides, with another 10 in the pipeline _ then
EPA would determine the permissible pesticide concentration in
groundwater supplies.
   Though several other federally mandated environmental programs
are run by states _ one example is strip mine reclamation _ Moore
acknowledged that ``there are no good models'' of states being
allowed to make exceptions to federal rules like what EPA is
proposing for pesticides.
   He said EPA would ``periodically revisit and reassure ourselves
that what the state had put together was being maintained,'' Moore
said.
   He singled out California, Iowa, Illinois, Wisconsin and Florida
as states with active pesticide-groundwater programs, generally
combining state agriculture, health and environmental protection
departments.
   Moore said he expected cooperation from farmers and their trade
groups: ``If there's been one area where I haven't had to convince
the user community they should pay attention, this is it. It's
their wells and their children drinking the water,'' Moore said.
   Pesticide contamination of groundwater is a relatively new
issue, and as recently as 10 years ago most government officials
and scientists believed it didn't happen. They thought the
chemicals didn't last long enough or penetrate far enough down.
   The first serious contamination cases were reported in New York
and California in 1979.
   Two years ago, EPA said 19 pesticides had been found in
groundwater in 24 states; today, said Patrick Holden, team leader
of the groundwater project in EPA's pesticides office, 50 to 60
different chemicals have been found in wells in 30 states. Iowa has
found pesticides in half the wells serving cities.
   Pesticides are not the only contaminants. Fertilizers, waste
disposal wells and leaking underground tanks all can contribute
substantially.
   EPA plans to adopt a groundwater strategy that would require
states to classify supplies, known as aquifers, in a three-tier
priority system _ high priority protection, drinking water sources,
and water needing little protection.
   Many environmentalists object to the plan, saying it would write
off a substantial percentage of groundwater supplies.
   Sen. David Durenberger, R-Minn., on Thursday introduced at least
the 10th bill this session calling for minimum federal standards
for all aquifers.
   The senator said he would have to study EPA's proposal for the
states. An aide, Jimmie Powell, said that ``to the extent you can
manage pesticides for their leaching ability, it could be a
reasonable proposal'' to let states make detailed, area-specific
management decisions along the lines EPA is proposing.
   But Rick Hind of the U.S. Public Interest Research Group said
EPA's use of a one-in-a-million standard for carcinogens is ``too
soft.'' He also said the drinking water standards for
non-carcinogens is based ``partly on the cost of cleaning it up''
and thus inappropriate for a strategy of protecting public health.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
