<FILEID>AP-NR-02-26-88 0322EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-FarmScene     02-26 0959</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Farm Scene,950</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>US Farm Exports To Reach Four-Year High In Fiscal 1988</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto WX6</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The outlook for U.S. farm exports continues to
improve as the Soviet Union begins a new round of corn purchases.
   Overall, the Agriculture Department says the value of U.S.
agricultural exports will rise to a four-year high of $32.5 billion
in the 1988 fiscal year that began Oct. 1.
   Spurred by recent heavy sales of grain to the Soviet Union and
China, partly under a special export subsidy program, the new 1988
forecast is up $500 million from $32 billion indicated on Dec. 17.
   Steve MacDonald of the department's Economic Research Service
said the Soviet Union may account for $1.7 billion of the total
export value this year, the most since 1985 when Moscow's purchases
totaled $2.5 billion. Soviet purchases last year were valued at
about $700 million.
   China's U.S. purchases are expected to be around $500 million,
more than double the $200 million of 1987, he said.
   The new export forecast came Thursday as the department
announced another cash sale of corn to the Soviet Union, the second
in two days.
   With a shipment value of $32 billion, this year's exports would
be up 16 percent from $27.9 billion in 1987 and 24 percent from a
decade low of $26.3 billion in 1986. Agricultural exports were
valued at $31.2 billion in fiscal 1985 and $38 billion in 1984.
   ``Most of the increase (from the earlier estimate) stems from
additional wheat sales under the Export Enhancement Program ,'' the
department said. ``Since the December forecast, EEP offers were
announced for 2 million metric tons of wheat to the Soviet Union
and 1.2 million tons to China, among others.''
   Under the EEP arrangement, private exporters get free surplus
commodities from the Agriculture Department as subsidies so they
can sell grain and other products overseas at reduced prices.
   On the basis of actual volume, 1988 exports were indicated at
142.5 million metric tons, up from 141 million forecast in December
and 129.2 million tons shipped last year.
   ``The U.S. share of the world market, particularly in grains and
cotton, is rising,'' officials said in their report. ``Relatively
low world prices and improved U.S. competitiveness through lower
(price support) loan rates, the EEP and a lower dollar have reduced
production incentives for foreign competitors.''
   Meanwhile, private exporters reported the sales of 601,600 tons
of corn for delivery to the Soviet Union this year under a
long-term supply agreement between the two countries.
   On Wednesday, the Soviets bought 350,000 tons of corn, the first
substantial amount since last October. Corn sales are not qualified
for EEP subsidies, however.
   A metric ton is about 2,205 pounds and is equal to 39.4 bushels
of corn or 36.7 bushels of wheat or soybeans. The 601,600 tons of
corn would be about 24 million bushels, having a farm value of
around $44 million at recent prices of about $1.82 per bushel.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Shipments of federally inspected reindeer
steaks across the country would be allowed under a proposal being
considered by the Agriculture Department.
   There is mandatory federal inspection of cattle, hogs, chickens
and turkeys at slaughter plants, which allows those carcasses to be
shipped across state lines.
   In addition, regulations permit the voluntary inspection of
certain exotic animals slaughtered for human food. Those include
the American bison, or buffalo, and the cattalo, a cross between
cattle and the buffalo.
   Lester M. Crawford, head of the department's Food Safety and
Inspection Service, said Thursday producers of exotic animals have
asked the inspection list be expanded to include reindeer, elk,
deer, antelope and water buffalo.
   ``This proposal is a response to their request and could
facilitate the sale and export of the carcasses, meat and meat food
products from these animals,'' he sad. ``Once the animals and
products are inspected and passed, they can be sold interstate or
exported.''
   Producers of the animals would pay fees to receive the optional
inspection service. Crawford said fewer than 2,000 exotic animals
are slaughtered annually at the present time and that the slaughter
level is not expected to increase much if the exotic list is
expanded.
   By comparison, he said, annual cattle slaughter has been running
at more than 32 million head.
   Public comments on the proposal can be sent by April 26 to:
Linda Carey, FSIS Hearing Clerk, Room 3168-S, FSIS, USDA,
Washington, D.C. 20250.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   United Airlines Inc. has paid an $11,000 civil
penalty to settle 1987 charges by the Agriculture Department that
it violated federal transportation standards for shipments of live
animals.
   The penalty was assessed by the department in an administrative
action stemming from nine shipments of dogs and monkeys in 1985 and
1986. A complaint was filed against United last year by the
department's Animal and Plant Health Inspection Service, which
administers the Animal Welfare Act.
   James W. Glosser, acting administrator of the agency, said
Thursday the complaints alleged that United had accepted dogs in
shipping kennels that did not conform to size requirement, and that
the airline ``either failed to observe and care for the dogs
properly'' or stowed them in cargo space without sufficient
ventiliation.
   Two dogs died during shipment and another was killed by highway
traffic after it escaped shipment, Glosser said. The airline also
was cited for having ``allegedly accepted a shipment of 50 monkeys
in cages that were not structurally sound'' and had no markings to
tell they contained wild animals, he said.
   Glosser said United also consented to an order against future
violations of the act and agreed within a year to buy a training
film approved by USDA and show it to all employees who handle live
animal cargoes.
</TEXT>
