<DOCNO> AP880226-0028 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-26-88 0427EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Dukakis     02-26 0518</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dukakis,490</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Warns He May Strike Back At Gephardt If Attacks Continue</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID ESPO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Dukakis, urged by his aides to begin
returning campaign fire, says Democratic presidential rival Richard
Gephardt ``better watch out'' if he persists with his sharp attacks
in the battle for the party's nomination.
   ``I've been in negative campaigns before and I can tell you if
people want to be negative, I know what to do,'' the Massachusetts
governor said Thursday as he opened a three-day campaign trip
through Dixie.
   ``I hope we don't go down that road,'' he said, adding that
negative attacks during the nominating battle would only damage
Democrats' chances of capturing the White House.
   Dukakis issued his warning one day after Gephardt unleashed a
stinging attack, the latest in a string that the governor's aides
believe may be taking a toll. The Missouri congressman said Dukakis
and Tennessee Sen. Albert Gore Jr. had ``hardly a dime's worth of
difference'' on economic issues.
   Gephardt said Dukakis' foreign policy experience consisted
mostly of ``negotiating with the governor of New Hampshire over the
use of nuclear power.''
   And he summarized Dukakis' campaign bitingly, calling him ``the
candidate with the most money and the least message.''
   Gephardt also has attacked Dukakis in television commercials.
   Yet with the campaign in an intensive phase leading to the 21
Super Tuesday primaries and caucuses set for March 8, Dukakis so
far has declined to respond with anything approaching the vehemence
used by Gephardt.
   Instead, he has replied with indirect attacks and issued a
series of increasingly stern warnings.
   ``If people want to get negative, I've had experience with
negative campaigns,'' he said at a news conference in Boca Raton,
Fla. ``If you've got a record as vulnerable as his is, you'd better
watch out, that's all I can say.
   The Massachusetts governor also chided Gore and Gephardt for
``going at each other'' in a mananer resembling Republican
presidential rivals George Bush and Bob Dole.
   ``I don't think this `prince of darkness' routine is going to
sell,'' he said.
   But some aides say they believe that negative television
commercials played a role in Gephardt's victory in the South Dakota
primary on Tuesday, a conclusion also reinforced by some public
opinion polls.
   And with the critical Southern primaries approaching, the
governor is getting advice to respond more sharply to Gephardt.
   ``We have to knock this negative campaigning out of the box,''
said S. Stephen Rosenfeld, Florida campaign manager for Dukakis.
``My own view is that it comes home to roost, but we've got to make
it come home to roost (for Gephardt) sooner rather than later.''
   Rosenfeld said he has told Dukakis as much and the governor
``made it very clear that it's important to respond.''
   But so far, Dukakis has passed up every opportunity.
   When he and Gephardt shared a stage to discuss long-term health
care before a group of senior citizens, his most biting comment was
a mild jab.
   Askdd if he had flip-flopped on the issue, Dukakis replied:
``There's the flip-flopper over there. I'm not the flip-flopper.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
