<1ST_LINE>r w PM-GM-SuddenAcceleration     02-26 0387</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-GM-Sudden Acceleration,400</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>NHTSA Quizzes GM Over Recall Withdrawal Recommendation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM BOVEE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The National Highway Traffic Safety Board is
asking General Motors Corp. to explain why its engineers withdrew a
recommendation that 703,225 cars be recalled because of possible
sudden acceleration problems.
   The Center for Auto Safety, a consumers group often at odds with
the automakers and their regulators, contends that the engineers
were pressured to change their position. GM has denied the
allegation.
   NHTSA is asking GM to describe the company's Product Problem
Evaluation Committee in Flint, Mich., which made the recommendation.
   A NHTSA letter released Thursday also asked GM to state whether
the committee memo withdrawing the recall recommendation
``constitutes a legitimate PPEC report.''
   NHTSA is investigating alleged throttle problems that produce
sudden acceleration in the 1986-87 Oldsmobile Delta 88 and Buick
LeSabre, and the 1987 Pontiac Bonneville.
   The agency has received 573 complaints of alleged sudden
acceleration in the cars, resulting in reports of 343 accidents,
145 injuries and one death, said Joe Collins, NHTSA spokesman. None
of the reports has been substantiated by the agency, Collins said.
   GM spokesman David Hudgens said it was ``preposterous'' to
suggest the engineers were pressured.
   ``We don't do business that way,'' Hudgens said.
   The automaker was preparing a response to NHTSA, Hudgens said.
``In the NHTSA letter and our response, the question of pressure
doesn't come up,'' he said.
   The Center for Auto Safety said the engineers' decision to
withdraw their recall recommendation was suspicious because it came
just 18 days before GM would have had to tell NHTSA of the
recommendation.
   The timing ``suggests the clear possibility that the GM
engineers' change of heart may have been less than voluntary,'' the
center said in a petition to NHTSA.
   NHTSA declined to comment on the GM investigation, citing agency
policy.
   The GM memo, part of the public record of the NHTSA engineering
analysis, was in the form of a two-page handwritten note dated Oct.
23, 1987, saying, ``Withdraw recommendation for lack of data
support of a trend or high frequency'' on one page, and, ``Withdraw
recommendation to conduct field actions on throttle cables on all
cars for lack of data to conclude there is a problem'' on the other.
   The committee on Aug. 24, 1987, had recommended a recall.
</TEXT>
