<1ST_LINE>r a PM-KingHoliday     02-26 0307</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-King Holiday,0314</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Arizona Senate Moving On King Holiday Proposal</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Mecham Impeachment</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY LOPEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   State lawmakers say they believe they will
be able to approve a holiday to honor slain civil rights leader
Martin Luther King Jr. after the impeachment trial of Gov. Evan
Mecham.
   ``I promised the (acting) governor (Rose Mofford) that after the
trial's over that'll be one of the first things we'll try to do,''
Senate government committee chairman John Mawhinney said Thursday.
   Mecham, who rescinded the state's first King holiday in 1987,
goes on trial Monday in the Senate on a 23-count impeachment,
accused of concealing a campaign loan, misusing state funds and
trying to thwart an investigation.
   Acting Gov. Mofford supports a federal-style King holiday, and
lawmakers narrowed their focus on Thursday when the Senate rejected
a proposal to have voters decide whether to create a paid King
holiday.
   The vote leaves untouched two other measures more acceptable to
supporters of the holiday: a straight, federal-style holiday and a
``cafeteria bill'' that would late state workers pick a certain
number of holidays froom a list.
   The state's Republican-controlled legislature killed King
holiday proposals for a number of years, citing the estimated $3
million cost of a paid holiday for state employees.
   Then, Democrat Bruce Babbitt, about to launch a presidential
campaign, decided in 1986 to end his term as governor by bypassing
the legislature and creating a paid King holiday through executive
proclamation.
   Mecham, Babbitt's successor, promptly rescinded the order in
1987, citing an attorney general's advisory opinion that only
lawmakers or voters _ not governors _ could declare such holidays.
   Mecham's decision triggered international boycotts of the state
by musicians and convention groups, and the House approved a
federal-style King holiday last year, only to see the measure die
in committee.
</TEXT>
