<1ST_LINE>r w PM-ContraAid     02-26 0487</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Contra Aid,480</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>House Plans To Vote Next Week On Contra Plan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM DRINKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   House Democrats and House Republicans are
offering different reasons for why a vote on the Democratic plan to
send $30.5 milllion in aid to the Nicaraguan Contras was postponed
until next week.
   Democrats say they wanted time to explain better how the package
differs from a rival Republican version. Republicans sa the
Democrats feared the package would have lost if had been voted on
Thursday, as originally scheduled.
   House Speaker Jim Wright, D-Texas, said he planned to bring the
measure before the chamber for a vote next Thursday, and both sides
appeared likely to continue to fine-tune their aid packages to pick
up votes.
   ``Too many members have complained that they don't know what's
in it,'' Wright said Thursday.
   The Democratic version includes some $16 million in food,
clothing, shelter and medical aid to the rebels fighting
Nicaragua's leftist Sandinista government, and $14 million to set
up a medical aid fund for children who are victims of that
country's seven-year civil war.
   Current aid to the rebels, which includes authority for the CIA
to deliver previously stockpiled weapons and ammunition, ends Feb.
29.
   But the House GOP leader, Robert Michel of Illinois, said the
scheduled vote this week was postponed because Democrats feared
they would lose, the Republican package would have been approved,
``and that would have aced out the speaker.''
   The $36 million Republican plan offered somewhat more aid to the
rebels, included non-lethal military items like jeeps and radios,
and adopted the Democratic plan's call for a ``children's survival
fund.''
   But the primary difference between the two proposals lay in the
conditions they set for the next showdown over a military aid
proposal that both sides expect President Reagan to offer later
this year.
   Democrats want to make any future military aid proposal
contingent on a finding by the House Intelligence Committee
sometime after June 1 that the two warring sides in Nicaragua have
not agreed to a cease-fire because the Sandinistas did not make
good-faith efforts.
   If such a determination is made, the new aid package would be
designed and controlled by the House Democratic leadership. There
would be no guarantee that the package would be offered, or if it
were, that the Senate would be forced to act quickly on it.
   But the GOP version would leave the determination of whether to
offer a new aid proposal up to Reagan, and would contain much
stricter rules to make sure the package would be quickly acted on
in both the House and the Senate. The president could act anytime
after April 15, under this version.
   Rep. Tony Coelho of California, the chief House Democratic vote
counter, said failure by Congress to pass some form of aid would
increase pressure for a vote later in the year on more weapons for
the Contras.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
