<DOCNO> AP880226-0036 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-26-88 0440EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Burnley-Airports     02-26 0387</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Burnley-Airports,380</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Burnley Says New Airport Security System Is Coming</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's largest airports would have to
install new security systems to screen the movements of airport and
airline workers, under regulations the government is drafting, the
secretary of transportation says.
   The secretary, James H. Burnley IV, told Congress on Thursday
that the proposed regulations should be ready ``reasonably
quickly,'' and would take effect after allowing the airports time
to install the equipment.
   Under the new system, employees would carry magnetized
identification cards similar to automatic teller cards.
Computer-controlled gates set up throughout the airports would
admit only certain workers during specified hours, and could be
programmed to bar admission to people who leave their airport jobs.
   ``You can de-program a person out, limiting access to certain
areas,'' Burnley told the Senate transportation appropriations
subcommittee.
   He did not mention a cost or say how many airports would be
affected. A similar system is already in use at Washington Dulles
International Airport.
   Last Dec. 7, a fired USAir employee boarded a Pacific Southwest
Airlines jet after flashing his expired identification card to
airport security workers and shot his former boss and the plane's
crew in flight. The aircraft, bound to San Francisco from Los
Angeles, crashed in central California, killing all 44 people on
board.
   Burnley said he ordered the FAA to begin writing the new airport
security rule before Christmas.
   In other testimony, the secretary said the FAA will not be able
to meet the congressionally mandated level of 10,450 fully trained
air traffic controllers by Sept. 30. Instead, he projects that
9,932 so-called full-performance level controllers will be at work
at that date.
   He also said his agency is talking with the Air Force, which
plans to reduce its work force because of budget constraints, about
hiring air traffic controllers who lose jobs there.
   He also repeated the Reagan administration's refusal to rehire
any of the controllers fired after their 1980 strike, saying,
``They not only broke the law, they left the American people very
much in the lurch.''
   The government plans to have a total of 15,900 air traffic
controllers at work by Sept. 30, including trainees and
supervisors. It usually takes three to four years for a newly hired
controller to reach full-performance level.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
