<1ST_LINE>u a AM-NearCollision     02-26 0199</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Near Collision,0204</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Alaska Airlines Boeing 727 Involved in Near-Miss With Small Plane</HEAD>
<DATELINE>POMONA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The pilot of an Alaska Airlines Boeing 727
was forced to take evasive action and dive when an unidentified
small aircraft passed 100 feet over the jetliner Thursday night,
officials said.
   ``I don't know the exact distance but it was close. He took
evasive action. He dove to avoid collision,'' said Lou Cancelmi,
spokesman for Alaska Airlines said from Seattle, Wash. ``The pilot
took the plane down to get underneath it.''
   The pilot filed a a near-collision report with the Federal
Aviation Administration following the 6:36 p.m. incident over this
community 35 miles east of Los Angeles, said Dick Tornquist, an FAA
officer in Los Angeles.
   ``A pilot files a near-miss report when he fears his aircraft is
in jeopardy,'' the FAA official said.
   The incident occurred as the Alaska Airlines jetliner was
departing Ontario Airport en route to Seattle with 62 passengers
and seven crew members aboard, Cancelmi said.
   The Boeing 727 was flying at 7,000 feet when the unidentified
aircraft passed 100 feet overhead, Cancelmi said.
   The plane landed safely in Seattle and no injuries were
reported, he added.
</TEXT>
