<FILEID>AP-NR-02-26-88 0442EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Justice-Memo     02-26 0416</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Justice-Memo,430</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Top Justice Official Tells Department to `Polarize Debate' on
Issues</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Justice Department officials have been
directed to ``polarize the debate'' on key legal questions this
year including AIDS, which an internal memo says is ``not a civil
rights or privacy issue.''
   The document says issues such as AIDS and drugs should be
discussed not as questions of individual rights but as ``public
health or safety issues.''
   The memo was sent Monday to various Justice Department officials
under the initials of William Bradford Reynolds, the counselor to
Attorney General Edwin Meese III. Reynolds also is assistant
attorney general in charge of the civil rights division.
   ``We must polarize the debate,'' it says. ``We must not seek
`consensus,' we must confront. Of course, we must confront
sensibly, in ways designed to win the debate and further our
agenda.''
   The memo was adopted from a document assembled several months
ago by Terry Eastland, the department's director of public affairs,
who said he wrote it to stimulate discussion on how to approach
various Justice Department issues.
   The contents of the memo were disclosed in Thursday editions of
the Baltimore Sun and subsequently confirmed by Eastland.
   The document recommends that the death penalty be defended as
necessary for ``deterrence, retribution and incapacitation (i.e.
decapitation).''
   Eastland said the department is not in favor of decapitation as
a method of capital punishment, but that he used the word to make
``incapacitation'' seem ``less abstract and professorial.''
   The memo says that ``AIDS is not a civil rights or privacy
issue, but one of public health and safety'' and recommends that
the department press lawsuits that seek to counter ``the privacy
advocates who challenge AIDS testing.''
   Regarding obscenity, it says that the department ``must attack
the idea that those trafficking'' in it ``have a right to practice
their trade.'' It suggests that public health laws, building codes,
and health and safety rules be used to attack obscenity, along with
laws making sale of obscene items a crime.
   Entitled ``A Strategy for the Remaining Months,'' the document
says the drug issue should be confronted by advocating a ``tough
approach'' emphasizing strong law enforcement and drug testing, as
opposed to ``the soft, easy way that emphasizes drug treatment and
rehabilitation.''
   The memo supports construction of more prisons instead of
alternatives to imprisonment and says that ``to polarize the issue
we must attack those by name (such as Sen. Paul Simon) who take the
other approach.'' Simon is a Democratic presidential candidate.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880226-0039 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-26-88 0445EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Bush-Dole-Taxes     02-26 0783</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bush-Dole-Taxes,750</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Unlikely to Catch Dole Unawares on Tax Issue, Observers Say</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   George Bush's characterization of Republican
presidential rival Bob Dole as a supporter of tax increases is
unlikely to work as it did in New Hampshire because Dole is more
vigilant now, political and economics analysts say.
   Larry Sabato, a University of Virginia political scientist, said
Bush's New Hampshire commercial depicting Dole as straddling the
tax issue succeeded only because the Kansas senator ``chose not to
respond to it.''
   Martin Anderson, a domestic policy adviser during President
Reagan's first term, said the vice president damaged Dole's chances
in New Hampshire with the ad raising doubts about the Kansas
senator's tax intentions. But Anderson also said that Dole did
himself in by refusing to accept Pete du Pont's debate challenge to
sign a no-tax pledge.
   Economist Barry Bosworth of the liberal-oriented Brookings
Institution said Bush's accusations about Dole are specious, but
said the vice president adroitly played to an issue of great
sensitivity to people worried about their pocketbooks.
   ``I think Dole has learned from that (New Hampshire loss) and
you probably won't see this happen again,'' Bosworth said in an
interview.
   Several economists and political analysts were asked whether
Bush would be able to campaign successfully in the ensuing months
as an opponent of tax increases while characterizing Dole as a
tax-hike proponent.
   ``Bush has no record. Dole has a record which includes both
revenue increases, in concert with the (Reagan) administration, and
deficit reduction,'' said Bob McIntyre of the private group,
Citizens for Tax Justice.
   The question of whether Bush will be able to score political
points out of the tax issue arose in the wake of the vice
president's successful use in New Hampshire of a television
commercial which raised doubts about Dole's tax intentions.
   In the aftermath of his loss in New Hampshire, Dole acknowledged
that he should have responded immediately to Bush's ads. And on
Thursday, Dole announced the departure from his campaign staff of
consultants David Keene and Donald Devine.
   A check of the Republican presidential candidates' records shows
that while Bush succeeded in raising doubts in people's minds about
Dole's stance on taxes, neither man has a record of unqualified
opposition to tax hikes.
   Bush, last November, muted his disagreement with a
deficit-reduction package in which President Reagan and
congressional leaders, including Dole, signed a compact aimed at
slashing the federal deficit by $76 billion over the next two
years, in part with $22 billion in tax increases.
   Bush seemed to dissent when he told a crowd in Iowa that while
he didn't like the tax hikes envisioned in the package, ``I'll
support whatever compromise the president makes.''
   Bush had slipped a month earlier by launching his presidential
campaign with an uncompromising pledge to not raises taxes, only to
subsequently leave the door slightly ajar.
   In an Oct. 15 interview on Cable News Network, Bush backtracked
from the Oct. 12 Houston promise.
   ``What I have said is, if I were convinced that all spending
that could possibly be constrained or cut had taken place, then and
only then would I consider a tax increase,'' he said. Later the
same day, when pressed for an explanation, Bush replied, ``I'm not
going to raise taxes, period.''
   The Dole campaign promises to perform some political ``truth
squad'' work on Bush's commercials during the balance of the
campaign, and the Bush camp continues to deny that it distorted the
senator's position on taxes.
   But with both Dole and Bush, the record is full of
inconsistencies regarding both general tax increases and the
question of imposing an import fee on foreign oil.
   Dole supported the sweeping reduction in tax rates in 1981, but
helped enact a $98.3 billion tax hike a year later.
   During the 1980, Bush labeled as ``voodoo economics'' Reagan's
pledge to restore U.S. military might while cutting taxes and
balancing the budget. But the record shows no evidence of a Bush
dissent from tax increases that Reagan has signed in the ensuing
years.
   The record shows that Dole supported various deficit-reduction
tax hike proposals, including the $98.3 billion package, a $50.6
billion program in 1984 and the $22 billion in hikes contained in a
plan Reagan agreed to last Nov. 20 in the wake of the Wall Street
crash.
   Bosworth said that in times of general economic prosperity,
candidates for political office score big points by suggesting an
opponent would raise taxes.
   ``I think Dole has probably learned from this (loss in New
Hampshire),'' he said. ``It appears Republicans voted for Bush
there because he appeared to be more adamant about not raising
taxes than Dole was.''
</TEXT>
