<1ST_LINE>r w PM-US-Portugal     02-26 0285</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-US-Portugal,280</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Names Leader Of Group To Meet With Portuguese Over Bases</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALEXANDER G. HIGGINS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. officials will visit Portugal next week
to talk about giving the Portuguese surplus American military
equipment as a means of offsetting budget cuts in military aid, the
State Department says.
   Gen. Charles Brown, chief of the Defense Security Assistance
Agency, will head the delegation leaving next Monday for Portugal
to talk about what kind of military equipment the United States
could provide.
   The United States has suggested giving Portugal surplus
equipment to make up for budget cuts that have forced a reduction
in aid below levels promised under a 1983 agreement allowing the
U.S. military to use bases in Portugal.
   The announcement Thursday came a day after Portuguese Prime
Minister Anibal Cavaco Silva met with President Reagan to complain
about the lower aid levels and call for a formal review of the
bases agreement.
   ``Portugal wants the military bases to continue,'' Cavaco Silva
reiterated in a speech on Thursday to the National Press Club,
``and we don't want to reduce the American facilities in Portugal.''
   ``Our decision is a result of difference in interpretation of
our mutual agreement, and we don't want that this point of friction
will continue until 1991,'' he said. ``That is the end of this
agreement.''
   The agreement, an extension of an original pact stemming from
1951, ``is out of date,'' Cavaco Silva said.
   State Department spokeswoman Phyllis Oakley said U.S. officials
were pleased that Cavaco Silva didn't want a reduction in American
military presence in Portugal, unlike the insistence of neigboring
Spanish officials that the United States remove F-16s that had been
based in Spain.
</TEXT>
