<1ST_LINE>r w PM-FamilyIncome     02-26 0515</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Family Income,520</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Old People Better Off Than Young Families, Study Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JILL LAWRENCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Young families with children have suffered the
most dramatic income drop since 1970 of any family group in
America, while the elderly have seen the sharpest rise, according
to a new congressional analysis.
   The study of family income trends by the Congressional Budget
Office found that median income for families with children, in
which the head of household was under 25, plummeted 43 percent from
1970 to 1986.
   For those over 65, including people living alone, income went up
more than 50 percent.
   A Republican senator and a Democratic congressman independently
requested the non-partisan CBO to do a study of family income
trends, and each offered his own interpretation of the analysis
released Thursday.
   Sen. Pete Domenici, R-N.M., stressed the encouraging CBO finding
that overall, American family income has risen 20 percent since
1970. Rep. George Miller, D-Calif., pointed to the plight of
low-income families with children.
   Miller also cited CBO's finding that many families increased
their incomes over the 16-year period not through higher wages but
by adding another wage-earner to the workforce, and with that
wage-earner such added costs as child care and commuting.
   ``In many families, both parents must now work to maintain the
standard of living, which results in increased costs as well as
increased income,'' said Miller, chairman of the House Select
Committee on Children, Youth and Families.
   CBO said that the elderly as a group were least buffeted by the
swings of the economy, and that rises in their income were due
primarily to higher Social Security payments.
   Among the findings:
   _While family income for the elderly grew more than 50 percent,
it grew only 26 percent for married couples with children and only
2 percent for single mothers with children. For families head by
someone under 25, including those without children, income dropped
20 percent.
   _Income fell 13 percent for low-income single mothers with
children, with 20 percent of such families having less than half
the cash income needed to live at the poverty level in 1986.
   _Income rose 12 percent to 37 percent for all families with at
least one full-time, year-round worker. For families with children
and no such worker, it fell 10 percent.
   Domenici, senior Republican on the Senate Budget Committee and a
member of the National Economic Commission, said he was not
surprised by the negative trends among young and single-parent
families. He said any deficit-reduction recommendations would be
screened for their impact on those households.
   However, Domenici said CBO might have found more encouraging
trends among such families if it had taken into account such
non-cash programs as food stamps and the 1986 tax law that took
millions of low-income families off the tax rolls.
   CBO said a lack of family-level data prevented it from including
non-cash programs in its analysis. The agency gave similar reasons
for not taking into account pre-1981 tax hikes, which reduced
disposable income, and said it was impossible to project the net
effect of either omission.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880226-0043 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-26-88 0501EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Meese-Pipeline     02-26 0848</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Meese-Pipeline,850</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Meese's Lawyers Dispute Wallach Memos' Accuracy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETE YOST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lawyers for Attorney General Edwin Meese III
say he knew nothing about a plan to use Pentagon money to give
Israel payments to protect a $1 billion Iraqi pipeline project.
   The plan was being promoted by Meese's longtime friend, E.
Robert Wallach. Wallach's attorney, George G. Walker, confirmed the
contents of two messages in December 1985 sent by Wallach to Swiss
oilman Bruce Rappaport, a partner in the proposed Iraqi project.
One contains a reference to Meese.
   Wallach was Rappaport's attorney.
   The Washington Post, which on Thursday disclosed the existence
of the proposal to use Pentagon money, said the December 1985
messages plus another Wallach-to-Rappaport telex on Feb. 3, 1986
show that Meese supported the plan and that the late William Casey,
then CIA director, endorsed it.
   ABC News, quoting anonymous sources, reported that under the
plan Israel would have gotten $400 million in U.S. military aid
over four years. The money was to be set aside in a special bank
account as construction of the pipeline began, the network said.
   ``The attorney general was not involved in any plans to utilize
defense department funds for the project, gave no `assurances'
about any such plan, and arranged no meeting for that purpose,''
said a statement by Nathan Lewin, one of Meese's lawyers.
   ``The attorney general has no recollection of anything being
said to him about any such plan,'' Lewin added in an interview.
   Meese's involvement with the pipeline project is under criminal
investigation by independent counsel James McKay, who is trying to
determine whether the attorney general may have violated the
Foreign Corrupt Practices Act.
   That act makes it illegal for U.S. citizens, companies or their
agents to offer foreign officials ``anything of value'' to
influence them and makes the attorney general responsible for
filing civil suits to block such payments.
   Federal investigators also are looking at Wallach's failure to
register as a foreign agent, The Washington Times reported today.
The newspaper quoted Justice Department officials, who were not
identified, as saying the issue could raise conflict-of-interest
problems for Meese.
   It said that when Wallach went to work as a paid lobbyist for
Rappaport, he also was acting as an unpaid personal attorney to
Meese during his confirmation hearings as attorney general.
   A Dec. 16, 1985, message from Wallach to Rappaport says that ``I
have assurance from my friend that if necessary, he will engage new
person on project.'' Wallach usually called Meese ``my friend.''
   But Walker said that rather than being a reference to Meese, the
``he'' referred to in that portion of the telex is someone else,
probably National Security Staff aide David Wigg, who would explain
the pipeline project in general terms to the new national security
adviser, John Poindexter. Poindexter had taken over the post from
Robert McFarlane on Dec. 4, 1985.
   Walker said that in 1985, NSC aide Wigg came up with the idea of
using Pentagon money to make payments to Israel to ensure that the
Israelis would not attack the pipeline.
   Wallach sent a Dec. 12, 1985 telegram to Rappaport relating that
Wigg was attempting to determine whether or not Pentagon financing
for the payments could be provided.
   Wallach said ``the capital DOD (Department of Defense) package''
was to be submitted that day by Wigg to McFarlane, who was wrapping
up his government employment.
   On Dec. 16, Wallach reported in a message to Rappaport that at a
meeting that day with Casey, who was a friend of Rappaport's, Wigg
and Wallach reviewed documents relating to the Pentagon budget plan.
   Wallach said that Casey ``approved the concept with expression
as to it being unique in his experience.'' Walker said the language
stops short of saying Casey endorses the plan, and is simply
expressing a view about the unique nature of the payment plan.
   In a Feb. 3, 1986 message obtained by the Post, Wallach tells
Rappaport Meese will contact Poindexter to arrange a meeting for
Wallach, ``if it is necessary to obtain signature of his
(Poindexter's) superior.''
   Lewin said Meese has no recollection of arranging a meeting for
Wallach with Poindexter nor does he recall being asked to do so.
Walker said he didn't have a copy of the Feb. 3 message and that
Wallach didn't remember sending one.
   Lewin's statement said Meese ``stands by'' a statement he made
Feb. 1 that ``the sum and substance'' of his involvement with the
Iraqi pipeline project consisted of referring Wallach to McFarlane
in May 1985, referring then-Israeli Prime Minister Shimon Peres to
McFarlane in October 1985 and discussing the pipeline briefly with
Peres.
   The only other involvement, Meese said, was having the Justice
Department Office of Legal Counsel consider a request in October
1985 on the legality of using U.S. aid money to Israel to help
protect the pipeline from Israeli attack.
   A Sept. 25, 1985 memo from Wallach to Meese says that a portion
of up to $700 million that would go to Israel from the pipeline
would be funneled to the Israeli Labor Party.
</TEXT>
