<1ST_LINE>r p PM-SC-GOPPoll     02-26 0401</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-SC-GOP Poll,370</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Leads in Newspaper Poll of South Carolina Voters</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHARLOTTE, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President George Bush holds a strong
lead over his GOP rivals among likely South Carolina voters, a poll
published by The Charlotte Observer indicated today.
   Coming three days before March 8, Super Tuesday, when 20 states
hold primaries and caucuses, the South Carolina primary has assumed
strategic importance in the GOP sweepstakes, despite its prize of
only 37 delegates.
   The poll indicated Bush had the support of 41 percent of those
who said they're likely to vote in the South Carolina GOP primary.
Trailing were Sen. Bob Dole with 29 percent, former television
evangelist Pat Robertson, 13 percent, and Rep. Jack Kemp of New
York, 4 percent. Twelve percent were undecided.
   The poll also indicated Bush had the support of most of the
younger voters: 61 percent of those 18-24 backed the vice
president, as did 45 percent of those from 25-34. But so did 45
percent of those over 65.
   However, 45 percent of the likely voters _ and 47 percent of
Republicans _ said they see little difference between Bush and Dole.
   The telephone poll, conducted by the market research division of
the newspaper, surveyed 687 registered voters who indicated they're
likely to participate in the primary. The margin of error was 3.7
percentage points.
   Meanwhile, a third of those polled said the controversy
surrounding television evengelist Jimmy Swaggart has hurt Robertson.
   And Robertson, who is counting on support from Democrats
eligible to vote in the state's ``open'' GOP primary, was trailing
Dole and Bush among Democratic voters.
   Half the voters said they would feel uncomfortable with a
television evangelist as president. And nearly a third said
Robertson would be hurt by the Swaggart affair. But 56 said they
didn't believe it would affect Robertson.
   One of the country's most popular TV evangelists, Swaggart
stepped down this week after allegations that he had been with a
New Orleans prostitute.
   This week, Robertson lashed out at Bush, suggesting that the
vice president's campaign had something to do with the timing of
the Swaggart revelations _ an implication Bush called absurd.
   At the same time, Dole was winning the endorsement of _ and
stumping the state with _ the state's most revered Republican, Sen.
Strom Thurmond.
   After indications that Dole would downplay the state, Bush
supporters say Thurmond's backing has raised his stakes.
</TEXT>
