<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Teen-AgeBusDrivers     02-26 0594</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Teen-Age Bus Drivers,590</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Ending Exemption Allowing 17-Year-Olds To Drive School
Buses</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROLYN SKORNECK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some 4,700 teen-agers will be ousted from the
drivers' seats of school buses in North Carolina and South Carolina
under a ruling issued by the Labor Department.
   The department, in an effort to crack down on enforcement of
child labor laws, announced Thursday that 17-year-olds must stop
driving school buses in those states after April 1, said department
spokesman Bob Zachariasiewicz.
   For the past two decades, the department had granted both states
annual exemptions from the child labor laws that enabled them to
hire the youths.
   The decision to end the exemptions reflected a failure of the
states to comply with more stringent conditions imposed in December
on the employment of 17-year-olds, the department said in a
statement.
   In January, a 4-year-old West Columbia, S.C., boy was run over
and killed by a 17-year-old bus driver who had a previous speeding
ticket. No charges were filed against the driver due to confusion
over whether he could have seen the child.
   Deputy Secretary of Labor Dennis Whitfield informed the two
states' governors of the decision Thursday.
   Officials from the two states expressed dismay at the ruling.
   ``If this in fact comes to pass, it would cause North Carolina
some very big problems, and we hope the Department of Labor will
send us some bus drivers to go with their order,'' said Jim
Sughrue, a spokesman for Gov. Jim Martin.
   South Carolina Gov. Carroll Campbell said he ``deeply regret(s)
the Department of Labor has seen fit to withdraw South Carolina's
exemption of 17-year-old bus drivers prior to the end of the school
year.
   ``But the department's findings that certain school districts
were ignoring its guidelines did not help South Carolina's position
in this matter,'' the governor added.
   South Carolina has 6,000 school bus drivers, of whom 1,200 are
17 years old, said Charlie Williams, the South Carolina
superintendent of education. A total of 1,000 young drivers had
been fired by December because of bad driving records.
   North Carolina has 13,000 drivers, of whom 3,500 are 17,
Zachariasiewicz said. In the 1986-87 school year, there were 14,350
drivers, of whom 5,000 were 16 and 17 years old.
   The department banned school bus driving by 16-year-olds in
December, he said.
   Employment of any drivers under 18 after April 1 would result in
assessment of monetary penalties and possible court action, the
department said.
   When the states applied for exemptions for the 1987-88 school
year, they were instead given extensions until Dec. 31, 1987, while
they supplied additional data, Zachariasiewicz said.
   In December, the department extended the exemptions through the
1987-88 school year, but three conditions were imposed for the use
of 17-year-old drivers: They had to have been trained and started
driving school buses on or before Aug. 31, 1987; they could not
have received a ticket for a moving violation or been involved in
an accident for which they were responsible _ in a car or a bus _
during the 1986-87 school year; and they had to be students or high
school graduates.
   Investigations by the department of how the states followed
these criteria ``revealed widespread non-compliance, particularly
employment of 17-year-olds with moving violations on their driving
records as student school bus drivers,'' the department statement
said.
   ``In South Carolina, in 14 of 15 school districts investigated,
the department found approximately 200 instances of
non-compliance,'' the statement said.
   North Carolina had received exemptions since 1967 while South
Carolina had received them since 1968.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
