<HEAD>Stocks Up; Dollar Declines</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 1 graf to CORRECT that dollar unchanged from
opening, sted unchanged for the week. Pickup 2nd graf pvs ``The
dollar's...''</NOTE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices closed higher on the Tokyo Stock
Exchange Friday, with the market's key index posting its 12th
consecutive gain, while the U.S. dollar ended the week at 128.35
yen, unchanged from its opening.
   The dollar's close was 0.45 yen lower than Thursday's closing
level of 128.80 yen.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues ended the day at
25,165.18, up 64.52 points or 0.25 percent.
   Currency traders attributed the dollar's opening weakness to
disappointment that the revised U.S. fourth-quarter gross national
product statistics released Thursday didn't exceed 5 percent, as
some had hoped. The Commerce Department said the revised growth
rate was 4.5 percent.
   At a press conference Friday in Tokyo, Finance Minister Kiichi
Miyazawa said intervention by central banks was not necessary at
this time since yen-dollar exchange rates were stable. His remarks
appeared to have little influence in the currency market.
