<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Markets,0177</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Stocks Up, Dollar Declines</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Tokyo Stock Exchange's key index rose today for
the 12th consecutive trading day, while the dollar declined against
the yen to end the week at 128.35 yen.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues rose 64.52
points, or 0.25 percent, in active trading to finish the day at
25,165.18.
   ``The investment environment is better now than before because
of declining interest rates and the relatively stable market in New
York,'' said a senior researcher at Nomura Securities, Japan's
largest brokerage, who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   Analysts also said many Japanese companies were revising their
forecasts for March because of better business performance.
   On the foreign exchange market, the dollar closed at 128.35 yen,
unchanged from its opening level but down from its 128.80-yen
closing Thursday. Spot turnover totaled $4.5 billion.
   Finance Minister Kiichi Miyazawa told a news conference today
that intervention by central banks was not necessary at the present
time because of stable yen-dollar exchange rates.
