<DOCNO> AP880226-0048 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-26-88 0503EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Reagan-Moscow     02-26 0407</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Reagan-Moscow,340</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan's Trip To Moscow To Mirror Gorbachev's Washington Visit</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERENCE HUNT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP White House Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Reagan administration is welcoming reports
from Moscow that a strategic arms agreement could be ready for
signing at a May summit, but says it is doubtful such a timetable
could be met.
   ``We welcome it, if it means the Soviets are going to work at
the negotiations just as hard as we will,'' an administration
official said Thursday, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   And Reagan, in an interview Thursday with The Washington Post,
expressed hope it could be signed by the end of the year although
``the time is too limited'' to complete work on the treaty by the
summit.
   A senior Soviet official in Moscow also said Thursday he
expected a treaty to reduce the superpowers' long-range nuclear
weapons stockpile would be ready for signing at the summit meeting,
the Post said.
   The official, who was not identified, talked to about 20 foreign
reporters at a two-hour meeting. The Post was uninvited but said it
obtained its account from other reporters.
   The official also said that Reagan will stay in the Kremlin
during the visit, which should last for about a week and could
include other cities besides Moscow, according to the account in
today's Post.
   The administration is known to completely discount the
speculation that Reagan would stay in the Kremlin.
   According to administration officials, Reagan's expected trip to
Moscow is likely to mirror in length and style the four-day visit
to Washington last December by Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev.
   The officials said Thursday that no dates have been fixed for
the president's trip, but that tentative plans continue to be that
it will fall sometime from mid- to late-May to early June.
   White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater told reporters this week
he did not expect a summit date to be set until Soviet Foreign
Minister Eduard Shevardnadze meets in Washington late next month
with Secretary of State George Shultz, who just returned from
Moscow.
   Gorbachev's visit was confined to Washington. In a strict
observance of the rule of reciprocity, Reagan is expected to remain
in Moscow.
   The New York Times, in an account of the briefing published in
today's editions, said the official indicated the Soviet Union
might drop a key objection to the U.S. development of a space-based
missile defense system by permitting the testing of components in
space.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880226-0049 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-26-88 0455EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-AIDSAntibody     02-26 0480</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-AIDS Antibody,470</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Team Develops Synthetic Peptide That Triggers AIDS Antibodies</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-AIDS Treatments Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The discovery of a synthetic peptide that
triggers antibodies to neutralize the AIDS virus in rabbits may
eventually help in combating the fatal disease in humans, a Chicago
researcher says.
   Mark Gurney, an assistant professor at the University of
Chicago, said Thursday that the peptides he synthesized imitate
part of the HIV virus. The HIV is the virus that causes AIDS, or
acquired immune deficiency syndrome.
   ``The potential is that you could use a peptide to elicit ...
the same type of antibodies in man and these would then attack the
virus,'' Gurney said.
   Peptides are compounds of amino acids, and the ones that Gurney
made were identical in some ways to a portion of the envelope that
surrounds the human immune virus.
   In the experiments, researchers put the peptides into laboratory
rabbits. The immune system of the rabbits produced three antibodies
against the peptides.
   Researchers then exposed these antibodies to several strains of
the HIV virus in test tubes, and Gurney said the HIV virus was
neutralized, or prevented from spreading to other cells.
   The experiment used a peptide that was a chemical mimic of a
portion of the HIV envelope that remains unchanged, Gurney said.
Other parts of the virus change frequently.
   This unchanging portion of the HIV virus does not elicit an
antibody response when it is attached to the whole virus for
reasons that scientists do not understand, said Gurney.
   He said peptide-antibody response is not well understood now and
that experiments in the past have shown that synthetic peptides can
trigger undesirable antibodies, only a small number of which will
attack the target.
   Until this process is further refined, he said, peptides will
not be useful against AIDS.
   He said the researchers also are unable to determine precisely
how the antibodies created by using the peptide are able to
neutralize AIDS in the test tube.
   Gurney worked on the experiment with David D. Ho of the
Cedars-Sinai Medical Center in Los Angeles, Joan C. Kaplan of
Massachusetts General Hospital in Boston, and Indre E. Rackauskas
of the University of Chicago.
   A report on the research appears today in Science, the journal
of the American Association for the Advancement of Science.
   AIDS kills by destroying a key part of the human immune system,
leaving the body open to infections. AIDS is spread principally
through sexual contact, but also by the shared needles of drug
abusers and the use of contaminated blood products in transfusions.
Infected mothers may also pass the AIDS virus to their babies while
giving birth.
   As of Feb. 15, AIDS had been diagnosed in 53,814 Americans, of
whom more than half, or 30,158, have died since 1981, according to
the federal Centers for Disease Control. No one is known to have
recovered from AIDS.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
