<1ST_LINE>r a PM-SpringsteenTour     02-26 0473</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Springsteen Tour,0486</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Packed House Cheers Rock Star; Police Report Crowd Orderly</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto BX2</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WORCESTER, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rock superstar Bruce Springsteen walked
onstage, threw a bouquet of roses into the crowd, stepped up to a
microphone and yelled, ``Ready for a date?''
   Nearly 13,000 people, most standing as they would throughout the
concert, roared back that they were.
   Springsteen and his 12-piece E Street Band then went to work,
and the Boss' nationwide ``Tunnel of Love'' tour _ his first in
nearly 2{ years _ got under way Thursday night at the Worcester
Centrum.
   ``I'm excited,'' said Cynthia Swienton of Simsbury, Conn.,
standing up in her seat 12 rows from the back of the auditorium.
She and her companion, John Smedick of Torrington, Conn., paid $300
for their two tickets.
   Although the concert was sold out, hundreds of people milled
around outside before the show began, hoping to buy tickets.
   According to the Worcester Telegram newspaper, ticket scalpers'
prices were generally between $150 to $225 a ticket, but one
unidentified person said he was offered a ticket for $750. Tickets
were $20 each when first went on sale.
   Ticket scalping is illegal in Massachusetts.
   The crowd was generally orderly outside the Centrum, said police
Lt. Paul F. Campbell. He said there were a few arrests for unarmed
robbery of concert tickets and one man was charged with being a
disorderly person after he allegedly spit in the face of a
television camerman.
   Police Sgt. John R. Harrington also said two men, one wielding a
crowbar, were arrested for robbing four teen-agers of their tickets
before the show began.
   Several celebrities were among the 12,800 people attending the
show, including basketball star Kevin McHale of the Boston Celtics
and Miami Steve Van Zandt, Springsteen's lead guitar player until
1981.
   ``A lot of the guys (Celtics) like Springsteen,'' McHale said,
taking time to sign autographs while sitting in a middle section of
the auditorium. ``The '84 tour, they seemed to be touring a lot of
cities that we were playing in. We'd play on one night, they'd come
to our game; we'd go to the concert next night. It worked real
nice.''
   Dressed in tight black jeans, black boots, vest and a white
shirt buttoned to the neck, Springsteen later took off the shirt to
reveal a black T-shirt, and his hair was lathered with sweat 3
hours and 25 minutes later.
   ``Do you want me to get a heart attack? On the first night?'' he
asked the crowd before he and the band did a 15-minute encore of
such rock favorites as ``Devil with a Blue Dress on,'' ``Good Golly
Miss Molly'' and ``CC Rider.''
   He opened the show with ``Tunnel of Love.''
   Springsteen, 38, will perform again Sunday and Monday in
Worcester before the tour moves on to Chapel Hill, N.C.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
