<1ST_LINE>r p PM-PoliticalBriefs     02-26 0898</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Political Briefs,880</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Traficant Petitions Ruled Invalid in Two Ohio Districts</HEAD>
<DATELINE>YOUNGSTOWN, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Rep. James A. Traficant Jr., whose
avowed campaign for the Democratic presidential nomination has yet
to take shape, has failed to make the ballot in two more Ohio
congressional districts.
   The problems disclosed Thursday brought to four the number of
Ohio districts in which Traficant's name will not be on the ballot.
Ohio has 21 congressional districts.
   In the sprawling 6th District of Southern Ohio, Traficant needed
150 signatures, and 159 were submitted. Every signature was ruled
invalid, said Nancy Stapleton, director of the Warren County Board
of Elections.
   Elections officials in the 2nd District in suburban Cincinnati
said Thursday that Traficant did not meet petition requirements
there, either. Traficant already was off the ballot in two other
districts.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Democrats File For New York Primary</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Supporters of Massachusetts Gov. Michael
Dukakis filed petitions containing more than four times the number
of signatures needed to get on the April 19 New York presidential
primary ballot.
   Thursday was deadline day for the Democratic candidates at the
state Board of Elections and, in addition to Dukakis, supporters of
Tennessee Sen. Albert Gore Jr. and Illinois Sen. Paul Simon also
filed petitions to get their candidates spots on New York's
statewide ballot.
   Supporters of Jesse Jackson and Missouri Rep. Richard Gephardt
had filed earlier in the week.
   The only one of the six major Democratic candidates not to make
the board's 5 p.m. deadline for in-person filing, was former
Colorado Sen. Gary Hart. New York campaign aides were shooting for
the midnight Thursday deadline for getting a postmark on their
petitions.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Education Secretary Objects To Columnist's Request To Rate Bush</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Education Secretary William J. Bennett
responded with a stern ``no'' to a columnist's request that Cabinet
officers rate Vice President George Bush as to his presidential
timber.
   Bennett took umbrage at a request from Dale Van Atta, co-author
of the Jack Anderson column, who sought the impressions of all 34
present and former Reagan Cabinet members who have served with Bush.
   Calling Bush ``a mystery to the voters,'' the columnist asked
for instances where Bush influenced policy decisions or actions,
and warned that a failure to reply ``may send a negative message
about Mr. Bush.''
   Bennett's wrote back that it was ``nonsense'' to call Bush a
mystery to the voters. He also said he would not violate the
confidentiality of Cabinet discussions, or ``the president's
injunction to all his Cabinet members to stay neutral in the
presidential race.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Poll Indicates Tight Democratic Race In Texas</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Democratic presidential race in Texas is a
tight contest, while the Republican field still is dominated by
Vice President George Bush, according to a new poll.
   The poll, conducted for the Dallas Morning News and the Houston
Chronicle and published Thursday, showed Jesse Jackson with 19
percent, Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis with 18 percent, Rep.
Richard Gephardt with 15 percent and Sen. Albert Gore Jr. with 12
percent of the vote in the Texas Democratic primary. Gary Hart had
6 percent and Paul Simon had 5 percent, while 24 percent were
unsure.
   Bush had 60 percent of the support in the Texas GOP primary,
according to the poll. His closest competitor was Sen. Bob Dole,
with 15 percent.
   The poll, conducted by the University of Houston's Center for
Public Policy, had a margin of error 6 percentage points. It
surveyed 294 likely GOP voters and 301 likely Democratic voters.
