<HEAD>Oklahoma Senate Leader Doubts Duke Will Get To Address Senate</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OKLAHOMA CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Ku Klux Klan leader David Duke, a
Democratic presidential candidate, wants to speak to the Oklahoma
Senate but Senate President Pro Tempore Bob Cullison doubts Duke
will get the chance.
   Democrat Cullison said a man identifying himself as a
representative of Duke, one of 12 Democrats on the Oklahoma primary
ballot, came to his office this week and asked if the candidate
could address the Senate next week.
   The Senate leader said he told the man Duke could talk if he
could get a Senate sponsor and there were no objections.
   Cullison said Senate rules require unanimous consent requests
before a non-senator can address the legislative body. He said such
requests are routinely approved, but he did not think that would be
the case for Duke.
