<HEAD>Dukakis, Gephardt, Jackson Ahead of Gore In Florida</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Dukakis, Richard Gephardt and
Jesse Jackson had substantial leads over Albert Gore in Florida,
according to a Mason-Dixon Opinion Research poll conducted for
Florida news organizations.
   The poll released Thursday showed that 23 percent of the
Democrats questioned were undecided. Dukakis had 23 percent,
Gephardt 18 percent, Jackson 17 percent and Gore trailed at 10
percent. Gary Hart was back at 6 percent, and Paul Simon had 3
percent.
   On the Republican side, George Bush had a huge lead over his
challengers in Florida at 47 percent. Bob Dole had 20 percent,
while Pat Robertson had 10 percent. Jack Kemp was at the back with
3 percent, and 20 percent of Florida Republicans questioned were
undecided.
   The poll was based on random telephone surveys Feb. 19-21 of 843
likely Florida voters. The poll was considered accurate within plus
or minus 4.4 percentage points for Democrats and 5.4 percentage
points for Republicans.
