<1ST_LINE>r i PM-HongKong-Earthquake     02-26 0153</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Hong Kong-Earthquake,0157</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Strong Earthquake Recorded In Southern Indian Ocean</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A strong earthquake was recorded in the
southern Indian Ocean today but there were no reports of damage,
the Hong Kong Royal Observatory said.
   The quake was recorded at 2:30 p.m. and registered a preliminary
reading of 6.9 on the Richter scale, the observatory said.
   The epicenter was about 1,110 miles east-southeast of the South
African port city of Durban, it said. The observatory said it had
received no reports of tsunamis, or huge waves generated by
earthquakes at sea.
   The Richter scale is a gauge of the energy released by an
earthquake, as measured by the ground motion recorded on a
seismograph. Every increase of one number means that the ground
motion is 10 times greater.
   An earthquake registering 7 is capable of widespread, heavy
damage in populated areas, but today's quake was centered far from
land.
</TEXT>
