<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Elderly-Shooting     02-26 0268</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Elderly-Shooting,0276</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Suspect Described As Congenial Retiree</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SCOTT ROTHSCHILD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ARLINGTON, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 79-year-old who burst into a board
meeting at the retirement home that evicted him and gunned down
four former neighbors was in custody today, booked for
investigation of attempted murder.
   ``Apparently, they had a board meeting and one former resident,
who was apparently disgruntled, walked into the board room and
started shooting'' at the 15 or 16 people gathered there, said
police spokesman Dee Anderson.
   Gunfire from a .22-caliber semiautomatic rifle wounded four
people and a fifth person suffered a heart attack in the 11 a.m.
attack Thursday at the Masonic Home for the Aged, authorities said.
   The wounded, treated for minor gunshot wounds, were listed in
fair condition today at Arlington Hospital, but the heart attack
victim was in critical condition, a hospital spokesman said.
   The suspect, whose name was not released, had lived at the
Masonic Home for three years, but was evicted in September 1987 for
breaking rules, officials said.
   The man burst into the monthly board meeting with two rifles,
one slung around his neck with twine, and opened fire. He fled to a
nearby kitchen and surrendered peacefully to police, who booked him
on investigative charges of attempted murder.
   At the Arlington Villa retirement home, where the suspect has
lived since Dec. 1, officials expressed shock.
   ``He is a good resident, very congenial and sociable,'' said
administrator Gennie Pace.
   Masonic home employees shut out all visitors and referred all
questions to board chairman Sam Hilburn, but refused to say where
he could be contacted.
</TEXT>
