<1ST_LINE>r a PM-HouseholdHead     02-26 0295</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Household Head,0306</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Husband No Longer Be Legal Head Of Household Under Oklahoma Bill</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BILL JOHNSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OKLAHOMA CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 98-year-old Oklahoma law stating that a
husband is head of the household and his wife must live where he
does is headed toward repeal in the state Legislature, but not
without debate.
   The bill to change the 1890 law was approved by the House 67-26
Thursday and moves to the Senate.
   ``I want to bring Oklahoma from the 19th century into the 20th
century before the 21st century gets here,'' said the bill's
sponsor, Rep. Freddie Williams.
   If the law were enforced, Mrs. Williams said, an appeals court
judge would have to step down from the bench because she lives on
one side of the state and and her husband lives on the other.
   Even so, opponents of repeal heatedly argued that the law is
based on biblical teachings about the family.
   ``I think there should be a difference between a man and a
woman, and when we get to where there's not a difference in it,
we're going to have all kinds of problems, whether it's war or what
it is,'' said Rep. Bill Smith.
   Rep. Leonard Sullivan contended he had ``never heard any lady''
call for repeal of the law.
   ``If it's not broke, don't fix it,'' Sullivan said. And ``if
it's not being enforced, why worry?''
   Rep. Ken Harris, a supporter of the bill, said, ``Even having to
argue about this bill is a sad, sad commentary.''
   Mrs. Williams and Harris pointed out that the law had been
declared unconstitutional by a former attorney general.
   Rep. John Monks said the attorney general who made the ruling
never married and ``never had the responsibility for a family.''
</TEXT>
