<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Dollar-Gold     02-26 0344</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dollar-Gold,0363</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Lower In Moderate Trade, Gold Mixed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar fell in moderate European trading this
morning on indications the U.S. economy is expanding slower than
the market expected, dealers said.
   Gold prices were mixed in quiet trading.
   Dealers said economic data released in the past few days showed
the American economy slightly less robust than expected, weakening
the dollar.
   ``The data has made dealers a little more selling oriented,''
said one trader with a U.S. commercial bank in Milan.
   Dealers noted the dollar had been moving higher since
mid-February, after the report that the U.S. trade deficit narrowed
in December for the second consecutive month.
   But recent economic data disappointed the market, especially
Thursday's report that the U.S. gross national product grew by 4.5
percent in the fourth quarter, lower than market expectations of a
5 percent rise, dealers said.
   As a result, traders said, the market feared the U.S. trade gap
might not be shrinking quickly enough, eroding sentiment for the
dollar.
   In Tokyo, where the business day ends as Europe's begins, the
dollar closed at 128.35 yen, down from 128.80 yen on Thursday.
Later, in London, it was quoted at 128.45 yen.
   Other dollar rates at midmorning, compared with late Thursday's
rates:
   _ 1.6895 West German marks, down from 1.6945
   _ 1.3895 Swiss francs, down from 1.3935
   _ 5.7165 French francs, down from 5.7315
   _ 1.89595 Dutch guilders, down from 1.9020
   _ 1,244.00 Italian lire, down from 1,248.25
   _ 1.2649 Canadian dollars, down from 1.2650
   In London, the British pound rose to $1.7715 from $1.7665 late
Thursday.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $434.20 a troy ounce. At
midmorning the city's five major bullion dealers fixed a
recommended price of $$432.65. Both were up from late Thursday's
428.00.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $432.60, down from $433.00 late
Thursday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold rose 88 cents to close at a bid
437.23.
   Silver was quoted in London today at a bid price of $6.21 a troy
ounce, up from Thursday's 6.15.
</TEXT>
