<1ST_LINE>r a PM-SchoolArson     02-26 0378</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-School Arson,0387</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Firefighter Confesses to Arson in School He Once Attended</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN K. WILEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OKANOGAN, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former firefighter who helped
authorities battle a $6.5 million series of fires in two churches
and the elementary school he once attended has confessed to setting
the blazes, authorities said.
   Okanogan County Prosecutor Jack Burchard planned to file six
counts of first-degree arson today against Adrian J. Howe, 23, who
was ordered held on $250,000 bail. Each count carries a maximum
sentence of life in prison and a $50,000 fine.
   The fires, which did an estimated $6.5 million damage, began in
December when Omak North Elementary School was hit twice within
eight days. Two Omak churches and a church house also were burned
in one week earlier this month.
   Burchard and Sheriff Jim Weed said there was no apparent motive
for the fires. Investigators have no reason to believe Howe, a high
school dropout, had any animosity toward his elementary school,
Burchard said.
   Howe reported the first blaze Dec. 6 at the elementary school,
helped set up barricades at a Dec. 14 fire, and was seen by police
at three other blazes, Burchard told Superior Court Judge James R.
Thomas.
   Howe lived in a trailer court across the street from the school
in December, then moved to an apartment across from one of the
churches before the February fires, Burchard said.
   He was arrested by investigators of a special 12-member arson
task force Wednesday and confessed to all six fires, Burchard told
Thomas.
   A lifelong resident of Omak in central Washington, Howe was
employed at a lumber mill on the Colville Indian Reservation and
fought range fires for the Bureau of Indian Affairs in past summers.
   Friends who knew Howe from several bars he frequented described
him as a loner who used to get into fights. But they said they
didn't believe Howe was responsible for the fires.
   ``I don't think that he had anything to do with it,'' said Brian
Marbach, a friend for 19 years. ``He'd be the last person I'd ever
think would do something like that.''
   Howe recently had been trying to reconcile with a girlfriend by
whom he had a daughter, about 2 years old, Marbach said.
</TEXT>
