02-26 0638</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Mecham's Prosecutors, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0471,0652</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mecham's Prosecutors Paired By Political Parties</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: CORRECTS date of criminal trial from May 22 to March 22 in
8th graf, `Mecham also ....'</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto PN4</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURIE ASSEO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Evan Mecham's impeachment
prosecutors, brought together in a shotgun marriage of Republican
and Democratic politics, say they are working well together on the
case to remove the governor from office.
   Attorney William French said he didn't expect to be teamed with
another lawyer, particularly one he'd never worked with, when House
Speaker Joe Lane, a Republican, hired him in October to look into
allegations against Mecham, also a Republican.
   French, 56, was joined by co-counsel Paul Eckstein, 47, after
House Minority Leader Art Hamilton insisted that French could not
be expected to represent Democratic interests because he was hired
by the Republicans.
   French, a former U.S. Justice Department attorney and Maricopa
County Superior Court judge, has also been accused of bias because
he is a registered Democrat who signed a Mecham recall petition. He
maintains he is largely apolitical.
   Eckstein is managing partner of a law firm that represents
Arizona's First Amendment Coalition, a journalism rights advocacy
organization. Until recently he chaired Democrat Carolyn Warner's
campaign against Mecham in the May 17 recall election.
   The two men, who took the Arizona bar exam at the same time in
1965, say they will draw on each other's strengths and rely on
methodical hard work to prepare for Arizona's first gubernatorial
impeachment trial Monday.
   Mecham was accused by the House of concealing a $350,000
campaign loan, misusing $80,000 from the governor's protocol fund
by lending it to his auto dealership, and trying to thwart an
investigation of an alleged death threat by a state official.
   Mecham also faces a March 22 criminal trial on charges of hiding
the $350,000 loan. He has denied any wrongdoing.
   French said he and Eckstein have had no major conflicts.
   ``I think we sort of sized each other up to see if we were going
to play it straight,'' French said. ``And within a matter of hours
I was satisfied that the politics had been left outside of the
door.''
   Their courtroom manner _ French, precise of speech both in word
selection and in timing for dramatic impact, and Eckstein typically
dry as he worked in French's shadow _ has contrasted sharply with
the combative, theatrical style often shown by Mecham attorney
Murray Miller.
   But Lane noted, ``we have not seen them under any stress
situations. It's going to be interesting when it gets really hot''
during the Senate trial.
   Both lawyers say they are ready to start the trial and figure
they're as well-equipped to handle it as anyone would be. ``There
aren't any `impeachment lawyers' around,'' Eckstein said.
   He said he probably will defer to French on some matters because
his elder partner was on the case first.
   French ``does bring the experience of a judge,'' but has a
relative lack of experience in politics and dealing with the media,
Eckstein said.
   Despite the political nature of the trial, Eckstein added,
``it's just practicing the law in a careful, workmanlike way.''
   ``We're trying to try it as if you would try it in the
courthouse,'' French said. He said the lawyers have had no contact
with the 30 senators, who essentially are serving as judges and
jurors in the case.
   French has been receiving state police protection since his law
office was damaged in an arson fire a week before he made the
report that led to Mecham's impeachment.
   Mecham was impeached Feb. 5 on a 46-16 House vote, forcing him
to temporarily hand over power to Secretary of State Rose Mofford,
a Democrat. A two-thirds vote of the 30-member Senate is required
to remove him from office permanently.
</TEXT>
