<1ST_LINE>r a PM-ReattachedHand     02-26 0460</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Reattached Hand,0475</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Long Wait Ahead Before Man Knows Whether Reattached Hand
Functional</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HOYT HARWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BIRMINGHAM, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A construction worker who underwent a
rare procedure in which his severed hand was attached to his
abdomen until doctors could sew it back on his arm says the
technique might help other people even if it doesn't work for him.
   After Mike Thomas' left hand was ripped off when he grabbed a
cable in a 70-foot fall from a girder last November, doctors used a
vein from his leg to attach the hand to an artery in his abdomen to
try to keep the tissue alive.
   Two weeks ago, they put the hand back on his arm.
   ``If it doesn't work, at least they know they can put a hand on
an abdomen and maybe use the procedure'' to help someone else,
Thomas, 31, said Thursday before leaving University Hospital for
his home in Cleveland, Ala.
   The procedure has been done twice before in Yugoslavia, once
successfully. Hospital spokesman Hank Black said doctors at the
hospital knew of no other such procedure in this country.
   Thomas' doctors said it will be months before he knows whether
he has any feeling in the hand, but the worker said that was not
what mattered.
   ``The hand was a minor detail when I first fell because I was
worried about living,'' said Thomas, who suffered internal injuries
in the fall.
   ``I have no feeling in the hand now, but the blood supply is
fine,'' he said. ``It will be six months to a year before I know
whether I have any feeling.''
   Thomas said he became accustomed to the hand not being there
``and now I've got to get used to it being back.''
   In reattaching the hand, the doctors connected two nerves, with
another operation needed to restore a third nerve.
   One of the physicians, Paul Sauer, said a therapist will work on
the hand twice a week for a few months.
   ``I have to keep the hand exercised,'' Thomas said, ``and
protect my arm like it was a child.'' His bandaged hand is in a
sling.
   He said one of his first priorities was to get some barbecue.
Later, he said, he wants his doctors to visit Blount County so he
can ``introduce them to farm life and take them bass fishing.''
   Another doctor, Michael Chernofsky, said that Thomas and his
wife, Loretta, had maintained a positive attitude and a sense of
humor.
   ``He is very lucky to be alive,'' Chernofsky said. ``The hand is
icing on the cake. He has done extremely well, and we're hopeful
things will continue in that trend.
   ``We have great hopes for Mr. Thomas. He promised to take us
fishing.''
</TEXT>
