<1ST_LINE>r a PM-PayolaIndictment     02-26 0324</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Payola Indictment,0333</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cash and Cocaine Buy Air Time For Record Promoter, Indictment Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A music promoter allegedly bribed radio
station employees with cash and cocaine to get his records on the
air, according to a federal payola indictment, lawyers said.
   Federal agents arrested Ralph Tashjian, 39, of San Mateo and his
wife, Valerie, in front of their children at their home Thursday,
said Anthony Brooklier, the promoter's Los Angeles attorney.
   Tashjian allegedly paid nearly $42,000 in cash and gave
undisclosed quantities of cocaine to three radio station workers
from 1980 to 1985 in exchange for air time for his records,
Brooklier said. The stations were in Fresno and El Paso, Texas.
   The indictment handed up by a Los Angeles federal grand jury
Thursday was announced by Brooklier and David Kenner, the
Tashjians' attorneys, who said their clients are innocent.
   ``We absolutely deny any wrongdoing on the Tashjians' part,''
Brooklier said. ``They were arrested at their home, in front of
their children, even though we had offered to surrender them (to
authorities).''
   The indictment charges Tashjian with three counts of payola, one
count of conspiracy to distribute cocaine, one count of obstruction
of justice and three counts of corporate income-tax fraud,
Brooklier said.
   Mrs. Tashjian was arrested for alleged corporate tax evasion.
They both face arraignment today in San Francisco, Brooklier said.
   Federal prosecutors at the Justice Department's Organized Crime
Strike Force in Los Angeles, which is handling the case, withheld
announcement of the indictment.
   Tashjian is an associate of Joseph Isgro, a Los Angeles-based
record promoter who has been investigated by the grand jury but
wasn't named in the indictment.
   Tashjian worked out of Isgro's Los Angeles office, but for his
own company, Ralph Tashjian Enterprises Inc.
   The payola investigation began in 1986, with reputed organized
crime figure Salvatore James Pisello, 64, of West Hollywood,
charged in July with three counts of tax evasion. His case is
pending.
</TEXT>
