<1ST_LINE>r a PM-CampusProtest 1stLd-Writethru a0559 02-26 0518</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Campus Protest, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0559,0526</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Protesters Occupy University of Dayton President's Office</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS grafs 3-4 pvs with 3 grafs to UPDATE with new estimate
of number of protesters this morning, students outside holding
picket signs, transition. SUBS 13th graf pvs, `Those who...' to
include first name for Ms. Rizvi, whose first reference deleted
higher up.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DOUG FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DAYTON, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Demonstrators continued to occupy the
University of Dayton president's office early today, demanding an
end to Central Intelligence Agency recruiting on campus.
   Brother Raymond L. Fitz, president of the Roman Catholic school,
met with members of the Democratic Socialists of America and
Plowshares for Peace in the office for about 90 minutes during the
night to hear their demands.
   About 50 members of the groups took over the office shortly
after 10 a.m. Thursday, but the number had dwindled to 30 by this
morning, university spokeswoman Valerie Galloway Elijah said.
   She said another eight students were outside holding up signs
and a few were standing at the end of a stairwell and blocked by
university officials from joining the demonstrators.
   Jon Wentz, co-chairman of the Democratic Socialists of America,
described Thursday night's meeting as ``very positive. Brother Fitz
was very cooperative with us.''
   He said they talked about establishing a forum on the CIA and
that the students demanded a one-year moratorium on any CIA
recruitment.
   ``We seem to be very confident that we will get that
moratorium,'' Wentz said. ``We're not going to leave until we are
guaranteed there is a moratorium.''
   Fitz said he would have to talk with his vice presidents and
faculty before he could commit the school to a moratorium. He also
said he was not yet committed to a forum and expected to meet again
with the students later today.
   Fitz would not say whether he would order the students removed.
   William C. Schuerman, dean of the school, met with student
representatives for about an hour Thursday evening.
   ``I think we've been very clear that we're offering the students
an opportunity to discuss the issues they're raising,'' Schuerman
said. ``What we're not prepared to do is to meet the demands
they've indicated.''
   The CIA was recruiting at the nearby Kennedy Union on campus,
but a statement issued by the protesters said they did not appear
there because they did not want to infringe on the rights of
students to interview with the agency.
   The students had been told they had to leave by 4:30 p.m.
Thursday or they would face charges. Schuerman said they were
allowed to stay past that deadline to avoid provoking them.
   Those who remained at St. Mary's Hall were charged with
disruption under the student conduct code and later would be
charged with trespassing under the code, spokeswoman Teri Rizvi
said. Penalties could range from a token fine to expulsion, she
said.
   The protesters demanded that if university organizations invite
the CIA to recruit, even off campus, the school should provide a
mandatory course for those seeking CIA jobs that would detail
alleged atrocities committed by the agency.
</TEXT>
