<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Cuba-US     02-26 0339</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Cuba-US,0349</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Delegate Rejects Cuban Charges as Disinformation</HEAD>
<HEAD>RETRANSMITTING a0575 to fix cycle designator</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The chief U.S. delegate to the U.N. Human Rights
Commission, former Cuban political prisoner Armando Valladares,
today rejected Cuban allegations that he lied about being
mistreated in Cuban prisons.
   ``They have had a disinformation campaign against me since
before I left prison,'' Valladares told a news conference.
   The Cuban government Wednesday distributed information in
Geneva, Washington and Mexico City saying Valladares had been a
police officer under the Batista government and that he had been
arrested and jailed in 1961 because he belonged to a terrorist
organization.
   Valladares and the U.S. State Department deny that he was a
police officer, and maintain that he was arrested and sentenced to
30 years in prison for making anti-communist statements.
   Valladares served 22 years of his sentence before being released
after the intervention of French President Francois Mitterrand.
   Since his release, he has spoken out about what he says are
human rights violations in Cuba, in particular torture and inhumane
treatment of prisoners.
   Valladares told the press conference that the Cuban government
resorted to personal attacks against him because ``they are not
able to deny the accusations'' of human rights violations. He spoke
in Spanish, and his remarks were translated into English.
   The Cuban deputy foreign minister, Raul Roa Kouri, said at a
press conference Wednesday that Valladares was lying when he said
he was mistreated in prison.
   Valladares, asked about Kouri's statement, showed reporters
scars on his hands which he said were from rat bites, and took one
reporter's hand and ran it along his head where he said he had a
scar from being beaten.
   The United States on Thursday submitted a resolution for the
second year in a row attempting to get the commission to examine
alleged human rights violations in Cuba.
   This year's resolution appears to be worded more softly than
last year's, which was blocked by one vote, and Valladares said he
was optimistic that it would pass.
</TEXT>
