<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Israel-Shultz     02-26 0717</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel-Shultz,0739</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Shamir Said To Urge Slow Approach On Peacemaking</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Israel-Violence</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir today urged
Secretary of State George P. Shultz to move slowly on Palestinian
self-rule in the violence-torn West Bank and Gaza Strip, informed
sources said.
   Shamir told Shultz at a two-hour meeting that there should be
``a time of testing'' for up to three years before negotiations are
held on a final settlement in the occupied territories, said the
sources, who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   Shultz also met with Foreign Minister Shimon Peres, leader of
the liberal faction of Israel's coalition government and Shamir's
political rival.
   Shultz is promoting a U.S. plan that calls for negotiations on
an overall settlement by December. But the sources said he applied
``no pressure whatsoever'' on Shamir.
   Israeli soldiers today killed two more Palestinians in
anti-Israel protests in the occupied territories, bringing the
death toll in 11 weeks of violence to 67.
   A U.S. official said today that some Palestinians have accepted
invitations to talk with Shultz, despite a Palestine Liberation
Organization ban and death threats. The meeting was set for tonight
in east Jerusalem, which Israel captured from Jordan in the 1967
war.
   The official said 15 moderates had been invited, and a few had
agreed to come although he declined to specify the number or
identify invitees. He spoke on condition of anonymity.
   Shamir later told reporters his session with Shultz was ``very
friendly and thorough'' and said they discussed ``the aspirations
of all of us for getting peace.''
   He said he hoped that the end result would be some ``positive
outcomes.''
   ``I think there are many openings,'' said Peres, who has
previously endorsed most elements of Shultz's proposals. ``I think
there is a great deal of work to be done.''
   Shultz said he agreed and added: ``As always it is a great
benefit to come and have a good long bull session about it all and
hear your views that have been very helpful.''
   Shultz scheduled two more sessions with Shamir on Sunday after
he will have been to Jordan and Syria to assess Arab positions.
   In the talks today, sources said Shamir reiterated his
objections to an international peace conference that would assign
an active role to the Soviet Union.
   Shultz told reporters on his way here Wednesday from Washington
that Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev and Foreign Minister Eduard
A. Shevardnadze have voiced interest in such a conference in their
meetings in Moscow. But Shultz said it was ``not a way to go for
substantive results.''
   Shamir's position would keep alive the 1978 Camp David formula,
which calls for a five-year period to see if the Palestinians and
Israelis can live side-by-side.
   Negotiations on a final settlement would begin after the third
year. The options would include statehood or linking the West Bank
and Gaza to Jordan in a confederation.
   But, Egypt, Jordan and several other countries have told the
United States that they rejected negotiations based on the formula.
The accords produced the 1979 peace treaty between Egypt and Israel.
   Jordanian Prime Minister Zaid Rifai, who will meet with Shultz
in Amman on Saturday, said ``we are against any project that deals
with partial solutions, a dividing approach or projects that deal
with Palestinian autonomy.''
   Autonomy would mean self-rule for the 1.5 million Palestinians
who live in the West Bank and Gaza, but they would not have control
over their security or conduct foreign relations, two key
attributes of statehood.
   Shamir aide Yossi Ahimeir said ``one shouldn't make a
dramatization out of this one meeting. It's part of a process that
will continue in Washington when the prime minister goes there'' in
mid-March.
   Prominent Palestinian moderates had said they would not meet
with Shultz tonight because the United States had not fulfilled a
PLO demand to consult with Palestinians living outside Israeli-held
territories.
   They said this was an indication the Americans were really
seeking to create an alternative Palestinian leadership to the PLO.
   ``I told (Shultz) I regret I cannot accept because the
Palestinian people have decided that we have to have a delegation
reflecting the true composition of the Palestinian people,'' said
Al Faj newspaper editor Hanna Siniora, who met with Shultz earlier
this month in Washington.
</TEXT>
