<1ST_LINE>r a PM-PalisadesDrilling     02-26 0282</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Palisades Drilling,0290</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Rejects Environmentalist Appeal</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB EGELKO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The California Supreme Court has rejected
an appeal by environmentalists and removed a major obstacle to
drilling for oil below scenic bluffs on the Southern California
coast.
   Occidental Petroleum Corp., which first applied for a permit 18
years ago, can begin exploratory drilling within a few months,
unless another court intervenes.
   ``The (Supreme) Court now is less environmentally concerned than
it used to be,'' charged Roger Diamond, a lawyer who represented
residents of the Los Angeles neighborhood challenging the drilling.
   The court Thursday denied a hearing on an appeal of a ruling
last November that upheld the city's 1985 approval of the drilling
project. Justice Stanley Mosk, whose son, Richard, is one of
Occidental's lawyers, did not participate in the Supreme Court
action.
   ``Occidental is obviously very pleased,'' said Arthur Groman,
senior member of the company's board of directors.
   ``This field, which we think may be as much as 60 million
barrels of oil, is a vital resource of the United States,'' he said.
   Diamond, in claiming the court had less concern about the
environment than it used to, noted that the court had blocked
another version of the Palisades project in 1974.
   The lawyer, also a board member of the environmental group in
the case, said opponents will ask a Los Angeles judge next week to
block the drilling while a challenge to the project's Coastal
Commission permit is pending.
   Opponents suffered another setback Monday when a Los Angeles
City Council panel voted 3-2 against a proposal by Councilman
Marvin Braude, who represents the Palisades area, to withdraw city
approval of the project.
</TEXT>
