<1ST_LINE>r i PM-SouthAfrica 1stLd-Writethru a0571 02-26 0631</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-South Africa, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0571,0644</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>All Public UDF Leaders Restricted; At Squatter Camp, Gunfire,
Burned Shacks</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 8 grafs to UPDATE with protests, arrests. PICKS up
5th graf pvs, `When the ... ADDS byline.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LAURINDA KEYS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The treasurer of the United
Democratic Front today became the last leader of South Africa's
biggest anti-apartheid organization to be silenced by the state.
   Police came to the house of Azhar Cachalia this morning and
served him with an order prohibiting him from speaking to the press
and participating in the front's activities.
   In the east coast city of Durban, 14 white women, members of the
volunteer civil rights group Black Sash, were arrested as
demonstrations continued against the new restrictions on major
black opposition groups.
   The move against Cachalia means that every national executive of
the front group, which represents 600 affiliates with 2 million
members, is either in jail, in hiding or restricted by the
government.
   At the University of Cape Town, 2,000 students and staff
gathered to protest the new bans. About half marched around the
campus carrying banners and singing ``God Bless Africa,'' which
many South African blacks regard as their national anthem.
   The Rev. Allan Boesak, president of the World Alliance of
Reformed Churches, told the gathering that nationwide protests
against the government's clampdown must begin immediately.
   Leaders of churches, which like most white opposition groups
were not targeted by the government's restrictions, already have
called for protest services in nations across the country on Sunday.
   ``The battle has only just begun,'' Boesak said. ``We have
decided we will resist. Our commitment starts right now.''
   When the government prohibited the front and 17 other opposition
groups from political activity on Wednesday, it also issued
restrictive orders against 18 senior black leaders, including front
presidents Archie Gumede and Albertina Sisulu.
   Mrs. Sisulu is the wife of imprisoned African National Congress
leader Walter Sisulu.
   About half of the front's leadership is underground. Many others
are in detention without charge, awaiting trial or on trial in
connection with treason charges.
   By law and custom, apartheid establishes a racially segregated
society in which the 26 million blacks have no vote in national
affairs. The 5 million whites control the economy and maintain
separate districts, schools and health services.
   In Cape Town, at least one person died and five were injured
during a clash between rival black factions in a squatter camp near
Crossroads.
   The fighting between militant youths and the management
committee of the KTC squatter camp, both considered anti-apartheid
groups, broke out at 3 a.m. with gunfire and stone-throwing,
residents told journalists. By 7 a.m. 20 shacks had been burned.
   Police reported one dead and two injured, but residents in the
part of the camp controlled by the youths said four people were
treated at a hospital for injuries. The Argus newspaper reported
two deaths.
   The fighting in the camp began last month and hundreds of shacks
have been burned in the feuding reminiscent of the May-June 1986
battles in the Crossroads-area squatter camps.
   In that violence, 70,000 people lost their homes and scores of
people died in battles between conservative ``vigilantes'' and the
squatter-camp groups.
   But this year the fighting is between two groups who had fought
together against the ``vigilantes'' in 1986, and appears to involve
an attempt by the militant youths to gain more power in the
administration of the squatter camp.
   Police reported three blacks were killed in violence in two
Natal province towns, where feuding between supporters of the
United Democratic Front and the Zulu political organization,
Inkatha, has steadily spread from the townships surrounding the
provincial capital, Pietermaritzburg.
   More than 400 blacks have died in the past year in the Natal
fighting.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
