<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Lebanon-Kidnap     02-26 0477</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lebanon-Kidnap,0492</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Amal Chief Fired, Claims Higgins And U.N. Officers Are Spies</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Shiite Moslem Amal militia today
dismissed its security chief in a rift in the forces searching for
kidnapped U.S. Marine Lt. Col. William R. Higgins in south Lebanon.
   Ousted security chief Mustafa Dirani issued a statement that
made no mention of his dismissal, but claimed that Higgins and
other United Nations peacekeeping officials in Lebanon were paid by
NATO to gather information about terrorists.
   Amal said in a terse statement that Dirani was ``relieved from
his responsibility as head of the central security system.'' It did
not elaborate.
   Higgins, 43, was abducted Feb. 17 near Tyre, 50 miles south of
Beirut. Higgins headed an observer group assigned to the United
Nations Interim Force in Lebanon, a peacekeeping force in south
Lebanon.
   The pro-Iranian Organization of the Oppressed on Earth claimed
it abducted Higgins and alleged he was a CIA spy. U.S. and U.N.
officials denied the accusation.
   Higgins is one of nine Americans among 25 foreigners missing and
believed kidnapped in Lebanon.
   ``Regarding the American officer, I would like to stress that we
have confirmed information that NATO is seeking to confront what it
calls terrorism ... by forming security systems specialized in
Lebanon to gather information in preparation for acts of piracy in
the future,'' Dirani said.
   ``For this purpose, NATO uses some U.N. officers and some UNIFIL
officers,'' he said in the handwritten statement.
   Dirani criticized Amal for seizing members of the fundamentalist
Iranian-backed Hezbollah, or Party of God, in south Lebanon during
the dragnet for Higgins. Amal is fighting the Iranian-backed
Hezbollah for control of south Lebanon. Tyre is an Amal stronghold.
   ``We denounce the security arrangements that followed the
abduction of the American officer,'' Dirani said.
   Amal's military commander in Tyre, Daoud Daoud, has been leading
a massive search for Higgins. His militiamen have rounded up at
least 42 Hezbollah members.
   Daoud told reporters today that ``we believe Higgins is still in
the south.'' He made no comment on Dirani's allegations.
   An Amal spokesman in Beirut said Lebanon's senior Shiite cleric,
Sheik Mohammed Mehdi Shamseddine, is involved ``in a quiet effort
to release Higgins.'' He refused to elaborate and spoke on
condition he not be identified.
   Hezbollah, made up of Shiite zealots loyal to Iran's Ayatollah
Ruhollah Khomeini, is believed to be an umbrella for pro-Iranian
factions holding most of the 25 missing foreigners.
   Amal, the main Shiite militia led by Justice Minister Nabih
Berri, is more secular and is backed by Syria, the main power
broker in Lebanon. The two Shiite factions have been vying for
control of south Lebanon.
   The longest held hostage in Lebanon is Terry A. Anderson, chief
Middle East correspondent for The Associated Press. he was seized
in west Beirut on March 16, 1985.
</TEXT>
