<1ST_LINE>u w PM-Vatican-Budget 1stLd-Writethru a0487 02-26 0438</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Vatican-Budget, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0487,430</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Vatican Releases Details of Expenses</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New throughout with detail on expenses; CORRECTS by
eliminating statement that Vatican finances being revealed for
first time</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's Roman Catholic bishops, who have
been asked to make special efforts to help whittle down the
Vatican's annual budget deficit, have released new detail on the
church's worldwide expenses.
   The record 1986 deficit of $56.7 million included spending of
$114 million and income of $57.3 million, said a statement sent to
U.S. bishops for use in making fund-raising appeals in their areas.
The statement was released Thursday.
   The picture for 1987 looked better at the time church leaders
met in Rome to discuss the situation last October, according to an
accompanying letter to U.S. bishops from leading cardinals.
   Contributions were up for the first nine months of 1987,
totaling $35.8 million compared with $32 million for the same
period of 1986, said the letter, which was signed by 10 cardinals,
including John Krol of Philadelphia and John O'Connor of New York.
   The letter spoke of ``a heartening response'' to earlier
appeals, but it also said the bishops were ``once more invited to
continue their generous efforts to make the faithful aware of the
Holy See's economic problems.''
   The biggest 1986 expense by far was for personnel _ $57.9
million, including $50.6 million to pay the Vatican's 2,315
employees and $7.3 million in pension payments to 885 retired
people.
   The Vatican statement said the next largest expense was $11.7
million for publishing activities, followed by $11 million for
expenses on investments.
   The investment expenses, including management of Vatican
investments and interest paid to depositors in Vatican accounts,
left a net income on investments of $17.8 million when deducted
from gross investment income of $28.8 million.
   Other expenses included:
   _$10.4 million for Vatican radio, including $3.9 million for
operating costs and $6.5 million for modernization of equipment.
   _$9.7 million for administrative expenses, ``from the most
elementary ones (stationery and printing supplies) to the most
complex (consultencies of all sorts).''
   _$9.6 million for depreciation and restoration of endowment
funds, to help cover the previous year's deficit and to deal with
inflation.
   _$2.1 million for electricity, water, heating and other
utilities.
   _$1.6 million for maintenance work on office buildings and taxes
on rented buildings.
   As for Vatican income, investment income was the largest item at
$28.8 million, followed by $17.1 million from publishing activities
and lesser amounts from other activities.
   The Vatican has been in the red every year since 1979, when it
first made financial details public. The deficit at that time was
about $20 million.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
