<1ST_LINE>r a PM-TeachersStrike     02-26 0335</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Teachers Strike,0344</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Classes Canceled after Teachers Declare Strike</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CLEVELAND (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Classes were canceled today for nearly 73,000
pupils in Ohio's largest school district after teachers rejected a
contract offer and set up picket lines.
   Talks were scheduled to resume at 1 p.m. today, according to
federal mediator Jack Buettner.
   Principals and administrative staff will reopen four high
schools Monday for 3,600 seniors, Superintendent Alfred Tutela
said. Teachers had planned to strike Thursday, but the district
declared a snow day and closed all buildings.
   School officials and Cleveland Teachers Union members declined
to discuss the school board's latest offer, which was made at 6:30
a.m. Thursday after two days of negotiations.
   At a regularly scheduled school board meeting Thursday evening,
Mildred Madison, board president, said she believed the board had
made a fair offer.
   More than 100 students and teachers attended the meeting, and
many were unhappy over negotiating efforts by school officials.
   ``It's the students who really need the education here,'' Reubin
Fitzhugh, a senior at Cleveland's Aviation High School, told the
board. ``You have your education. Why can't we have ours?''
   The school board reportedly has dropped its demand that a
mandatory career ladder system be included in the new contract,
leaving wages as the major unresolved issue. A career ladder system
would have linked teacher advancement and pay raises to performance
evaluations.
   The school board initially offered a one-time 2 percent bonus
payment, with further raises contingent on passage of a tax levy.
Union president Eugene Kolach said the board had revised its offer
to a 2 percent raise retroactive to September, and another 1
percent raise retroactive to Jan. 1. A pay raise in the second year
would be linked to a levy approval.
   Beginning Cleveland teachers are paid $17,600 a year. The
average teacher makes $29,000 annually and the highest paid teacher
makes just more than $34,600. Of the 5,093 union members, 2,559 are
classroom teachers.
   The last teachers strike in the district lasted 11 weeks in 1979.
</TEXT>
