<1ST_LINE>r a PM-SoldierofFortune     02-26 0486</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soldier of Fortune,0496</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Classified Ad Not Protected by First Amendment, Judge Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL L. GRACZYK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Soldier of Fortune magazine ad, subject of a
negligence suit that seeks millions of dollars in damages, does not
fall under First Amendment protection because the ad represents a
commercial form of speech, a federal judge says.
   U.S. District Judge David Hittner issued the written opinion
Thursday, elaborating on a pre-trial decision that refused to
dismiss the $22.5 million suit filed against the magazine by the
family of a Texas woman slain in 1985.
   In an eight-page decision, Hittner cited several federal rulings
that allowed negligence suits where commercial speech was the issue.
   According to the judge, the magazine acknowledges that the ad
fell into the realm of commercial speech and to allow dismissal of
the suit under First Amendment grounds ``would afford to commercial
speech a broader protection than that given core speech.''
   Gary Black, 18, and Marjorie Einmann, 64, are suing the
self-styled ``Journal for Professional Adventurers'' for running a
classified ad that led to the killing of Sandra Black, Gary Black's
mother and Mrs. Einmann's daughter.
   Robert Black is on Texas' death row for paying John Wayne Hearn
$10,000 to kill his wife at her Bryan home in February 1985. Hearn
is serving three life terms in Florida for the Black slaying and
two others in that state.
   Hearn's ad appeared in four issues of the magazine in late 1984,
offering services of former Marine and Vietnam veterans and weapons
specialists with jungle warfare expertise for ``high-risk
assignments'' in the United States or overseas.
   Attorneys for the magazine do not dispute that the ad brought
Hearn and Black together, but insist that Soldier of Fortune
publisher Robert Brown had no way of knowing the ad was for illegal
activity. Brown has testified he would have halted the classified
ads for personal services if he had known they were linked to
crimes.
   Brown, publisher and founder of the Boulder, Colo.-based
magazine, was expected to return to the stand today as the trial
completed a second week. He was called last week as an adverse
witness for the plaintiffs and his attorneys reserved
cross-examination until later.
   A former top editor at the magazine testified Thursday he
favored elimination of classified ads from the publication because
they were journalistically unprofessional.
   William Guthrie, now a free-lance writer living in Idaho, said
the ads continued despite his objections because Brown thought they
lent an air of mystique to the publication.
   ``Certain kinds of classified ads appeared to trivialize the
magazine,'' said Guthrie, who was executive editor before leaving
in 1986. ``If Soldier of Fortune was trying to look like a
legitimate military news magazine, to have ads for brass knuckles
and so forth seemed inappropriate.''
   Guthrie said he was not aware that any of the ads may have been
linked to criminal activity.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880226-0090 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-26-88 1048EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-FireSickout     02-26 0321</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Fire Sickout,0330</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Fines Union, Drops Contempt Charges Against Firefighters</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge dropped contempt-of-court
citations against 34 firefighters, but ordered their union to pay a
$25,000 fine for a three-day sickout.
   The president of the union Thursday read a letter of apology to
the court for not doing more to comply with a back-to-work order
issued on the first day of the sickout that eventually involved 110
firefighters.
   Leo J. Miller, the president of Local 799 of the International
Association of Firefighters, also promised to ``monitor all sick
leave that appears to be excessive'' in the future.
   Later, Miller said the apology was not an admission that
firefighters had participated in any type of job action. Job
actions by municipal employees are illegal under Rhode Island law.
   Superior Court Judge Americo Campanella told Miller he was
fining the union ``in order to impress upon you ... the importance
of a court order.''
   The 34 firefighters failed to appear before Campanella on Monday
afternoon, after they were served notice by the city to appear in
court.
   City labor lawyer Vincent Ragosta Jr. said he was pleased with
the ruling, but said the city will press a civil suit to recover
$100,000 spent on overtime during the sickout. The fire department
kept its night shift on duty throughout the sickout; no major fires
occurred during the three days.
   The city said the firefighters called in sick _ 50 out of 51 on
Saturday and all 60 on Sunday _ to protest what they believed were
unilateral changes made in their contract by the city. The walkout
ended Tuesday.
   The city has yet to sign the agreement ratified by the union in
December, though it has been honoring wage and benefit increases.
   The dispute, according to Fire Chief Michael F. Moise, concerned
the union's insistence that rescue truck crews have the highest
level of emergency medical technician training.
</TEXT>
