<2ND_LINE>PM-Teen Stabbing,0316</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Teens Charged In Stabbing Death Of High School Senior</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: MacDonald and McDonald are cq</NOTE>
<DATELINE>EDWARDSVILLE, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An honors student was fatally stabbed
by two teen-agers after a quarrel over a girl, but before the
victim died he was able to warn a brother and call his girlfriend,
police reported.
   ``After the stabbing he called his girlfriend and said, `I
probably won't be seeing you again,''' said Madison County Sheriff
Bob Churchich.
   Christopher A. McDonald, 18, also was able to tell his father
what had happened and to identify his assailants before he died a
short time later Wednesday at Anderson Hospital in Maryville,
police said. An autopsy found he had been stabbed in the chest and
the abdomen.
   The boy's father, Gary McDonald, said his son had been visited a
few days earlier by a girl who apparently was a friend of one of
the suspects.
   The elder McDonald told police that Christopher and his
12-year-old brother were home alone when the quarrel and attack
occurred. Christopher had been on the first floor and the younger
brother was upstairs, he said.
   ``They threatened to kill our family, but Chris stood up to
them, and they stabbed him to death,'' Gary McDonald told the St.
Louis Post-Dispatch.
   The younger brother did not hear the fight, but Christopher was
able to stagger upstairs and warn him to lock his bedroom door,
McDonald said.
   He said he was returning home when the suspects' car sped out of
the driveway ``and almost hit me.''
   Alec MacDonald, 17, of rural Edwardsville, and Dennis M. Miller,
16, of rural Worden, were charged Thursday with first-degree
murder, home invasion and armed violence, said Assistant State's
Attorney Randy Massey.
   Authorities refused to say which suspect was believed to have
stabbed Christopher or whether the weapon had been recovered.
</TEXT>
