<1ST_LINE>r a PM-UAW-Chrysler     02-26 0454</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-UAW-Chrysler,0468</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Angry Workers Demonstrate To Protest Possible Acustar Sale</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JANET BRAUNSTEIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Auto Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HIGHLAND PARK, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A top UAW official says he will give
local unions permission to strike on a plant-by-plant basis in an
attempt to discourage the company from selling its $1 billion
parts-making subsidiary.
   More than 1,000 angry workers massed outside Chrysler
headquarters in 20-degree temperatures Thursday chanting ``Strike!
Strike!'' to protest the proposed sale of Acustar Inc., which
employs 28,000 workers and represents nearly a fifth of Chrysler's
worldwide operations.
   ``You do whatever you need to do _ and you know what to do,''
UAW Vice President Marc Stepp told the demonstrators. The rally
followed a special meeting of the 140-delegate Chrysler bargaining
council representing the company's 49 UAW locals.
   Although the union can't legally call a national strike against
Chrysler over Acustar, Stepp said he will give local UAW unions
permission to strike on a plant-by-plant basis over unresolved
issues such as health-and-safety grievances.
   A series of local strikes at key Chrysler plants could shut down
the company nationwide.
   At least seven Chrysler locals have voted to seek strike
authorization and one, a key 4,000-worker stamping plant in
Sterling Heights, should receive authorization as early as next
week, Stepp predicted.
   Stepp said the possible Acustar sale, which Chrysler Chairman
Lee Iacocca confirmed in early February, threatens the jobs of all
Chrysler workers by weakening their bargaining power and reducing
work opportunities within the corporation.
   The council unanimously passed a resolution calling for
suspension of all joint labor-management programs that require
trust and cooperation, including special team-concept agreements at
six plants, unless Chrysler decides not to sell Acustar.
   Chrysler has begun implementing the so-called Modern Operating
Agreements at plants in Huntsville, Ala., and in Indianapolis and
Newcastle, Ind.
   Local union leaders said they immediately will stop attending
labor-management plant meetings.
   Similar agreements, in which workers share tasks as part of a
team, have not yet taken effect at plants in Detroit; Newark, Del.;
and Trenton, N.J., Stepp said.
   Chrysler has said it may sell Acustar because it doesn't want to
invest in the research needed to upgrade some operations. Chrysler
already buys 70 percent of its parts from outside sources.
   Workers say they are angry at the possible sale because they
made concessions and helped Iacocca win loan guarantees from the
federal government to rescue the company from the verge of
bankruptcy at the beginning of the decade.
   Stepp will lead negotiations with Chrysler this summer to
replace its contract, which expires Sept. 14. Stepp said Chrysler
already has made talks more difficult with its announcement last
month that it will close its assembly plant in Kenosha, Wis., by
the end of the year.
</TEXT>
