<1ST_LINE>u a PM-HelicopterCrash 2ndLd-Writethru a0552 02-26 0863</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Helicopter Crash, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0552,0881</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Transport Chopper Crashes After Onboard Fire Breaks Out</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS grafs 14-17 pvs bgng `The copter,...' with 7 grafs to
UPDATE with Fort Sill comment on fatalities and injured from that
base, ID of dead, later hospital conditions for three men. Pickup
18th graf `Fort Hood...'</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto DN1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF AWALT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICO, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Army helicopter nosedived into a cow
pasture and skidded about 75 feet before it broke apart in a sheet
of fire, killing 10 men and seriously burning eight others,
authorities and witnesses said.
   Two soldiers leaped about 35 feet to the ground from the burning
twin-rotor CH-47D Chinook before it crashed about 50 miles from
Fort Worth on Thursday, said state Department of Public Safety Sgt.
Robert Rankin. One of the soldiers died.
   The other soldier said that a fire had broken out at the back of
the helicopter based at Fort Sill, Okla., and that those aboard had
tried to move to the front to get away from the flames, Rankin said.
   Residents raced to the scene, pulling casualties away from the
raging grass fire sparked by the crash.
   ``Some of them were just sitting there screaming,'' said
17-year-old Dale Christopher, a Chico High School student who was
among the first on the scene. ``And they kept asking us `Help us.
Help us.' And then we'd say `Help is on the way.' That's all we
could do for them.''
   A three-person team of investigators from the Army Safety Center
at Fort Rucker, Ala., was investigating the crash today.
   The Chinook CH-47D has a history of problems and the Army
grounded its entire fleet of 63 of the big transport helicopters
for 1{ months in 1985 after an accident in Honduras injured eight
soldiers.
   Witnesses said the helicopter was tilted forward at a 45-degree
angle, puffing smoke and descending rapidly when it crashed about
3:29 p.m., slicing through a power line.
   ``All of a sudden a little thin streak of smoke came out of it
and there was a small explosion on the right side underneath it,''
said Joe Haworth, who was working at a nearby plant. ``Then it put
out a little more smoke and it flew straight for a ways, then parts
went to coming out of it.''
   The craft skidded about 75 feet before breaking apart in a sheet
of fire, said Wendell Berry Sr., 53, who watched the accident from
his home a half-mile away.
   Berry cut the seat belt away from a crewman strapped to the
remains of the cockpit.
   ``There was only one guy still in the helicopter who was either
the pilot or the co-pilot, and he was conscious,'' Berry said. ``He
was so conscious that when I cut his seatbelt he said, `That feels
better _ thanks.'''
   Jack Souther, 54, used a small fire extinguisher from his pickup
truck to douse burning bodies. ``The only thing I could do was put
the fires out on the bodies. I went from body to body trying to put
them out,'' he said.
   The copter, carrying 13 passengers and five crew members, was
returning to Fort Sill from Fort Hood in central Texas, Fort Sill
spokesman Rick Brink said.
   Fort Sill officials said today that two pilots and a flight
engineer from the post were among the 10 killed, and that two of
the injured were also from Fort Sill.
   Fort Sill spokesman Richard Brown identified the three dead as
Staff Sgt. Raymond T. Hill, 31, of New Baltimore, Mich.; Chief
Warrant Officer 4 Ronald W. Bender, 40, of Rockville Center, N.Y.,
and Chief Warrant Officer 4 Scott J. Temple, 43, of Irving, Texas.
Bender was the command pilot and Temple was a pilot. Hill was a
flight engineer.
   Of the 10 dead, six died at the scene, one died in Parkland
Hospital in Dallas, one died in Bridgeport Hospital and another
died early today at Brooke Army Medical Center in San Antonio.
Another soldier was found dead at the crash site after dark
Thursday.
   Three soldiers remained hospitalized at Parkland Memorial
Hospital this morning, one of them in critical condition with skull
fractures and lacerations on his thigh, said spokesman Tom Geddie.
A second was in fair condition with a hip fracture and a third was
in good condition with a broken leg and cuts on his face.
   Four soldiers who had been initially taken to Parkland late
Thursday were moved to Brooke Army Medical Center in San Antonio,
but one died shortly after arrival, a spokesman said today.
   Fort Hood soldiers Paul Stroud and Calvin Turner were in serious
condition at Harris Methodist Hospital in Fort Worth early today,
said spokeswoman Mandy Goad.
   The CH-47D, which has a troop capacity of 44, is a modernized
version of earlier models of the Chinook, which was used in Vietnam.
   In the Honduras accident, a transmission bearing failed on a
CH-47D taxiing to a refueling depot. The failure caused one of the
copter's main rotors to stop turning; the other rotor began hitting
it and the helicopter tore itself apart.
   The Chinook's main rotors mesh as they turn, and therefore must
be synchronized.
</TEXT>
