<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BusShooting 1stLd-Writethru a0560 02-26 0422</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bus Shooting, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0560,0429</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Street Gang Member Opens Fire on City Bus, Wounds Four</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Inserts two grafs after the 7th, beginning ``The shooting,''
to update with gang attack elsewhere.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A member of a street gang opened fire at a
member of a rival gang on a crowded city bus, seriously wounding
the 15-year-old boy and three other teen-agers, police said.
   ``This is every day,'' bystander Mary James said at the scene of
the shooting spree Thursday afternoon. ``I wouldn't mind seeing the
National Guard around here.''
   Witnesses aboard the packed Southern California Rapid Transit
District bus said two teens on the bus asked passengers if they
were members of a rival gang, said police Lt. Joseph Freia.
   The passengers said they weren't, but one of the two youths
pointed to another teen-ager and identified him as a rival gang
member, Freia said.
   The youth singled out then pulled a .45-caliber pistol from his
waistband and shot the challenger in the chest, said police Lt.
Bruce Hagerty.
   He fired at random and wounded three other 15-year-old boys
before he fled on foot into the South Central Los Angeles
neighborhood, police said. A search of the neighborhood turned up
no suspects, police said.
   The shooting occurred in an area of the city that is plagued by
gang violence and drug dealing. More than 300 gang-related killings
occurred in Los Angeles County last year, many of them in the
neighborhoods of South Central.
   On the north side of the city, a man was stabbed in the neck
late Thursday when he drove his pickup into a residential
neighborhood just as a fight between 25 to 50 alleged gang members
broke up, said police Lt. Don Brown.
   ``A couple of gang members jumped in the back of his truck'' and
rode for about half a block, Brown said. When the victim stopped
his truck, one pulled out a knife and stabbed him in the neck,
narrowly missing his jugular vein, officials said. The victim was
in stable condition today. No one was arrested.
   The street violence stirred up political tensions in the city
after a 27-year-old Long Beach woman was gunned down by gangs in
the trendy Westwood area last month.
   Police Chief Daryl Gates deployed more officers to the area,
prompting complaints by residents of the gang-plagued poorer
neighborhoods that they don't receive the same attention.
   Earlier this week, county Supervisor Kenneth Hahn suggested
National Guard troops be called in to quell the epidemic of gang
violence.
</TEXT>
