<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Castro-Drugs 1stLd-Writethru a0601 02-26 0519</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Castro-Drugs, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0601,0532</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Castro Denies Allegations That Cuba Aided Drug Trafficking</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS new grafs 5-8 to UPDATE with Miami Herald report on
indictments and to move up similar NBC report. Pickup 5th graf pvs,
`Castro said Blandon... DELETES last graf of pvs, now redundant.</NOTE>
<HEAD>With PM-Panama, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cuban President Fidel Castro called a Panamanian
military aide's assertion that Castro was an active partner in
alleged drug operations with Panama's Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega
``lies, all lies.''
   In an NBC News interview broadcast Thursday, Castro sharply
denied claims by Jose Blandon, a former Panamanian Defense Forces
aide and the country's former consul general in New York.
   Blandon told a congressional committee two weeks ago that Castro
was involved in the alleged drug operations with Noriega, Panama's
military strongman. Federal grand juries in Miami and Tampa, Fla.,
indicted Noriega earlier this month in connection with cocaine and
marijuana trafficking.
   NBC also reported Thursday that U.S. officials say they have
solid evidence that Cuban MiG fighters and Cuban coast guard boats
have been involved in escorting and protecting cocaine shipments on
their way from Colombia to the Florida Keys via Cuba.
   In a related development, the Miami Herald reported today that a
federal grand jury has returned sealed indictments against 17
people it accuses of using Cuba as a way station to smuggle cocaine
from Colombia to South Florida.
   The indictments describe four cocaine loads totaling 3,800
pounds, two that came through Cuba, one through Haiti and one
through the Bahamas, federal law enforcement sources told the paper.
   The grand jury returned two indictments, one charging five
people and another 12. Neither accuses Cuban officials of
wrongdoing, sources told the Herald.
   NBC also reported that the Miami grand jury was ready to hand up
the indictments.
   Castro said Blandon ``has accused Noriega of bypassing the
blockade (the U.S. trade embargo against Cuba), of warning Cuba
before the invasion of Grenada, of being a spy, of drug
trafficking, of asking me for advice to return some money, and all
those are lies and slander.''
   ``What he says is lies, all lies,'' Castro said through an
interpreter in the interview taped Wednesday in Havana.
   Blandon also testified that Castro mediated a dispute between
Noriega and a Colombian drug cartel.
   Castro denied he ever talked to Noriega about the dispute. ``I
have documents on archives that this type of conversation never
took place. It's a lie from top to bottom,'' he said.
   Blandon also accused Noriega of acting as a double agent.
   ``He said that Noriega sells CIA secrets to us. He has never
given U.S. confidential information to us,'' Castro said.
   Castro denied that there is drug trafficking of any type in
Cuba: ``Cuba is the cleanest country in the world.''
   However, the network reported that Colombian pilots have been
landing at Havana International Airport and a nearby Cuban air
force base with loads of cocaine, which are then shipped into
Florida.
   NBC interviewed a Colombian pilot who said he was working
undercover for the FBI as part of an investigation into the alleged
drug operation.
</TEXT>
