<1ST_LINE>r a PM-NoRadar     02-26 0190</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-No Radar,0192</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>FAA Facility At Longmont Loses Radar For 3 Minutes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONGMONT, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   For three long minutes, air traffic
controllers at the Denver Air Route Traffic Control Center were
without radar systems to track planes in parts of nine Western
states, relying instead on manual calculations.
   The primary computer system used to track air traffic failed at
6:14 p.m. Thursday, and controllers were unable to switch to the
backup system until 6:17 p.m. because it had been taken apart for
maintenance, said Lee Fryer, a duty officer for the Federal
Aviation Administration in Seattle.
   During those three minutes, air traffic controllers had to keep
the traffic separated by using manual calculations.
   A controller who was working during the shutdown said that the
equipment failure lasted longer than three minutes. ``Three minutes
is optimistic on the FAA side,'' he said. Safety at the center was
``most definitely compromised,'' said the controller, who asked
that his name not be used.
   However, Fryer said that a three-minute shutdown was not long
enough to cause a safety problem. Keeping track of the aircraft
``was not a serious problem,'' he said.
</TEXT>
