<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Soviet-Armenia 2ndLd-Writethru a0562 02-26 0853</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-Armenia, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0562,0873</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gorbachev Appeals to Armenian Public for Calm</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS graf 7-13, bgng, `The protests ...,' with 9 grafs to
UPDATE with details of speech and report that protests waning.
PICKS up 14th graf, `The protests ...' EDITS to tighten.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN-THOR DAHLBURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mikhail S. Gorbachev today made an unprecedented
public appeal for calm in the protest-plagued republic of Armenia,
but thousands ignored him and took to the streets in a ``sea of
banners,'' witnesses said.
   For the past five days, protesters have jammed the center of
Yerevan, Armenia's capital, to demand that a region of the
neighboring republic of Azerbaidzhan, Nagorno-Karabakh, whose
population is more than three-quarters Armenian, be made part of
Armenia.
   The Communist Party Central Committee, over which Gorbachev
presides as party general secretary, rejected the call earlier this
month. That sparked street protests in Yerevan in numbers without
precedent in the 70 years of Soviet history.
   Sergei Grigoryants, an Armenian dissident, said a speech from
Gorbachev was read over Armenian state-run radio at 11 a.m. by
Vladimir I. Dolgikh, a non-voting member of the ruling Politburo.
It was later read by Dolgikh over local television, said Gevorg
Mirozyan, an editor at Armenian Gostelradio, the state broadcasting
authority.
   ``Gorbachev called on the Armenian people to be calm, and said
there were a lot of unresolved problems, including that of
Nargorno-Karabakh, and that a patient approach is required,''
Grigoryants told The Associated Press by telephone from Yerevan.
   The 15-minute speech also was broadcast over loudspeakers at
Yerevan airport and elsewhere in the city, said Grigoryants, a
Moscow resident who arrived in Armenia earlier today.
   Demonstrators also watched the address on TV monitors that had
been set up on in Yerevan's streets, said Valery Aidinyan, chief of
the propaganda department at the local Communist Party newspaper
Kommunist.
   Gorbachev said the Central Committee intends to devote one of
its next plenary meetings to examining relations among the
country's more than 100 ethnic groups.
   The Soviet Union has recently faced ethnic problems among the
Baltic republics and in the Central Asian republic of Kazakhstan,
where three people were killed and 200 injured in rioting Dec.
17-18, 1986.
   Armenia, the smallest of the 15 Soviet republics in area, has
3.4 million people.
   Grigoryants said Gorbachev's speech was more conciliatory and
soothing than ``combative'' remarks made Wednesday night in Yerevan
by Dolgikh, but he said it failed to sway protesters.
   ``The numbers in the streets have grown to more than 1 million
today,'' Grigoryants said. ``Columns are marching along the major
streets, and there is a sea of banners.''
   Several hours later, Aidinyan said the demonstrators had begun
to disperse. A worker at the Yerevan Hotel, speaking on condition
of anonymity, confirmed that by nighfall, virtually all of the
demonstrators had left the city center.
   ``There is no disorder. Everyone is working again,'' he said by
telephone.
   Factories, scientific institutes and the Armenian telegraph
agency reportedly went on strike in sympathy with the protest.
Armenians who had served with the Soviet army in Afghanistan were
said to be among the protesters, throwing away their medals and
their Communist Party membership cards.
   The protests in Yerevan, now in their fifth straight day,
constitute a clear challenge to Gorbachev's campaign for greater
democratization and openness. Gorbachev's personal appeal showed
how seriously the Kremlin regards the situation.
   There has been no official estimate of the number of protesters,
and the state-run travel agency Intourist has refused to allow
Moscow-based reporters to travel to Yerevan.
   Ayrikyan said that before midnight Thursday, 1,500 Soviet
paratroopers had been flown into Yerevan, and were ferried in a
40-vehicle motorcade to the Dynamo sports hall and other locations
around the republic's capital.
   ``They came with full equipment, including clubs,'' Ayrikyan
said. He said paratroopers were told by officers aboard their
transport planes that an ``uprising for national independence'' was
under way in Armenia, but would not say how he obtained the
information.
   Ayrikyan, a former political prisoner who spent 17 years in
labor camps and exile for alleged nationalist behavior, called the
arrival of the paratroopers ``an interference in Armenia's
affairs.'' Each of the Soviet Union's 15 republics is ostensibly
independent.
   Mofses Gorgisyan, 26, a member of an Armenian underground group
called the Alliance for National Determination, told the AP by
phone from Yerevan Thursday that other soldiers took up positions
in the city's downtown area and stationed tanks in the outskirts.
   A 17-year-old resident of Nagorno-Karabakh said after arriving
in Moscow Thursday that virtually the entire Armenian population of
the region, about 120,000 people, has been demonstrating daily in
the main city, Stepanakert, since Feb. 13.
   The student, who spoke on condition she not be identified, said
protests were continuing round-the-clock and that schools and
businesses were closed in a strike.
   She also said some Armenians in her region had been killed by
Azeris, members of the dominant ethnic group in Azerbaidzhan, but
that she had did not know how many or the circumstances.
   Soviet officials have said there were ``victims'' of the unrest,
but did not give other information.
</TEXT>
