<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BombFound     02-26 0226</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bomb Found,0233</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Excavation At Nuclear Plant Scoops Up World War II Bomb</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HANAU, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A construction crew working on the
grounds of a plutonium-refining plant found an unexploded World War
II bomb in a load of soil they had just dumped onto a truck,
officials said.
   Explosives experts safely disarmed the 110-pound U.S.-made bomb
after moving it to a wooded area, said Christiane Kohl, spokeswoman
for the Hesse state Environment Ministry.
   The crew was digging the foundation for a new building at the
Alkem nuclear-reprocessing facility in Hanau, 12 miles east of
Frankfurt, she said.
   The excavator's metal shovel scooped up a chunk of earth ``and
loaded it onto a truck,'' she said, and the crew then noticed the
bomb amid the dirt.
   Work at the scene was halted and police and atomic safety
officials were informed, an Alkem statement said.
   ``Detonation experts said there would have been no danger to
stored nuclear materials had the bomb gone off'' because of the way
the facilities at Alkem are constructed, Ms. Kohl said.
   The bomb was unearthed about 80 yards from production buildings
at the reprocessing facility, she said.
   Manfred Popp, state secretary for the Hesse Environment
Ministry, said experts will search the grounds for more ordnances
before work resumes.
   The Alkem nuclear facility produces radioactive fuel rods for
nuclear power plants.
  
</TEXT>
