<FILEID>AP-NR-02-26-88 1236EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Economy Bjt   02-26 0791</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Economy, Bjt,780</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Consumer Prices Up 0.3 Percent In January</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Economics Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Consumer prices rose a moderate 0.3 percent in
January, about the same rate of inflation as through 1987, but a
large decline in energy costs cloaked hefty increases in many other
areas, the government reported Friday.
   The January increase in the Labor Department's Consumer Price
Index followed a revised December increase of 0.2 percent. The
December rise initially been reported as 0.1 percent.
   The advance was equivalent to an annual inflation rate of 4.2
percent, according to department analysts. That compares to the 4.4
percent actual rate of inflation posted for 1987 and is also in
line with the Reagan administration's projection of 4.3 percent
inflation for 1988.
   But, while most analysts do not see a major acceleration of
inflation this year, January's figures showed particularly steep
increases in the category of services.
   Medical care services rose 0.8 percent, its steepest increase in
two years. The cost of hospital rooms was up 1.2 percent,
physicians' bills were up 1.0 percent.
   Rent costs rose 1.1 per cent, auto insurance prices were up 1.5
percent and entertaintment costs rose 0.9 percent.
   Analysts said that many of the price increases may reflect
one-time-only increases timed to coincide with the beginning of the
year.
   But Donald Ratajczak, a Georgia State University economist who
specializes in price activity, called the report ``a bit
worrisome.''
   ``We didn't expect that much of a rise in services,'' he said.
``It does appear that there was some aggressive pricing going on in
January. We should see some calming in February.''
   In another economic reports Friday:
   _The Commerce Department said Americans' personal incomes and
consumer spending both rose at moderate rates of 0.3 percent in
January, less than half the 0.7 gains both posted in December.
Economists expect weakening consumer spending this year as the
economy slows down.
   _A real estate trade group said sales of existing homes fell 3.6
percent in January, the third consecutive monthly decline. The
National Association of Realtors said that sales of existing
single-family homes were at their slowest pace since June 1985.
   January's consumer inflation level would have been higher had it
not been for the second consecutive monthly decline in energy costs.
   In fact, subtracting the usually volatile food and energy
categories, consumer prices for all other goods and services rose a
sharp 0.5 percent in January _ equivalent to about a 6 percent
annual inflation rate _ after a 0.2 percent increase in this
category in December.
   Overall, energy prices fell 0.7 percent in January after a 0.8
percent drop in December.
   Gasoline prices fell 1.6 percent, heating oil costs were down
0.8 percent, natural gas prices dropped 0.1 percent and electricity
charges were down 0.3 percent.
   Food prices, meanwhile, rose but not as much as they had in the
previous month _ up 0.3 percent after December's 0.6 percent gain.
   Overall, grocery prices were up 0.2 percent while restaurant
meal costs climbed 0.3 percent. After climbing sharply through the
fall, the index for fruits and vegetables fell 0.4 percent last
month. Beef prices were down 1.4 percent, pork prices fell 0.5
percent.
   Poultry prices, however, climbed 1.0 percent while cereal and
bakery products rose 1.1 percent.
   Although import prices have been rising recently under the
pressure of a weaker U.S. dollar, the January price report did not
show much evidence of dollar-related inflation.
   And, despite the surge in service prices in January, most
economists stuck to their predictions of relatively little price
acceleration for 1988.
   ``There were a lot of price increases that come at the first of
the year, but I'm not overly alarmed,'' said Lawrence Chimerine,
chairman of The Wefa Group, a Philadelphia-area forecasting service.
   ``Services are clearly a major source of inflation. But I think
that in the months to come, we'll see less inflation from services
and more from import price increases,'' Chimerine added.
   The Labor Department gave these other specifics of January price
behavior.
   _New automobile prices were down 0.2 percent; used automobile
prices fell 0.1 percent.
   _Housing expenses were up 0.4 percent.
   _Apparel costs gained 0.1 percent.
   _Tobacco products rose 2.8 percent.
   January's increase left the CPI at 115.7, meaning that a
selection of goods and services that cost $100 during a 1982-84
base period cost would have $115.70 last month.
   The department recently abandoned a 1967 base period in favor of
the 1982 standard. Under that earlier base period, a selection of
goods and services costing $100 in that year would have cost
$346.70 last month _ which is $1.56 more than the same goods cost
in January 1986.
   The overall index is not adjusted for seasonal variations while
other figures in the report are.
</TEXT>
