<1ST_LINE>r a AM-SettlementReached     02-26 0278</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Settlement Reached,0284</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Woman Receives $925,000 In Malpractice Settlement</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JACKSONVILLE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman has reached a $925,000
settlement of her suit against a hospital and nursing company
charging a nurse incorrectly hooked up a pump, causing air pressure
that blew a hole in the woman's intestine.
   Juanita Johns continues to suffer infections and has a
disfiguring scar on her stomach, one of her attorneys, Wayne
Alford, said Friday.
   Mrs. Johns, 53, reached the settlement this week with University
Medical Center and Medical Personnel Pool of Northeast Florida
Inc., which supplied the nurse under a contract with the hospital.
Mrs. Johns' malpractice lawsuit had been scheduled to go to trial
next week.
   Mrs. Johns was recovering from lung surgery at University
Hospital in Jacksonville last year when her doctor ordered a tube
placed down her throat to remove intestinal gas.
   However, a private-duty nurse attached the tube to the exhaust
end of a pump and air was pumped into Mrs. Johns, blowing a hole in
her intestines, her lawyers said.
   ``She realized something was wrong when because her stomach
started blowing up like a balloon,'' Alford said of his client.
``She suffered extreme pain. At that point, she ripped this thing
out of her nose and out of her stomach and a doctor later said this
ultimately saved her life.''
   Mrs. Johns was rushed into surgery and was in intensive care for
eight days.
   Under the agreement, the hospital will pay $150,000 and the
nursing pool will pay $775,000, said Alford and fellow attorney
John Kalil. The settlement was reached after a judge ruled that
both the hospital and the nursing firm could be held liable.
</TEXT>
