<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Panama 6thLd-Writethru   02-26 0882</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Panama, 6th Ld - Writethru,a0626,0911</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Assembly Removes President, Cabinet Appoints New Chief of State</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 31 grafs to ADD Noriega and Reagan comments. Picks
up 1st graf a0627</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ALINA GUERRERO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The National Assembly today convened
an emergency session and ousted President Eric Arturo Delvalle
after he tried to fire the nation's military chief and de facto
leader, Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega.
   In a 10-minute session, 38 legislators voted Delvalle out of
office and accused him of promoting U.S. interference in domestic
affairs by trying to force Noriega out.
   The Cabinet immediately named a new chief of state, Education
Minister Manuel Solis Palma, who was sworn in before dawn. Devalle
called the moves ``legally despicable.''
   Noriega blamed the upheaval on the United States but said U.S.
interests in Panama would be safe. He said the events were
``strictly internal.''
   In Washington, President Reagan said the United States does not
plan military intervention in Panama. ``No, I don't think that's
the answer,'' he said when asked.
   U.S. Ambassador Arthur Davis said the U.S. government would not
recognize the replacement for Devalle, who had acted to assert
civilian control over the government.
   Opposition leaders were meeting today to discuss a possible
national strike and the university was closed, but banks and stores
opened and there was no sign of unrest.
   Noriega, under indictment in the United States on drug
trafficking charges, said through his Miami attorney, Ray Takiff,
``All American interest in the republic are and shall remain
undisturbed and unharmed.''
   Noriega said he was a friend of the American people, but he
denounced U.S. politicans who he said advocate ``hysteria (and) act
with a wreckless disregard for the truth.''
   In an interview broadcast today by the government's Radio
Nacional, Noriega said of the United States: ``They have been using
a web that includes psychological warfare ... slander, lies,
injury, conjecture, and ... misinformation.''
   Drivers honked their horns and some waved white handerchiefs
immediately after Delvalle announced his plan to oust Noriega. Both
have been signs of opposition to Noriega, who was the target of
nationwide protests and strikes last summer.
   Carlos Ernesto Gonzales de la Lastra, a spokesman for the
opposition National Civic Crusade coalition, said today in a
telephone interview, ``The National Civic Crusade and other
opposition leaders are meeting to reach an agreement, with the
intention of carrying out a national strike.'' He declined to give
more details.
   Officials of the National University of Panama closed the school
and said it was to prevent disturbances. Secondary and primary
schools were out for vacation.
   Delvalle called his own ouster ``something legally despicable
that only fulfills a formality in the mind of those who want to
grasp power at any cost.''
   He urged a trade embargo against Panama but said he opposed U.S.
military intervention.
   Panama, with 2.2 million people, is headquarters for U.S.
military operations in Latin America.
   The U.S. Southern Command has 10,000 troops and 20,000
dependents in Panama. The U.S. garrison was on alert and told
Americans to keep a low profile during any unrest.
   The White House called for Noriega's resignation after his
indictment in Florida on Feb. 5. Delvalle's attempt to oust
Noriega, announced in a nationwide broadcast Thursday night,
received immediate backing from the United States.
   But Noriega and his supporters moved quickly.
   The National Assembly was called into session, although
opposition lawmakers in the 67-member legislature boycotted the 1
a.m. meeting. Both Delvalle and Vice President Roderick Esquivel
were removed from office.
   Noriega, who says he is innocent of all charges, did not comment
publicly on the events.
   Delvalle said of his opponents, ``They will not receive
acceptance from any country that takes pride in being democratic. I
continue to feel that I am president of the republic.''
   From his home, Delvalle said he asked Noriega to ``retire'' as
soon as the U.S. indictments were announced, but the general
refused.
   Defense Forces police chief Col. Leonidas Macias told Panamanian
television Thursday that no officer would replace the general.
   ``He (Delvalle) is going first,'' said Macias, flanked by senior
officers at the Defense Forces' central garrison.
   Delvalle said earlier that Col. Marcos Justines, the chief of
staff, would replace Noriega. Justines refused and told reporters:
``We have been conversing with him (Delvalle) constantly, and he
knows that our position has been that there is too much American
interference in this Panamanian affair.''
   In its resolution, the National Assembly said Delvalle violated
the law in removing Noriega and noted that Esquivel had abandoned
his post in September without resigning.
   The resolution said Delvalle mentioned U.S. charges against
Noriega ``with the object of permitting the intervention of the
government of the United States in the internal affairs of
Panama,'' damaging national sovereignty and endangering national
security.
   The U.S. indictments accuse Noriega of using his authority to
let Colombian drug traffickers use Panama as a base for smuggling
cocaine and marijuana into the United States. The charges said
Noriega received a healthy kickback from drug profits.
   Later, at his home, the president told The Associated Press,
that he ordered Noriega's dismissal ``for the health of this
country.''
   Roman Catholic Archbishop Marcos Gregorio McGrath arrived at the
house and pledged support for Delvalle.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Picks up 1st graf, a0627</HEAD>
