<1ST_LINE>r a AM-CarRadar     02-26 0194</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Car Radar,0202</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Back-Seat Driving Goes High Tech</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   California's ``Vehicle of the Future''
features a back-seat driver that not only nags but also is capable
of slamming on the brakes.
   A 1977 Dodge van equipped with an experimental radar-based
``collision-avoidance'' system was demonstrated Thursday at a
meeting of the Governor's Regional Transportation Management
Conference.
   The system has a grill-mounted radar dish and a computer under
the dashboard to warn the driver of approaching hazards.
   John Davis, the San Diego engineer who invented and sells the
system, took the van on a demonstration spin.
   ``Watch it! Watch!'' the computer voice snapped as he drove out
of the parking lot.
   ``Look out! Look out!'' it barked as he came too close to a car.
   ``Fall back! Fall back!'' it commanded before finally putting on
the brakes.
   The state has ordered six vehicles equipped with the system,
said interim Director Donald Watson of the state Transportation
Department.
   ``This system will enable more vehicles to move faster at closer
intervals and will substantially increase the capacity of our
highways,'' he said.
   The six experimental trucks and cars will cost about $250,000,
he said.
</TEXT>
