<DOCNO> AP880226-0116 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-26-88 1301EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w PM-Panama-Blandon     02-26 0477</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Panama-Blandon,460</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>With US-Panama Reax</HEAD>
<HEAD>Dissident Discloses Plan for Noriega's Ouster</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A leading Panamanian dissident said today that
ousted President Eric Arturo Delvalle knew in advance his effort to
fire military strongman Manuel Antonio Noriega would fail.
   But Jose I. Blandon, a former close associate of Noriega's, said
in an interview that Delvalle's bid to depose Noriega was but one
step in an 18-point plan that is designed to lead to Noriega's
ouster within three weeks.
   ``It is exactly what we thought was going to happen,'' Blandon
said, referring to Delvalle's attempt to replace Noriega with the
second-ranking officer in Panama's Defense Forces and Noriega's
decision to ignore the order.
   Early today, the Panamian legislature voted to remove Delvalle
from office and appointed a successor.
   Blandon said that he and about 10 other opposition leaders have
joined with Delvalle in putting together the plan over the last
several weeks.
   The next steps in the plan, Blandon said, include rallying broad
international support for Delvalle, a general strike in Panama and,
they hope, an embargo by the United States aimed at crippling
Panama's economy.
   These steps, Blandon said, ``will leave Noriega more isolated
than ever'' and force his eventual downfall.
   Blandon said his allies already have been in touch with
authorities in the Dominican Republic to determine whether they
would be willing to allow Noriega to enter the country if and when
he is forced out. He said Dominican officials have responded
positively to the proposal.
   One potential obstacle to Noriega's acquiescence to this
solution is the possibility of his arrest in the Dominican Republic
and his extradition to the United States based on federal drug
smuggling indictments against him, Blandon said.
   He said Delvalle raised last week with Assistant Secretary of
State Elliott Abrams the possibility of dropping the U.S.
indictments against Noriega. He said Abrams was unable to make any
such commitment and that a final decision on withdrawing the
indictments would have to be left either to the Justice Department
or President Reagan.
   In any case, Blandon said, the political and economic
circumstances in Panama are such that it is doubtful that Noriega
can survive much longer, especially if the United States and Latin
American countries close ranks behind Delvalle.
   Blandon spoke to a reporter at a local hotel where he is under
24-hour guard by U.S. marshals. He was a key witness earlier this
month in congressional hearings on Noriega's alleged drug smuggling
activities and his ties to the CIA.
   As he spoke, Blandon frequently referred to a folder outlining
the plan to end Noriega's domination of Panamanian politics and to
restore elected civilian rule to the country. The plan was dated
Feb. 22 but its contents had been agreed to weeks earlier by a
broad-based coalition of Panamanian opposition leaders, Blandon
said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
