<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Liverpool     02-26 0641</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Liverpool,0662</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>City In Rebirth, Liverpool Ready To Receive Modern Art</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GRAHAM HEATHCOTE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LIVERPOOL, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An abandoned rum warehouse has become
the latest symbol of rebirth in this port city that was founded on
cotton, famed for its Beatles and devastated by changing times.
   Contractors on Wednesday handed over the keys of the old
warehouse to Sir Alan Bowness, director of London's Tate Gallery.
   On May 24, Prince Charles, the heir to the throne, will come to
the building and open the ``Tate in the North,'' the first endeavor
by a state museum in Britain to show its works on a large scale
outside of London.
   A series of 10-month exhibitions will keep pictures and
sculpture circulating to Liverpool from the Tate's collection of
40,000 works of British and 20th century art.
   It is a bid to attract another 500,000 visitors a year to
Liverpool.
   First to be seen will be surrealist art, the works of American
abstract painter Mark Rothko and British sculpture of the past 20
years.
   ``Liverpool has had a hard time and it's trying to pull itself
up. I hope we can help, not least because I've always felt it was
unacceptable that the Tate should only be in London,'' Bowness told
The Associated Press.
   It will cost about $17.6 million to convert a warehouse in the
Albert Dock, completed in 1846, to a museum. The dock contains five
blocks of five-story, red-brick and cast-iron warehouses
surrounding a 7-acre ``courtyard'' of water.
   The dock area already has a maritime museum and shops. More
shops, restaurants and apartments are being created in the
warehouses, which have been empty since World War II when the dock
fell into disuse.
   Now the dock buildings are considered so valuable as
architectural history that they are state-protected, and Liverpool
Waterfront, stretching 1{ miles along the banks of the
one-mile-wide Mersey river, is being transformed from dereliction
into a major tourist area.
   ``More than 50 million pounds ($88 million) has already been
sunk into the waterfront and we are sure it is going to be a
spectacular success,'' said Diana Day, publicist for the Merseyside
Development Corp.
   Private industry has invested more than $315 million in other
Liverpool projects.
   Liverpool, with 600,000 people 210 miles northwest of London, is
beset by 20 percent unemployment and miles of decaying housing.
Fifteen million people live within one hour's drive from the city,
which was home to the rock group, the Beatles.
   ``Liverpool was once the second port in Britain after London and
the major port of Europe for the Atlantic,'' said Eric
Leatherbarrow, spokesman for Mersey Docks and Harbor Co.
   ``But when Britain joined the European Economic Community trade
tilted from here to southeast England, and containerization saw a
lot of the old shipping lines disappear.
   ``Now we are pulling up because European businessmen are
realizing that Liverpool is still the nearest major port to the
United States. Shipping companies are coming back and our cargo
throughput was up by 1 million tons a year to 11 million tons in
1987.''
   To generate interest for the new museum, ``The Tate in the
North'' has prepared charming and funny posters introducing
Liverpudlians to the world of modern art.
   One radio commercial features Picasso's ``Three Dancers.''
   A male voice explains the painting as follows:
   ``The bloke on the right was married to the woman on the left
who was having an affair with the bloke in the middle who was
obsessed with her, only she lost interest so he invited her to a
restaurant with some friends, they have a slap-up dinner, then he
pulls a gun, fires at her, she ducks, plays doggo, then he shot
himself.
   ``When his mother heard, she died of shock. You see, paintings
talk to you.''
   ``I don't hear nothing,'' a second voice replies.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
