<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Panama-Delvalle 2ndLd-Writethru a0597 02-26 0721</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Panama-Delvalle, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0597,0742</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ousted President Vows To Fight Removal</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE. pickup</NOTE>
<BYLINE>With PM-Panama, Bjt
^By REID G. MILLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eric Arturo Delvalle today insisted
he is still president of Panama and called for a worldwide trade
embargo against his nation and its de factor ruler, Gen. Manuel
Antonio Noriega.
   Delvalle, ousted by the National Assembly today after he tried
to fire Noriega, said a trade embargo would create economic chaos,
``but we all have to realize that a country has to suffer to rid
itself of a dictatorship.''
   He said he also he also supports U.S. congressional calls for a
halt to commercial airline flights and to free-zone banking
transactions between the United States and Panama, home of one of
the Western Hemisphere's largest banking centers.
   Delvalle spoke informally to reporters at his home, where he has
remained since he announced Thursday afternoon he was firing
Noriega.
   The assembly is dominated by a coalition of Noriega's supporters
and its brief, post-midnight session was boycotted by minority
opposition members.
   ``I am the president of Panama this morning,'' Delvalle
declared, his eyes baggy and red-rimmed from lack of sleep. ``There
is no doubt about it. There is no legal power in Panamanian laws or
the Constitution that allows the National Assembly'' to dismiss a
president.
   But asked how he intended to exercise the functions of the
presidency, Delvalle shrugged and replied with a tired smile:
``That's a good question.''
   He said he knew that his ``chances were slim'' in calling for
Noriega's departure because ``never has any president ousted the
commander of the Defense Forces in Panama in all our history. It
has always been the other way around.''
   Delvalle said he would take his case to the nation's Supreme
Court, ``where my chances are also very slim, because it also is
controlled by Gen. Noriega.''
   The Cabinet named Education Minister Manuel Solis Palma as the
new chief of state.
   Meanwhile, a coalition of business, professional, labor and
political organization known as the National Civic Crusade was
meeting to consider a call for a nationwide work stoppage.
   Delvalle said he would support ``an indefinite strike'' and
called ``the people of Panama to unite, all for one and one for
all, to struggle for the removal of Gen. Noriega.''
   He said that as soon as U.S. grand jury indictments charging
Noriega with drug trafficking were announced in Miami and Tampa,
Fla., earlier this month, he called Noriega and asked him to step
down.
   ``But he said he didn't think it was advisable.''
   ``I let him consider his answer for a couple of days and then
again I requested his own decision to retire, which he didn't
accept, and that's why I acted today (Thursday.)''
   In a telephone interview with ``CBS This Morning,'' Delvalle
said the United States had not pressured him to fire Noriega.
   Delvalle, 51, spent most of the evening huddled in a back room
with U.S. Ambassador Arthur Davis and his personal advisers.
   Between 30 and 40 people, most of them close friends, listened
to radio and television news reports at the Delvalle home and he
occasionally strolled out to chat with them.
   Asked about the naming of another president, Delvalle replied:
``I will fight it out, because there is no reason for me to be
removed from my position. I am acting within the laws and the
constistution of the country.''
   Asked what reaction he expected from the international
community, Delvalle said, ``The reaction of the international
community will be against the Defense Forces.''
   Asked if he had discussed Thursday's action with U.S. Assistant
Secretary of State Elliott Abrams while in Miami last week,
Delvalle said, ``No, not at all.''
   But Delvalle said he had a four-hour visit from Davis Thursday
evening and ``received State Department support ... stating that
they will back me and support my actions.''
   He said he did not fear for his safety.
   Delvalle had no political experience before he became vice
president in October 1984, after running for the Republic Party in
a coalition with five other parties.
   He was president and general manager of National Sugar, a sugar
producing and refining company owned by his family. He studied in
the United States.
   He and his wife Mariela Diaz have three children.
</TEXT>
