<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Waldheim 3rdLd-Writethru a0638 02-26 0675</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Waldheim, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0638,0697</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Waldheim Won't Speak at Anniversary of Nazi Annexation of Austria</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 9 grafs to UPDATE with praise from Socialists.
PICKS up 9th graf, `Austria is ...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN COSTELLOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A top Socialist minister today reversed
his decision to boycott a ceremony marking the 50th anniversary of
Nazi Germany's annexation of Austria after President Kurt Waldheim
dropped plans to speak during the event.
   Other Socialists hailed the decision of the president, who
served as a lieutenant in the German army during World War II.
   In a televised interview Thursday, Waldheim announced he would
not give a speech March 11. He said he would give a televised
speech March 10.
   In the interview, Waldheim also said he had considered quitting
the presidency but had rejected the idea.
   The announcement on the speech prompted Finance Minister
Ferdinand Lacina to reverse his decision to boycott the solemn
ceremony.
   Lacina, a Socialist, said Friday that a Waldheim speech would
have led to ``a renewed polarization'' among Austrians and
``criticism coming from other countries.''
   Heinz Fischer, a leader of the Socialist Party, said Waldheim's
decision to drop the speech ``will lead to an easing of tensions on
March 11.''
   Waldheim has been surrounded by controversy since March 1986,
when it was disclosed that he had served as a lieutenant with the
German army in the Balkans during World War II. The United States
and put him on a ``watch list'' of undesirable aliens, barring him
from entering the United States.
   In the interview Thursday, Waldheim said he had a ``clear
conscience'' and repeatedly insisted he did nothing wrong.
   Austria is governed by a coalition of Socialists and
conservatives. Waldheim is the ceremonial head of state.
   The head of the government, Chancellor Franz Vranitzky told
ABC-TV's ``Good Morning America'' today that it was up to Waldheim
to determine whether he should step down.
   The 69-year-old Waldheim said he will address the nation in a
televised broadcast on March 10, the eve of the ceremony marking
the Anschluss, when Austria was absorbed into the German Reich in
1938. Austria was liberated by the Allies in the spring of 1945.
   Waldheim opponents had promised to take to the streets in
protest if the president went ahead with the talk on March 11 in
the Hofburg Palace.
   Several leading Austrian politicians said a Waldheim speech was
not the way to lead the country into reflecting on its Nazi past.
   There have been calls for Waldheim's resignation since March
1986, when Austrian and U.S. media and the World Jewish Congress
reported that he served as a lieutenant with the Germany army in
the occupied Balkans during World War II.
   The calls intensified after an international historians'
commission issued a critical report earlier this month, which left
open the question of whether he was guilty of war crimes.
   ``If I thought I had done anything false or anything wrong, then
I would have taken the consequences,'' Waldheim said.
   In the controversy over Waldheim's past, ``taking the
consequences'' has come to be synonymous with resignation.
Waldheim's term is scheduled to end in 1992.
   Waldheim was asked if he had considered quitting.
   ``Naturally I thought of it,'' he said. ``Otherwise I wouldn't
be a human being. I'd have to be a piece of wood.''
   But he firmly rejected any notion of stepping down. ``My
resignation would only make things worse,'' he said.
   Waldheim's decision not to speak at the Anschluss commemoration
dominated the front pages of newspapers today.
   ``Waldheim Cancels the Speech at the Remembrance Ceremony,''
said the Salzburger Nachrichten. The conservative newspaper has
strongly criticized Waldheim for his handling of his wartime past.
   Vienna's Kurier tabloid, which also has criticized Waldheim,
focused on conciliatory remarks he made in the interview.
   ``Waldheim: I Apologize for the Misunderstandings,'' the Kurier
newspaper said in a banner headline.
   The March 11 speech originally had been planned as a way to
avoid a political showdown over whether Waldheim would address a
joint session of Parliament to mark Anschluss.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
