<1ST_LINE>r a AM-DapperBandit     02-26 0307</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dapper Bandit,0315</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dapper Bandit Strikes Two Banks In One Day To Bring 10-Year Toll
To 24</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ARLINGTON, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man dubbed the ``Dapper Bandit,''
disguised with sunglasses, wig and fake mustache, robbed two banks
in one day to bring his 10-year total in Texas to 24, authorities
said.
   In one robbery, the man disarmed an off-duty police officer
working as a guard and escaped with the officer's pistol, police
said.
   Officials would not disclose the amount taken in the robberies
Thursday, which came four hours and two miles apart. The
well-dresssed robber had been idle since striking a bank in east
Dallas last September.
   In addition to the usual disguise, the well-dressed bandit has
been known to wear bandages on his face. He has been photographed
numerous times by bank cameras and a $25,000 reward has been
posted, but there have been no significant leads, police say.
   The first robbery occurred at First RepublicBank, said Arlington
police spokesman Dee Anderson.
   ``We had an off-duty uniformed officer there working security,''
he said. ``He was approached by the suspect, who pulled a gun and
ordered him to drop his weapon.''
   After picking up officer Eddie Bell's pistol, the bandit,
wearing a gray suit and maroon tie, leaped over the tellers'
counter and scooped up money from cash trays, Anderson said.
   Bell slipped outside and told passers-by to call police. He ran
back in time to see the bandit jump into a car and leave, Anderson
said.
   In the second robbery, at Landmark Bank, the robber pulled a
pistol from a leather briefcase, walked around the tellers' counter
and took money from both tellers' drawers, Anderson said. He fled
out a back door and drove away in a different car.
   Police recovered both getaway cars, both of which had been
stolen in nearby Irving, Anderson said.
</TEXT>
