<1ST_LINE>r a AM-CostaDivorce     02-26 0301</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Costa Divorce,0312</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Brink's Robbery Gang Member Seeks Divorce</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BROCKTON, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A member of the 1950 Brink's robbery gang
who seeking a divorce says his wife can have their house, built on
land he purchased with some of his share of the $1.2 million heist.
   Vincent Costa, 74, told Brockton Probate Court Judge Summer Z.
Kaplan that he bought the land for $1,800 on Nov. 10, 1950.
   When asked by his lawyer where he got the money, Costa replied,
``I got it from the Brink's case.''
   Costa, one of the two surviving members of the 11-member gang,
told the judge his share amounted to about $100,000. A son cheated
him out of most of it, he said.
   The Jan. 17, 1950, robbery of the Brink's counting house in
Boston's North End was then the largest in U.S. history. None of
the money was ever recovered.
   Two of the 11 men involved in the robbery two died before the
FBI solved the case in 1956. The remaining nine were sentenced to
life in prison, but had their sentences commuted after serving
various terms.
   Costa didn't admit his involvement until May 1977, when he and
another participant held a news conference to publicize a book and
a movie about the robbery.
   Costa told the judge this week he wants his wife of 54 years,
Nancy, 76, to spend her remaining years in the home. But, he said,
he or his estate would be entitled to half of the proceeds whenever
the house is sold.
   The house, now valued at $125,000, is the couple's only asset,
her lawyer said.
   Mrs. Costa testified she is a devout Roman Catholic and doesn't
believe in divorce but said she won't oppose it. The couple, both
of whom have serious medical problems, have five children.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
