<FILEID>AP-NR-02-26-88 1402EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w PM-US-Delvalle     02-26 0365</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-US-Delvalle,360</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>With US-Panama Reax</HEAD>
<HEAD>US Continues to Recognize Delvalle as President of Panama</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HENRY GOTTLIEB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States said today it continues to
recognize Eric Arturo Delvalle as president of Panama, even after a
parliamentary vote to oust him.
   State Department spokeswoman Phyllis Oakley, reiterating what
she termed ``our support for the supremacy of civilian
constitutional rule,'' said ``we continue to recognize President
Delvalle as the president of Panama.''
   Asked to describe the legal grounds for such recognition, she
said, ``I don't think it's for us to interpret their constitutional
law. We had regarded him as the president, we still regard him as
the president.''
   She described the situation among Panamanian political figures
as one of ``a great deal of political maneuvering.''
   She said Delvalle's decision to fire Manuel Antonio Noriega as
the nation's defense chief _ which precipated Delvalle's ouster by
the assembly _ ``took great courage and we continue with our
policy.''
   The spokeswoman said Delvalle made the decision on his own,
though she acknowledged that U.S. officials were in close contact
with him. She declined to reveal the substance of the discussions.
   Mrs. Oakley also said the United States continues to recognize
Juan B. Sosa as Panama's ambassador in Washington. Sosa has
supported Delvalle.
   ``I informed the state department that I will continue with
him,'' Sosa said, referring to his support for Delvalle.
   ``I'm sure they will try to send another ambassador,'' he said,
adding that he had asked for continued recognition by the U.S.
government.
   Mrs. Oakley said Elliot Abrams, the assistant secretary of state
for Inter-American affairs, met with Sosa this morning, but she
wouldn't reveal details of the discussion.
   ``Many people knew that we had been aware of the actions that
President Delvalle was contemplating doing,'' she said. ``We had
been informed that the decision was President Delvalle's own to
make.''
   ``I'm not going to get into who was behind what; who said
what,'' she said. ``This is obviously an unstable period,
confused.''
   ``The situation there obviously has to clarify,'' she said.
   Asked if the United States had been in contact with Noriega, she
said, ``not that I'm aware of.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
