<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Poland-Church     02-26 0468</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Poland-Church,0483</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Polish Bishops Urge More Rights For Private Enterprise, Unions</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHARLES J. GANS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's Roman Catholic bishops on
Friday said time was running out for communist authorities to bring
sweeping economic and political reforms to Poland.
   Among the reforms they called for are constitutional guarantees
for private enterprise and the right of workers to form independent
trade unions.
   The bishops also said they viewed with ``seriousness and
concern'' the impact of price hikes imposed by the government
earlier this month. They said authorities must protect pensioners,
invalids and poor families from ``further impoverishment.''
   The bishops made their remarks in a communique released after a
two-day meeting of the Polish episcopate in Warsaw presided over by
the Polish primate, Cardinal Jozef Glemp.
   The communique reflected growing concern within the influential
church about the authorities' slow pace in introducing political
and economic reforms announced last fall.
   The bishops quoted extensively from the recent encyclical issued
by Pope John Paul II on social action.
   They cited passages saying that the development and well-being
of nations depends on guaranteeing the right to undertake economic
initiatives at the expense of bureaucratic state apparatuses,
respecting human rights including the freedom to set up trade
unions, and reforming unjust political institutions.
   Glemp, in a pastoral letter read aloud in the nation's churches
Feb. 21, said the many ``shortcomings'' in Poland's economic system
had embittered and discouraged people, while the government's
economic recovery program seemed ``incomprehensible'' and
``inconsistent'' to many Poles.
   The bishops said there had been many official announcements
about introducing reforms aimed at allowing more political and
economic initiatives. But they had remained ``in the sphere of
declarations and discussions.''
   ``Administrative practice often goes in the opposite direction,
setting a dam for various economic and social initiatives,'' the
bishops said. ``Time is running out.''
   ``It is only acts that can convince the society about the real
wish of reforms in the economic, social and political life,'' they
said. ``Without them there is a danger of deepening the crisis in
our country.''
   The bishops said the authorities should make it easier for
individuals to set up their own businesses, grant more economic
decision-making powers to local governments, and reject ``political
criteria'' in the selection of managerial personnel.
   ``It is necessary to widen the role of the private sector in the
national economy,'' the bishops said.
   They added that the economic reforms should be accompanied by
``wide reforms ... allowing (the society) to organize independent
social associations and workers' representations.''
   The government has said its political and economic reform
programs advocate many of the same goals supported by the bishops.
   The outlawed Solidarity labor union has called the reforms
inadequate because they fail to loosen the Communist Party's grip
on economic and political decision-making powers.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880226-0132 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-26-88 1408EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w PM-US-PanamaReax 6thLd-Writethru a0655 02-26 0908</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-US-Panama Reax, 6th Ld-Writethru, a0655,920</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New material, editing thruout</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRISCOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan said today the United States
does not plan any military intervention in Panama and the State
Department reaffirmed U.S. support for that nation's embattled
president.
   At the White House, Reagan was asked about the governmental
crisis in Panama, where President Eric Arturo Delvalle failed in
his attempt to oust Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega, the country's
strongman, and was in turn dismissed himself.
   ``There are some limits on what we can do, but we are looking at
the situation to see if there is anything we can do,'' the
president said.
   When asked if military intervention was planned, he said, ``No,
I don't think that's the answer.''
   ``We are not prepared to come up with any answer yet,'' Reagan
added.
   When he was asked whether he thought the 10,000 or so U.S.
troops in Panama were in danger, the president replied, ``No, I do
not. I don't think there is any appetite on the part of anyone
there, including Mr. Noriega, to take on our troops.''
   Separately, the State Department said it continues to recognize
Devalle as Panama's president despite an early-morning
parliamentary vote to oust him.
   Department spokeswoman Phyllis Oakley reiterated what she termed
``our support for the supremacy of civilian constitutiona rule,''
and said, ``We continue to recognize President Delvalle as the
president.''
   Asked to describe the legal grounds for such recognition, she
said, ``I don't think it's for us to interpret their constitutional
law. We had regarded him as the president, we still regard him as
the president.''
   In other developments:
   _Panama's ambassador to the United States, Juan Sosa, an ally of
Delvalle, said he had informed the State Department he would stay
on, at least for the time being, despite a call from Noriega
telling Sosa he would be replaced.
   Mrs. Oakley said the United States does, indeed, continue to
recognize Sosa.
   _Vice President George Bush said in South Carolina that the
United States should do ``whatever is necessary, including military
force'' to protect American interests.
   Bush stopped short of calling for military intervention, saying
the United States' history of intervention in Latin American
affairs is ``what's hurting us in some areas now.''
   During a presidential campaign visit to South Carolina, he said,
``We will do whatever is necessary to protect American interests in
Panama. We've got treaty interests on the (Panama) canal. I don't
want to rattle any sabers. ...''
   _Defense Secretary Frank Carlucci, interviewed on a U.S.
Information Agency program, also said that ``it would be premature
at this time'' to discuss an American military move.
   _Jose I. Blandon, a former Noriega ally but now a leading
Panamanian dissident, predicted that Noriega would be out of power
within three weeks and said Delvalle's allies have already asked
the Dominican Republic if it would let Noriega live there if and
when he is forced out.
   He said Dominican officials have responded positively to the
proposal.
   Reagan said the United States did not instigate Delvalle's
action, but had been ``very much aware of it.''
   When asked whether the United States still wants Noriega to
stand trial on drug trafficking charges on which he was indicted by
a federal grand jury in Miami, the president said, ``I assume so.''
   Presidential spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said earlier that
Delvalle had consulted with American officials at the U.S. Embassy
in Panama City.
   ``We have had discussions with Delvalle over the past several
days. We assured him of our position, which is that we would like
to see a peaceful transition to civilian rule,'' the spokesman said.
   Asked whether the United States had encouraged Delvalle to
dismiss Noriega, who has been indicted by a federal grand jury in
this country on charges of drug trafficking, presidential spokesman
Marlin Fitzwater replied:
   ``I can't elaborate on any of the specific conversations. We did
not urge him to take this action. He did it on his own. ...
   ``We have a precarious position. Yes, we want him (Noriega) to
stand trial. Yes, we want a civilian government in Panama. Yet, we
want to be careful not to unduly intrude upon the affairs of
Panama.''
   Another U.S. official, speaking on condition of anonymity, said
the United States would ``take steps'' if Americans are endangered
in Panama.
   Meanwhile, Sen. Jesse Helms, R-N.C., a leading Noriega critic,
said, ``Panamanians will take care of that themselves. Just wait
and see what happens if and when the United States takes a
flatfooted stand and tells the Panamanian president, we're with you
and we're against him,'' Helms said.
   He said of Noreiga: ``He's a bum; he ought to be thrown out.''
   Sen. Alfonse D'Amato, R-N.Y., proposed a trade embargo against
the government under the control of military strongman Manuel
Noriega and called for U.S. troops to be put on full alert to
protect the Panama Canal and 50,000 U.S. citizens in the country.
   Fitzwater said no consideration is being given to a trade
embargo.
   Delvalle, in a telephone interview with ``CBS This Morning,''
indicated he still considers himself president and urged a U.S.
trade embargo against his country as ``the only way that we can get
rid of the dictators of the Americas'' but said he saw no reason
for military intervention.
   The Reagan administration on Thursday voiced ``unqualified
support for civilian constitutional rule'' in Panama after Delvalle
tried to fire Noriega as military chief.
</TEXT>
