<FILEID>AP-NR-02-26-88 1408EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Bush     02-26 0640</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bush,650</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Tells Robertson to `Prove It'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GREENVILLE, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   George Bush said Friday that Republican
presidential rival Pat Robertson should produce evidence to back up
rash allegations that the vice president said were ``scaring the
American people.''
   Bush, in a forceful response to the former television
evangelist, recounted several allegations that Robertson has made
against Bush and his Republican presidential campaign.
   Of each he demanded, ``prove it.''
   Bush made the remarks in an address to state newspaper editors.
He was less direct about Robertson moments later in a private
meeting with about two dozen fundamentalist church leaders but told
them ``I believe in Jesus Christ as my personal savior.''
   ``I don't like to feel there's a monolith out there'' that will
back just one candidate for president, he said.
   Bush and Robertson have both targeted South Carolina as a
crucial battleground in their White House bids, with Robertson
saying he must win the March 5 primary.
   A group of 21 congressmen supporting Bush flew into South
Carolina to spend the day campaigning for him as the vice president
departed for Atlanta after a two-day campaign swing here. Appearing
with the congressmen, who donned white baseball-style caps bearing
the words ``Bush '88,'' the vice president said, ``These guys can
talk Southern.''
   South Carolina holds its GOP primary just three days before the
rest of the South votes, and Bush forces hope a win here will be a
indicator of the Super Tuesday vote that follows, when one-third of
the GOP delegates are at stake.
   Answering questions from the South Carolina Press Association,
Bush was asked about Robertson's charges in the state earlier in
the week that the Bush campaign had engaged in ``sleazy''
campaigning and ``dirty tricks'' against the Robertson campaign. He
also was asked about Robertson's suggestion that Bush aides
engineered the release of information about the sex scandal
involving evangelist Jimmy Swaggart to embarrass Robertson.
   ``No,'' Bush said. ``If you make such an allegation, the
American sense of fair play says, prove it.''
   ``I have something to do with arranging for the Assembly of God
(church) to bring out information two weeks before the South
Carolina primary?'' Bush asked, referring to the Swaggart charge.
``Forgive me. Prove it. That's all I say.''
   Bush asked why his questioner was smiling, saying the nature of
the allegations by Robertson were serious. In recounting them, Bush
included Robertson's claim in a debate in New Hampshire two weeks
ago that nuclear missiles are hidden in Cuba.
   ``If you think there's Cuban missiles _ scaring the American
people _ what's your facts?'' Bush said.
   He also cited Robertson's claim in backing out of a debate in
Dallas last week that questions had been leaked in advance and the
audience was stacked against him. ``Prove it,'' Bush said.
   Bush told the church leaders he had ``respect for life'' and had
been frustrated by the administration's lack of success in
supporting prayer in public schools.
   ``I know we're pluralistic. I also know we're one nation under
God. I feel strongly about that,'' Bush said. ``... I would not be
afraid of asking God's help.''
   Before the editors, Bush cited the developments in Panama and
said the United States would use military force if necessary to
protect U.S. interests in Panama following strongman Gen. Manuel
Antonio Noriega's removal of the nation's president.
   ``Noriega's gone bad, and he's proven he's trafficked in
narcotics,'' Bush said. ``... Noriega should go and in my view he
will go.''
   Bush referred to the American hostages in Lebanon and said a
problem in helping recover them has been that ``many of our sources
(in Lebanon) dried up because of the excessive publicity and
exposure'' of the CIA in the 1970s. ``That's hurt us very, very
badly,'' the former CIA director said.
</TEXT>
