<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Waldheim     02-26 0360</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Waldheim,0369</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Political Leaders Welcome Waldheim Decision</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROLAND PRINZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Politicians said Friday that Kurt
Waldheim's decision not to address the main ceremony will ease
tensions when Austria marks the 50th anniversary of the Anschluss
that made it part of Nazi Germany.
   Two Socialist members of the Cabinet had said they wouldn't
attend the ceremony March ll and two others said they also might
stay away if the president spoke.
   Socialist Party leaders have said it would be inappropriate for
Waldheim, who faces unresolved accusations of war crimes, to lead
the nation in remembering atrocities of the Nazi past. The party is
the senior partner in Austria's governing coalition.
   Waldheim announced Thursday that he was canceling the speech,
and said in a television interview later: ``I thought that with
this decision, which was my own initiative I might add, I would
contribute to the orderly carrying out of the solemn ceremony.''
   Heinz Fischer, Socialist floor leader in Parliament, said Friday
that Waldheim's decision ``will lead to an easing of tension on
March 11'' and it ``certainly was the most reasonable thing'' to do.
   Finance Minister Ferdinand Lacina, also a Socialist, withdrew
his decision to boycott the March 11 ceremony.
   In the television interview, Waldheim repeated his intention to
remain in the presidency, which is largely ceremonial, and insisted
that resigning would make matters worse.
   He also repeated criticism of a report on his wartime activities
by an international panel of historians, declaring it ``full of
contradictions'' and errneous presumptions.
   Waldhim concealed his World War II service as a German army
lieutenant in the Balkans until accusations arose during the
presidential campaign in 1986 that he had committed war crimes.
   The United States put the former U.N. secretary-general on a
``watch list'' of undesirable aliens last year, and in September
the government appointed the historians at Waldheim's request.
   They said in their report this month that Waldheim was ``in
close proximity'' to atrocities, knew of them and did not try to
prevent them. The historians said they found no proof that he
committed war crimes, but left the question of personal guilt open.
</TEXT>
