<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Obit-Cox     02-26 0388</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Obit-Cox,0401</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Outspoken Federal Judge Dead at Age 87</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Note contents.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>JACKSON, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   William Harold Cox, a federal judge who
enraged civil rights advocates with his remarks about blacks but
presided over a 1967 trial that convicted eight Klansmen of
murdering three civil rights workers, has died at the age of 87.
   Cox died of natural causes Thursday night at his home here, a
family spokesman said.
   ``He was a real colorful and effective-type judge who was his
own man,'' former Gov. Bill Waller said of Cox. ``He was strictly
independent in interpreting the law and in carrying out court
proceedings as he wanted to do it. He left his mark on the
judiciary of our state.''
   Gov. Ray Mabus agreed, saying Cox ``had an impact on
Mississippi.''
   Cox, the son of a Sunflower County sheriff, built a successful
practice in corporate and civil law before he became a U.S.
District Court judge in 1961. He was an active judge until July
1983.
   In the course of his judicial career, Cox was attacked by the
National Assocation for the Advancement of Colored People and
others for his remarks about blacks, segregation and civil rights.
   During a hearing on a voter discrimination suit in 1964, Cox
said: ``I don't know who is telling these Negroes they can push
people around just by getting into a line and acting like a bunch
of chimpanzees.''
   The remark triggered a demand for his impeachment by U.S. Sen.
Jacob Javits, R-N.Y., and U.S. Rep. Peter Rodino, D-N.J., but there
never was an impeachment proceeding.
   Cox also disdained the Civil Rights Act of 1964 and said in
court, ``I don't know anybody down here who don't oppose it.''
   When a civil rights attorney complained in 1971 that a
decades-old mural behind the bench depicted blacks as serfs to
white people, Cox retorted loudly, ``Well, it will remain in this
court whether you like it or not.''
   In 1967, Cox presided over one of the most famous cases of the
decade _ the trial of eight Klansmen charged in the 1964 murders of
three civil rights workers in Philadelphia, Miss.
   After the jury seemed deadlocked for two days, Cox ordered them
to come up with a verdict. The jury found the eight Klansmen guilty.
   Survivors include a son and a daughter.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880226-0144 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-26-88 1437EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-CubanDeportations     02-26 0269</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cuban Deportations,0278</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Immigration Official: Any Cuban Criminal Can Be Deported</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cuban immigrants who commit crimes in the United
States can be shipped back to their homeland, even if they have
obtained U.S. citizenship, a top Immigration and Naturalization
Service official said.
   The U.S.-Cuban immigration agreement reached in November does
not limit those eligible for deportation to the 2,500 Cuban
detainees in federal prisons, INS commissioner Alan Nelson said
Thursday.
   His comments appeared in Friday's editions of The Miami Herald.
   Nelson attended an academic conference in Washington, D.C.,
examining the 1980 Mariel boatlift of Cubans to the United States
and the status of Cuban detainees in U.S. prisons.
   ``Any Cuban who commits a crime, whether he is a resident or
citizen of the United States, and if the law so sees fit, can be
deported,'' Nelson said.
   Advocates for Cuban prisoners immediately criticized Nelson's
statements.
   ``Cuban deportation and what Nelson is doing, representing the
government's politics, is scandalous and truly unjustifiable,''
said Steven Donziger, a member of the Cuban Detainees Support
Coalition in Atlanta.
   The immigration pact with Cuba allows the deportation of 2,500
Mariel detainees who have committed crimes in the United States. In
turn, the United States agreed to allow about 20,000 Cubans and
3,000 political prisoners to immigrate every year.
   News of the agreement triggered riots by Cuban detainees at
prisons in Atlanta and Oakdale, La.
   The pact was aimed at normalizing immigration, Nelson said.
   ``There would be no purpose in sending 2,500 refugees back now
and not be able to deport anyone else in the future for committing
crimes,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
