<1ST_LINE>r w AM-SugarbeetFarms     02-26 0423</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sugarbeet Farms,410</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sugarbeet Costs Low in Midwest, High in West</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A new study shows that sugarbeet production
costs in 1984 were lowest in the Midwest and highest in some
western areas, the Agriculture Department said Friday.
   The study involved seven regions that produce nearly all the
U.S. sugarbeets. About 8,700 farms produce beets in the seven
regions. Overall, the department's Economic Research Service
reported that it cost an average of $30.30 per net ton to produce
beets. The range, however, was between $24 and $35 per ton.
   ``About 60 percent of the 1984 U.S. sugarbeet crop was produced
at a cost below the U.S. average price support of $31.63 per ton,''
the report said. ``The producers received a weighted average price
of $33.90 a net ton, ranging from $23.30 in Region 3 (Colorado,
Nebraska and southeastern Wyoming) to $37.10 in Region 6 (eastern
Idaho).''
   Most beet producers in Region 3 operated at a loss because of
the closing of several processing plants by the Great Western Sugar
Co., the report said.
   The study of 1984 costs, by region, showed:
   _Region 1, Michigan and Ohio, 10.8 percent of the U.S. sugarbeet
acreage; government support of $27.79 per net ton; actual price
received by growers, $32.95 per ton; average cost of production,
$24.02 per ton.
   _Region 2, Minnesota and eastern North Dakota, 35.2 percent of
the U.S. acreage; support of $32.24 per ton; actual price received
by growers, $36 per ton; average cost of production, $25.66 per ton.
   _Region 3, Colorado, Nebraska and souteastern Wyoming, 12.8
percent of the acreage; support of $31.23 per ton; actual price
received by growers, $23.30 per ton; average cost of production,
$28.06 per ton.
   _Region 4, New Mexico and Texas, was not included in the study.
   _Region 5, Montana, northwestern Wyoming and northwestern North
Dakota, 5 percent of the acreage; support of $31.37 per ton; actual
price received by growers, $35.40 per ton; average cost of
production, $34.26 per ton.
   _Region 6, eastern Idaho, 7.4 percent of the acreage; support of
$31.05 per ton; actual price received by growers, $37.10 per ton;
average cost of production, $34.87 per ton.
   _Region 7, western Idaho and Oregon, 6.5 percent of the acreage;
support of $31.05 per ton; actual price received by growers, $36.90
per ton; average cost of production, $34.68 per ton.
   _Region 8, California, 18.8 percent of the acreage; support of
$32.98 per ton; actual price received by growers, $35.10 per ton;
average cost of production, $34.57 per ton.
</TEXT>
