<1ST_LINE>r a AM-RunawayBus     02-26 0179</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Runaway Bus,0184</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Innocent Pleas For Driver on Misdemeanor Manslaughter Counts</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A plea of innocent to three misdemeanor
counts of vehicular manslaughter was entered Friday for the driver
of a runaway bus that killed three people and injured 15.
   Salvador Orogo was at the wheel of a commuter bus on Jan. 19
when it pulled out of a terminal during rush hour and plowed
through a crosswalk filled with pedestrians.
   Defense attorney Gilbert Eisenberg entered the pleas for Orogo,
53, who was not in court. He is free on $10,000 bail.
   Orogo surrendered Thursday after an arrest warrant was issued.
District Attorney Arlo Smith said charges were filed when ``it was
determined that the cause of the incident was negligent operation
of the bus by Orogo.''
   Orogo said after the crash that his accelerator had jammed and
his brakes had failed, but investigators said the bus showed no
mechanical defects.
   Authorities said there was no justification for felony charges
in the case because there was no allegation that alcohol or drugs
played a role.
</TEXT>
