<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Dukakis     02-26 0497</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dukakis,490</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Jabs at Gephardt, But Only Gingerly</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID ESPO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AUSTIN, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Dukakis jabbed gingerly at Richard
Gephardt on trade and taxes Friday, saying the 1981 tax cut his
Democratic presidential rival voted for was ``one of the biggest
mistakes in recent American history.''
   Dukakis refrained from directly attacking Gephardt as he pressed
his campaign for Southern support in the multi-state primaries and
caucuses on March 8.
   ``No culprits,'' the Massachusetts governor said with a smile
after delivering his speech to an overflow crowd at the Lyndon
Johnson School of Public Affairs without uttering Gephardt's name.
``Just good, strong, positive efforts to get this country moving
again.''
   Dukakis devoted much of his speech to his campaign message of
``good jobs and real opportunity'' for all, with special emphasis
on the need for education and research. ``It's going to take hard
workers, not high rollers, to get America moving again,'' he said.
   He spoke as he moved through a three-day Southern swing in
advance of the March 8 primaries, most of which will be in Southern
or border states. Aides said he has begun airing television
commercials in targeted areas of Florida and Texas, as well as in
the Baltimore area.
   If Gephardt's name was not mentioned, Dukakis' meaning was clear
when he said in his speech that ``building walls around America''
was a mistake. ``We tried that 60 years ago and it gave us the
worst depression in our history,'' he said.
   Gephardt favors trade legislation that would give the president
authority to retaliate against trading partners that failed to open
up their markets.
   The Missouri congressman also voted for the 1981 Reaganomics tax
cut, which passed with substantial help from Southern Democrats in
the House.
   ``In seven years that one mistake transformed our nation from
the world's largest creditor into the world's largest debtor,''
Dukakis said.
   ``Reaganomics isn't an economic theory; it's theft from our
children,'' he said. ``It's a felony against the future and it has
played the hard-working, tax-paying families of middle America for
fools.''
   The governor's speech reflected at least a temporary decision to
remain above the fray in an increasingly fierce rhetorical battle.
Gephardt sharply attacked Dukakis earlier this week and the
governor said on Thursday his rival ``better watch out'' if he
persisted.
   In his speech, Dukakis said he has no ``Southern strategy'' for
the primaries on March 8. ``The people of Texas and Florida and
Virginia aren't voting for a Zip code. They're voting for a
president of the United States,'' he said.
   But at the same time the Massachusetts governor sought to
re-establish a political bond created 28 years ago when John
Kennedy and Lyndon Johnson were on the winning ticket in the
national election.
   ``Together, John Kennedy and Lyndon Johnson inspired a whole
generation,'' he said. ``Ten months ago, in the spirit of JFK and
LBJ, we launched a campaign for the future of America.''
</TEXT>
