<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SouthAfrica 2ndLd-Writethru a0718 02-26 0630</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-South Africa, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0718,0643</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>14 Women Arrested For Protesting As Crackdown Continues</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 1st graf to CORRECT that Cachalia was last high-ranking
UDF official operating freely, sted not in hiding.
^By DAVID CRARY</NOTE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police on Friday arrested 14
white women protesting the crackdown on black opposition groups,
and authorities silenced the last high-ranking United Democratic
Front official who was operating freely.
   At the University of Cape Town, 2,000 students and staff
assembled to denounce the government's bans on political activity
by the UDF, the country's largest anti-apartheid coalition, and 17
other groups.
   ``The battle has only just begun,'' said the Rev. Allan Boesak,
one of the UDF's founders, at the campus rally. ``We have decided
we will resist. Our commitment starts right now.''
   The 14 members of Black Sash civil rights group were arrested as
they carried placards in Durban. They were taken to police
headquarters, told they were being charged with participating in
illegal gathering, then released.
   Azhar Cachalia, treasurer of the United Democratic Front, was
served with a restriction order prohibiting him from speaking to
the press, publishing any statement or participating in activities
of the UDF or other anti-apartheid organizations.
   Cachalia had been the only UDF executive committee member not in
hiding, in custody or restricted from UDF activities. The
5-year-old coalition has 600 affiliates with about 2 million
members.
   The government Wednesday banned the UDF and 17 other opposition
groups from political activity, and issued restrictive orders
against 18 senior black leaders, including UDF co-presidents Archie
Gumede and Albertina Sisulu.
   Also on Friday, the Pietermaritzburg Chamber of Commerce met
with Law and Order Minister Adriaan Vlok to discuss the feuding
between UDF supporters and members of the Zulu political
organization, Inkatha. More than 400 people have been killed in the
past year in fighting between the groups for control of black areas
in Natal province.
   With the UDF banned from all activity, and its leaders
restricted, observers predicted the violence would continue and
Inkatha would have an advantage.
   Chamber of Commerce manager Paul van Uytrecht was quoted Friday
as saying that peace talks sponsored by his group could not proceed.
   Inkatha, with an estimated 1.5 million members, was not affected
by the new bans.
   The KwaZulu homeland assembly, headed by Inkatha President
Mangosuthu Buthelezi, condemned the restrictions. But at the same
time, it asked the government to give the homeland's pro-Inkatha
police force jurisdiction over all Natal townships.
   The Weekly Mail, a newspaper the government has threatened with
closure, quoted an unidentified UDF representative Friday as saying
the crackdown ``simply gives Buthelezi a free hand to gain control
of the whole of Natal.''
   Musa Zondi, an Inkatha delegate at the Chamber of Commerce peace
talks, said the restrictions ``dash all hopes for the talks. The
UDF is a crucial element in the search for peace.''
   Police said three blacks were killed in violence in Natal late
Thursday, but gave no details.
   At the KTC squatter camp near Cape Town, rival black factions
shot at each other and burned shacks early Friday, resulting in at
least one death and five injuries, police and witnesses said.
   The fighting was between militant youths and the squatter camp
management committee, both considered anti-apartheid groups. About
20 shacks were burned during the battle.
   The fighting in the camp began last month, and hundreds of
shacks have been burned. In 1986, 70,000 people in the area lost
their homes and scores of people died in battles between
conservative ``vigilantes'' and the squatter-camp groups.
   This year the fighting is between two groups who fought together
against the ``vigilantes'' in 1986, and appears to involve an
attempt by the militant youths to gain more power in the
administration of the squatter camp.
</TEXT>
