<FILEID>AP-NR-02-26-88 1527EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Shultz-Israel Bjt   02-26 0753</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Shultz-Israel, Bjt,0774</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Shamir Asks Shultz to Go Slowly; Palestinians Boycott Meeting</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto JRL5</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir urged Secretary
of State George Shultz to move slowly on Palestinian self-rule, and
15 prominent Arabs didn't show up for a meeting Friday night to
which Shultz had invited them.
   Shultz went to a hotel in Arab east Jerusalem, stood in the
floodlit courtyard and read a statement suggesting the Palestinians
were fearful of working with the United States.
   ``Peacemaking is difficult,'' he read. ``Peace has its enemies,
but peace is a necessary ingredient to a decent life. Even small
steps toward peace can be significant in moving beyond distrust and
hatred.''
   Shultz is here pursuing new American proposals for Middle East
peace.
   The no-show was not new for him. A group of Palestinians also
refused to meet him in Jerusalem during a visit last October.
   In the statement he read Friday night against a backdrop of
Moslem evening prayers in the distance, Shultz still pursued the
goal of bringing Palestinians into Middle East peace talks.
   ``Opportunity knocks loudly on your door,'' he read out in the
hotel courtyard. ``Now is the time to get to work. We have a
workable plan, and we are ready to commit our efforts to it. The
time is right, together, to make decisions of historic
proportions.''
   Earlier Friday, several Palestinians issued statements saying
they would not attend the meeting. The Palestine Liberation
Organization had told Palestinians from the West Bank and Gaza
Strip, where riots began more than 11 weeks ago, not to meet with
Shultz in Jerusalem.
   ``Mr. Shultz seems to be trying to make a political statement by
insisting on a meeting here: that the Palestinian problem is in the
context of civil, religious and perhaps economic rights,'' said
Sari Nusseibeh, a professor at Bir Zeit University in the West Bank.
   ``By saying I will not attend, I'm saying this is wrong. The
problem is one of the national rights of the Palestinians.''
   Hanna Siniora, editor of the newspaper Al Fajr, said he told
Shultz ``I regret I cannot accept because the Palestinian people
have decided that we have to have a delegation reflecting the true
composition of the Palestinian people.'' Siniora conferred with the
secretary earlier this month in Washington.
   Shultz met on Friday with the three principal members of
Israel's coalition government _ Shamir, Foreign Minister Shimon
Peres and Defense Minister Yitzhak Rabin.
   He put ``no pressure whatsoever on Shamir,'' an Israeli official
said, on condition of anonymity. The official said Shamir urged
Shultz to move slowly on self-rule in the West Bank and Gaza Strip.
   During a two-hour meeting, Shamir told Shultz there should be
``a time of testing'' of up to three years before negotiations on a
final settlement in the occupied territories, the official said.
The American plan calls for negotiaitons on an overall settlement
by December.
   The attempt by Shamir to keep alive the 1978 Camp David formula
for interim Palestinian self-rule puts Shultz in the middle,
between Israel and the Arabs. Egypt and Jordan have declared the
process out of date.
   Shamir also insisted that Palestinian ``autonomy,'' which would
involve some self-rule but not statehood, not be ``accelerated''
because of the current violence, the Israeli official said.
   Peres, Shamir's partner and rival in the ``national unity''
coalition, said he found Shultz ``open-minded and very attentive,
looking for fresh ideas and information.''
   ``He brought workable proposals,'' the foreign minister
said.``We have some workable proposals, and for that reason we have
started to work.''
   Rabin, the defense minister, said Arab demonstrators should have
``no illusion that by force they can change the position of
Israel.''
   A solution is possible only through negotiations involving
Palestinians who live in the West Bank and Gaza, along with Jordan
and Israel, he said.
   He told reporters: ``They are going to suffer more than anybody
else by the violence. ... By military means we can achieve
tranquility, but not a solution.''
   Peres and Rabin represent the center-left Labor Party, which for
20 years has proposed that Israel yield some of the occupied
territory as part of an overall peace settlement. Shamir and his
conservative Likud bloc oppose trading land for peace, which Shultz
has suggested.
   Shultz flies to Amman on Saturday to meet with Prime Minister
Zaid Rifai of Jordan, then to Damascus to see the Syrian president,
Hafez Assad.
   He also will travel to Cairo during his five-day shuttle, for
which Jerusalem is the base.
</TEXT>
