<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Panama-LatinReax     02-26 0629</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Panama-Latin Reax,0647</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Venezuela Backs Deposed President, Nicaragua Backs Noriega</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Panama, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Nicaragua came out in support of Panamanian strongman Gen.
Manuel Antonio Noriega on Friday in the showdown over the
leadership of the Central American nation.
   Venezuela backed Eric Arturo Delvalle, who was removed from
office early Friday by legislators a few hours after he ordered
Noriega to step down.
   In Cartagena, Colombia, the foreign ministers of eight other
Latin American nations attending a regional meeting stayed
non-committal, saying they were studying the situation.
   In Bogota, ex-presidents Alfonso Lopez Michelsen of Colombia,
Daniel Oduber of Costa Rica and Carlos Andres Perez of Venezuela
said they had agreed earlier with Noriega on a plan for the
``democratization'' of Panama under which they said Noriega would
promise to retire as armed forces commander to allow free elections
next year.
   But the three former leaders said the events in Panama had
aggravated the situation in the country.
   In Managua, Nicaraguan President Daniel Ortega offered his
support to Noriega and accused the U.S. government of trying to
destroy the nation's sovereignty, the government-owned Sandinista
newspaper reported Friday.
   ``The president of Nicaragua assured Gen. Noriega that the
Panamanian people, facing threats, blackmail and the danger of
American troop intervention, could count on the militant and
combative solidarity of the people of Sandino,'' a government
communique printed in the newspaper said.
   The Sandinista communique said Ortega spoke with Noriega on the
telephone Thursday night and offered ``unconditional solidarity in
these moments when the American government is trying to kill the
spirit of Torrijos to save the sovereignty of Panama.''
   Brig. Gen. Omar Torrijos, the nationalist leader who staged a
1968 coup, became a national hero by working out the transfer to
Panama in 1999 of the American-built Panama Canal. He died in a
plane crash in 1981.
   The Sandinista links with Torrijos and the Panamanian government
go back to before the 1978-79 revolutionary war in Nicaragua.
Torrijos' government sent combatants and arms to the leftist
Sandinistas, who overthrew Anastasio Somoza.
   Weeks after Noriega's problems broke out last June, Ortega flew
to Panama as a show of support. Ortega said the United States was
engaged in a conspiracy to break the 1977 canal treaties.
   The eight Latin American foreign ministers attending the meeting
in Colombia discussed the events in Panama at the request of
Panamaian Foreign Minister Jorge Abadia.
   ``We are being informed about developments in Panama,'' said
Colombian Foreign Minister Julio Londono Paredes, but he declined
to make any further comment.
   Abadia had asked Thursday that his fellow ministers of
Argentina, Brazil, Colombia, Mexico, Peru, Uruguay and Venezuela
should offer their solidarity to Panama against ``a worldwide
disinformation campaign.''
   Abadia told them that drug-dealing charges against Noriega ``do
not correspond with the facts in Panama'' and he denounced
``maneuvers'' by the United States to keep its troops in control of
the Panama Canal beyond the year 1999, when a treaty stipulates
that Panama will take over control of the waterway.
   Abadia returned hurriedly to Panama on Friday.
   Venezuelan Foreign Minister German Nava Carrillo said in
Cartagena that his government supports ``the democracy, sovereignty
and independence of Panama'' but warned that ``the military forces
should be subject and obedient to civilian power.''
   In Caracas, the Venezuelan government expressed support for
Delvalle's decision to oust Noriega and called on the Central
American nation's armed forces to respect such a decision.
   ``The Venezuelan government reaffirms its unequivocal position
on the respect that the military forces in Panama owe to the
civilian power, as dictated by the Panama's Constitution,'' said a
communique issued Thursday night by the Miraflores Government
Palace.
   ``The Venezuelan government expresses categorically its support
to all the efforts aimed at strenthening the Panamanian democratic
process,'' the brief communique said.
</TEXT>
