<1ST_LINE>r a AM-CopKilled     02-26 0441</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cop Killed,0454</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Commissioner Calls Cop Shooting Assassination</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VIRGINIA BYRNE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A rookie policeman was killed in his patrol car
Friday by three point-blank shots to the head in what the police
commissioner said was an assassination meant to intimidate a crime
witness.
   Officer Edward Byrne, 22, was shot as he sat in a marked patrol
car in Queens, guarding the home of a threatened witness in a drug
case. The house had been firebombed twice, allegedly by dealers.
   Two men drove up to the patrol car at 3:30 a.m. One man got out
and fired up to five shots into the patrol car, said Police
Commissioner Benjamin Ward.
   The gunman had approached the car ``in a way not likely to alarm
the police officer that anything was amiss, and then when he was so
close that he could not miss, and moving so rapidly that the police
officer would not be able to respond defensively, fired into the
car,'' the commissioner said.
   Byrne was the first officer killed in the line of duty this
year, said police spokesman Sgt. Peter Sweeney. Three city police
officers and one transit police officer were killed in 1987.
   Ward acknowledged that the shooting could have been an act of
random violence, but said ``it smacks more of a deliberate
assassination attempt.''
   He described the shooting as ``an attempt to intimidate not just
that witness but all of you, and all of the people of this city and
this country to say that if you cooperate with criminal justice
something is going to happen to you.''
   The resident of the house is a witness in impending cases
against area drug dealers.
   The house was firebombed twice in November by drug dealers who
believed the man had complained to police about drug dealing on his
street, police said.
   Southeast Queens has become a hub of crack trafficking and
drug-related violence in the last two years. Many shootings in the
area are the result of constant turf wars between drug cartels,
Ward said.
   Authorities assigned a 24-hour police guard to the house after
the firebombings. Ward said the witness has also received other
threats against his life for cooperating with authorities.
   He said assigning a single officer was standard practice. The
patrol car was provided for the officer's convenience because of
the weather.
   Ward said having two officers in the patrol car would not make a
difference in officers' safety ``if an assassin decides to arrive.''
   Byrne was single and was a second generation police officer; his
father, Matthew Byrne, headed the department's Legal Bureau from
1972 to 1976.
</TEXT>
