<1ST_LINE>r a AM-HurricaneCarter 1stLd-Writethru a0724 02-26 0375</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hurricane Carter, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0724,0379</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Signs Papers Releasing Carter From Prosecution</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: ADD three grafs background.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>PATERSON, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A state judge Friday formally dismissed
22-year-old triple murder charges against Rubin ``Hurricane''
Carter a week after prosecutors said they would not seek a third
trial of the former boxer.
   ``I'm joyous with the result and deeply satisfied that justice
finally has been done and the charges dismissed,'' said Carter's
attorney, Myron Beldock, after Superior Court Judge Ralph V. Martin
signed the order dismissing the indictment against Carter and John
Artis.
   Carter had served 19 years in prison before a federal judge in
1985 voided his second conviction and ordered his release on
grounds that the conviction was tainted by racial bias and the
witholding of information from the defense.
   Carter, who has been living in seclusion, could not be reached
for comment. Beldock would not release his telephone number or
whereabouts, but said his client would meet with reporters Monday.
   Prosecutors had said dismissal of the charges was justified
because of the passage of time since the 1966 killings, problems
finding witnesses, court decisions descrediting previous testimony
and the burden posed by a third prosecution.
   They also cited the time served in prison by the defendants.
Artis, who was paroled in 1981, is serving a six-year term on an
unrelated drug conviction.
   Carter and Artis were convicted in 1967, but given a new trial
in 1976 after two witnesses recanted. They were convicted again,
and the verdicts were upheld by the state Supreme Court.
   The federal judge's decision releasing Carter from prison was
upheld by an appellate court, and the U.S. Supreme Court refused to
accept an appeal by prosecutors.
   Carter, 50, and Artis, 41, had been accused of killing a
bartender and two patrons of a Paterson bar. The victims were
white; and the gunmen, like Carter and Artis, were black.
   Hours earlier, a black Paterson bartender had been shot to death
by a white man. Prosecutors theorized that the later killings were
in retaliation.
   Celebrities such as Muhammed Ali and actress Ellen Burstyn took
up Carter's cause, viewing him as a symbol of racial injustice. Bob
Dylan wrote and sang ``Hurricane,'' a ballad about the boxer's case.
</TEXT>
