<1ST_LINE>u w AM-US-Panama-Envoy     02-26 0421</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Panama-Envoy,400</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Panama's Ambassador Backs Delvalle, Calls for Trade Embargo</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-US Panama Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRISCOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Panama's ambassador to Washington said he
refused an order Friday by military strong man Miguel Antonio
Noriega to resign and would continue to serve as envoy under
U.S.-recognized President Eric Arturo Delvalle.
   Ambassador Juan Sosa also said a U.S. trade embargo might be
necessary to depose Noriega and acknowledged that Delvalle has no
support in the military.
   Sosa declared his support for Delvalle hours before the State
Department said it would continue to recognize him even though he
was ousted by Panama's national assembly after he tried to fire
Noriega as military chief.
   Department spokeswoman Phyllis Oakley said the U.S. government
still considered Sosa Panama's legal ambassador.
   Sosa said at a news conference that he expects Noriega to
appoint a rival ambassador, but he said later that he would retain
his office with the full backing of his embassy staff in Washington.
   Sosa said he had not contacted other Panamanian envoys around
the world and did not know whether others would support Delvalle.
   He said, however, he expects official recognition of Delvalle's
government from several other countries.
   The envoy said he told Noriega in a telephone call Friday that
as a member of Delvalle's Republican Party, he still considered him
president of the country. Noriega asked for his resignation and he
refused, Sosa said.
   He noted that as ambassador for four months he had opposed
economic sanctions against Panama, ``but there are some times in
the history of nations when economic sanctions (are needed) to get
the country back on track.''
   ``We certainly hope that not only the U. S. but the whole
hemisphere will support Panama and if necessary apply economic
sanctions to help Panama get back onto the road of democracy,''
Sosa said.
   He said, however, Delvalle would not support U.S. military
intervention.
   Sosa said he did not expect reprisals against the 50,000 U.S.
citizens in Panama and predicted the crisis could be resolved by
peaceful means.
   He denied that U.S. pressure had led to Delvalle's attempt to
depose Noriega, saying it is a ``step that has been taken
consciously and courageously'' without anyone else's help.
   Asked if there were any signs of support for Delvalle in the
military, Sosa said, ``The national defense forces are very united.
There might be dissent, but I don't know of it.''
   ``We do not have any military support. We only have the weapon
of being right,'' he said.
</TEXT>
