<DOCNO> AP880226-0162 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-26-88 1608EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Soviet-Armenia Bjt   02-26 0865</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Armenia, Bjt,0895</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gorbachev Speech Calls For Calm in Armenian Unrest</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW KATELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A top Soviet official went on Armenian radio and
television Friday and read a plea by Mikhail S. Gorbachev for an
end to unrest by protesters demanding land from a neighboring
republic.
   Armenian activists speaking by telephone from Yerevan described
an increased presence by the Red Army, including paratroopers armed
with clubs.
   The 15-minute unprecented speech, broadcast at 11 a.m., blasted
from speakers throughout Yerevan, the capital of Armenia.
Demonstrators crowding the streets heard it read over TV monitors
placed outside by government officials.
   Reports from Yerevan late Friday indicated that the thousands of
demonstrators began dispersing several hours after the broadcast. A
witness said the protesters only began heading home after the
Armenian Communist Party Central Committee agreed to ask the Soviet
Central Committee to reconsider the request for land.
   Another witness said 1,500 Soviet paratroopers had been flown
into Yerevan around midnight Thursday and were ferried in a
40-vehicle motorcade to the Dynamo sports hall and other locations
around the republic's capital.
   ``They came with full equipment, including clubs,'' said Paruyr
Ayrikyan, an Armenian activist.
   For the past week, unsanctioned mass demonstrations have rocked
Yerevan. Protesters are demanding that Nagorno-Karabakh, an
autonomous region of the neighboring republic of Azerbaidzhan, be
made part of Armenia.
   Protests also were reported earlier in the week in
Nagorno-Karabakh where more than 80 percent of the 157,000
residents are Armenians.
   The Armenian National Committee, an anti-communist group based
in Athens, Greece, claimed that Azerbaidjanis killed more than 70
Armenians in the disputed region.
   A 17-year-old resident of Nagorno-Karabakh said Thursday that
virtually the entire Armenian population of the region demonstrated
daily in the main city, Stepanakert, since Feb. 13.
   Tass reported that Soviet officials said there were some
``victims'' in those protests but said there were no deaths.
   In his speech, Gorbachev appealed to the people of Armenia and
Azerbaidzhan to show ``civic maturity and restraint,'' the official
Tass news agency reported.
   He said the Central Committee will meet to examine relations
among the country's more than 100 ethnic groups, Tass said.
   In a late night dispatch, Tass reported that Gorbachev
acknowledged ``there are unresolved problems in the life of Soviet
society, but the fomenting of strife and mistrust among peoples
only hinders their resolution.''
   One witness said the demonstrators did not begin dispersing
immediately after hearing the address, read by Politburo member
Vladimir I. Dolgikh.
   They began leaving a few hours later, after learning that the
Armenian Central Committee had requested the national Central
Committee to reconsider the annexation proposal, said the witness,
a 40-year-old Armenian woman reached in Yerevan by phone Friday
night.
   A hotel worker said the demonstrators planned no more protests
until after March 23 when a decision on the dispute is expected
from the Armenian Central Committee.
   ``There is no disorder. Everyone is working again,'' said the
employee of the Yerevan Hotel who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   Asked how the demonstrators reacted to Gorbachev's speech,
Valery Aidinyan, chief of the propaganda department at the Yerevan
Communist Party newspaper Kommunist, said: ``They took it with good
feelings. It had a calm tone, and was warm, without the usual
rhetoric.''
   Earlier Friday, Sergei Grigoryants, a dissident of Armenian
origin, estimated that more than 1 million people were in Yerevan's
streets Friday morning.
   ``Columns are marching along the major streets, and there is a
sea of banners,'' he said.
   Gevorg Mirozyan, an editor at the Armenian state broadcasting
authority Gostelradio, put the number of demonstrators at more than
a million.
   Aidinyan said his crowd size estimate was in the range of tens
of thousands or hundreds of thousands.
   There has been no official estimate of the number of
demonstrators, and the government has barred foreign reporters from
traveling to Armenia.
   Aidinyan said factories and public transportation, reported
earlier to have been closed by a strike in support of the
protesters, had returned to normal.
   Late Friday, Tass issued the first official confirmation of
labor disruption.
   ``A number of industrial enterprises in Yerevan have been in a
fever of late as people were leaving their workplaces to take part
in demonstrations and meetings in connection with the events in
Nagorny-Karabakh,'' the news agency reported, quoting an Armenian
Central Committee member identified only as S. Petrosyan.
   Armenia is the smallest of the 15 Soviet republics in area, and
has 3.4 million inhabitants. By annexing Nagorno-Karabakh, which at
1,760 square miles is smaller than Delaware, Armenia's area would
increase by 14 percent, and its population by 4 percent.
   The protests test Gorbachev's campaign for greater
democratization and openness, and his personal appeal showed how
seriously the Kremlin leadership regards the situation. Gorbachev
has said relations among the Soviet Union's nationalities are the
country's greatest problem.
   Grigoryants said protesters carried signs linking their actions
with Gorbachev's policies of ``glasnost,'' or openness, and
``perestroika,'' his broad plan for rebuilding Soviet society.
   The speech marked the first time Gorbachev has personally
intervened in a nationalities dispute.
   Even in December 1986, when rioting broke out in the Central
Asian republic of Kazakhstan, killing three and injuring hundreds,
Gorbachev did not surface.
</TEXT>
