<FILEID>AP-NR-02-26-88 2137EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Reagan-Commerce     02-26 0165</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Reagan-Commerce,160</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan To Nominate Commerce Officials</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan is nominating Frank DeGeorge
to be inspector general at the Commerce Department, the White House
announced Friday.
   DeGeorge, if confirmed by the Senate, will succeed Sherman
Maxwell Funk in the job.
   Reagan also announced his intention to nominate Robert H.
Brumley II to be general counsel of the Commerce Department,
succeeding Douglas A. Riggs.
   Since 1982, DeGeorge has been deputy inspector general at the
Commerce Department. Before that he was associate deputy
administrator for administration at the Veterans Administration
from 191-82.
   DeGeorge, 58, graduated from La Salle College in 1951 and
completed graduate studies at the University of Delaware in 1955.
   Brumley since 1985 has been deputy general counsel at the
Commerce Department, and before that was a special assistant to the
general counsel and had been in private practice of law from
1979-83.
   Brumley, 39, is a graduate of East Tennessee State University
and the University of Tennessee College of Law.
</TEXT>
