<1ST_LINE>r w AM-BRF--Hunters-ForeignBirds     02-26 0144</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Hunters-Foreign Birds,130</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Hunters Getting Permission To Bring Home Foreign Birds</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soon it will be all right for American hunters
to bring foreign-bagged wild pheasant and grouse home for cooking,
the Agriculture Department said Friday.
   That is, so long as the birds have been eviscerated and their
heads and feet removed, said James W. Glosser, acting administrator
of the department's Animal and Plant Health Inspection Service. The
new rule takes effect March 28.
   Previously, such game birds had to be cooked before being
brought into the United States to prevent the introduction of
poultry diseases. Glosser said the agency has determined that wild
pheasant and grouse carcasses are not threats if they are first
trimmed of innards, heads and feet.
   About 300 to 400 American hunters annually have been returning
with cooked fowl shot in foreign countries, he said.
</TEXT>
