<1ST_LINE>u w AM-AIDS-Children     02-26 0355</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-AIDS-Children,370</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bowen Announces Task Force To Focus On Childrren With AIDS</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY ESTILL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Health and Human Service Secretary Otis R.
Bowen on Friday announced the formation of a federal task force to
focus on AIDS among children.
   ``The purpose of the initiative is to cut across agency lines,
ensuring that we provide not only the best medical response but
also the best use of our social programs on behalf of these
children and their families,'' Bowen said at the latest in a series
of department briefings on AIDS.
   Dr. Antonia C. Novello of the National Institute of Child Health
and Human Development heads the newly designated Pediatric HIV
Infection Working Group, which includes representatives from five
agencies within the sprawling HHS department.
   Bowen cited emerging evidence that the deadly disease affects
children somewhat differently than adults as justification for
designating the special task force.
   He said the working group ``will help carry out the agenda set
last year at the Surgeon General's Workshop on Children With HIV
Infection and Their Families.''
   Bowen noted that many agencies within HHS have already been
working on special problems associated with AIDS among children. He
cited as an example a plan by the Health Resources and Services
Administration to spend $4.4 million this year on demonstration
programs for innovative ways of caring for children with AIDS.
   He also said the Office for Human Development Services ``will be
funding projects to improve recruitment of foster parents and to
provide supportive services for natural and foster families'' of
children with AIDS.
   There are just over 1,000 officially reported AIDS cases among
people under 18 years old, but Bowen said that is projected to
increase to 3,000 in three years.
   Moreover, he added, ``We believe that for every one child who
meets the definition for AIDS itself, at least another two are HIV
infected and the number of probably higher. By 1991, we expect that
there will be some 10,000 to 20,000 HIV-infected children in the
United States.''
   Existing evidence suggests that most children infected with the
virus eventually develop the disease itself.
</TEXT>
