<1ST_LINE>r a AM-PayolaIndictment     02-26 0453</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Payola Indictment,0466</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Federal Grand Jury Indicts Four</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROGER GILLOTT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two independent music promoters, a former
radio executive and a promoter's wife were indicted on bribery, tax
evasion or other charges stemming from a two-year-old payola
investigation, federal officials said Friday.
   One promoter used cocaine as well as cash to bribe radio station
employees to play his records, according to the indictment.
   ``The independent promoters were acting on behalf of virtually
all record companies in this country,'' U.S. Attorney Robert Bonner
said at a news conference after the indictments were unsealed.
   However, Bonner said there was no evidence the record companies
were aware of any bribery, or payola as it's called in the industry.
   The investigation was continuing with help from authorities in
half a dozen cities, Bonner said, but he declined to say whether
additional indictments were expected.
   Federal agents arrested promoter Ralph Tashjian, 39, of San
Mateo and his wife, Valerie, at their home Thursday, even though
their attorneys had offered to surrender them to authorities, said
Anthony Brooklier, the promoter's lawyer.
   Tashjian is accused of three counts of payola, one count of
conspiracy to distribute cocaine, one count of obstruction of
justice and three counts of corporate income-tax fraud, Brooklier
said.
   Tashjian allegedly paid nearly $42,000 in cash and gave
undisclosed quantities of cocaine to three radio station workers
from 1980 to 1985 in exchange for air time for his records.
   The charges against him, handed up by a Los Angeles federal
grand jury Thursday, were denied by the Tashjians' attorneys.
   Mrs. Tashjian was arrested for alleged corporate tax evasion.
   A second indictment announced Friday by Bonner charged
independent promoter William Craig, 42, of Scottsdale, Ariz., also
known as William Craighead, with willfully aiding in the
preparation of false federal tax returns and attempting to evade
individual income tax.
   It also charges Craighead with making illegal payments to three
radio stations to ensure that certain records were played on the
air.
   The third indictment charged George Wilson Crowell, also known
as George Wilson, 59, former vice president and general manager of
radio station KIQQ in Los Angeles, with willful failure to file
federal income tax returns for 1984, 1985 and 1986.
   Craig faces 18 years in prison and fines of $1.64 million if
convicted. The charges against Tashjian carry penalties of up to 23
years and $1.53 million in fines; Mrs. Tashjian, 15 years and $1.5
million; and Crowell, three years and $75,000, Bonner said.
   The payola investigation began in 1986. Alleged organized crime
figure Salvatore James Pisello, 64, of West Hollywood, was charged
last July with three counts of tax evasion. His case is pending in
Los Angeles federal court.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
