<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Panama-Blandon 1stLd-Writethru a0737 02-26 0765</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Panama-Blandon, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0737,740</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Delvalle Has Secret Plan for Noriega's Ouster, Dissident Says</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Deletes redundant attribution from 2nd graf</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Panama's President Eric Arturo Delvalle knew
in advance that his attempted firing of Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega
would fail but is confident that planned steps would lead to
Noriega's downfall within three weeks, a Panamaniam dissident said
Friday.
   Jose I. Blandon, a onetime Noreiga associate, said in an
interview that Delvalle has devised an 18-point plan for the ouster
of the military strong man, and his unsuccessful bid to replace him
was but one element.
   ``It is exactly what we thought was going to happen,'' Blandon
said, referring to Delvalle's bid to install the second-ranking
officer in Panama's Defense Forces as commander on Thursday and
Noriega's decision to ignore the order.
   Hours later, the Panamanian National Assembly, dominated by
Noriega allies, voted to oust Delvalle and replace him with the
education minister. But Delvalle said he still regards himself as
president.
   Blandon said other elements in the effort to topple Noriega
include a general strike, the rallying of international support for
Delvalle and the consent of the Dominican Republic to give Noriega
a safe haven if and when he flees Panama.
   Delvalle received a boost Friday when the State Department
announced that it continues to recognize him as president. Blandon
said he expects similar support from many Latin American
democracies.
   The Reagan administration has been increasingly hostile to
Noriega, especially since his indictment on drug-smuggling charges
by federal grand juries in Florida three weeks ago.
   Other aspects of the anti-Noriega plot, Blandon said, include a
purging of Panama's Defense Forces, leading to the ouster of six
majors he said are involved in drug trafficking and eight colonels
who are serving in violation of rules requiring retirement after 25
years' service.
   If Noriega leaves, Col. Elias Castillo, the third-ranking member
of the Defense Forces, would take command. Blandon said Castillo is
a military professional, is untainted by corruption and leads a
modest middle-class existence that contrasts sharply with the
opulent life styles of some of Noriega's close military associates.
   Castillo is ``not involved in drugs and he's clean,'' Blandon
said. ``He's a good soldier. He does not have political ambitions.''
   With U.S. marshals deployed nearby, Blandon sat in a local hotel
suite and outlined how he, Delvalle and a group of other opposition
leaders have been planning to restore civilian rule in Panama.
   Noriega once looked on Blandon as a close confidante, but the
two had a falling out last fall after Blandon told the military
chieftain that Panama's crisis can only be solved if he steps down.
   Blandon is under U.S. government protection because of testimony
he gave outlining Noriega's alleged drug-smuggling activities and
his ties with the CIA, among other issues.
   During his 90-minute conversation with a reporter, Blandon
perused a document he said was an 18-point plan for restoring
civilian supremacy in Panama. It was dated Feb. 22, but Blandon
said the essentials of the plan had been worked out by himself,
Delvalle and opposition leaders weeks earlier.
   Blandon said that during a meeting in Miami last week, Delvalle
asked Assistant Secretary of State Elliott Abrams if it would be
possible to drop the indictments against Noriega.
   Abrams replied that it would be legally possible but that any
such decision would have to be made by either the Justice
Department or President Reagan, Blandon said.
   Withdrawal of the indictments presumably would leave Noriega
free to seek a safe haven outside Panama without fear of U.S.
extradition. But Blandon said the administration has given no
indication it would agree to lift the indictments.
   He said authorities in the Dominican Republic, where Noriega has
a son-in-law, have agreed to allow him and five to seven associates
into the country should he be forced out. Noriega has been informed
of this development, he said.
   But if the indictments remain in place, Noriega would be subject
to U.S. extradition under a treaty with the Dominican Republic.
   Still, Blandon said he was confident that Noriega's days as
defense chief are numbered, particularly if there is widespread
adherence to a scheduled call for a general strike and if the
United States imposes an economic embargo against Panama.
   He said Alaskan oil is shipped through a Panamanian pipeline for
eventual delivery to U.S. East Coast ports. An embargo would
prevent continued use of the pipeline by American companies,
depriving Panama of millions of dollars of badly needed revenue and
aggravating what he described as the country's acute financial
crisis.
</TEXT>
