<2ND_LINE>AM-Jackson-Georgia,350</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jackson Stumps In Georgia, Picks Up Amy Carter's Backing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BYRD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic presidential condidate Jesse Jackson
campaigned in Georgia on Friday, visiting the Legislature, cajoling
Atlanta attorneys to help the poor and picking up an endorsement
from Amy Carter.
   Jackson, as he has done at other stops across the South,
reminded members of the Georgia General Assembly of his Southern
roots.
   ``I am one of you,'' he said in remarks to the state Senate. ``I
worked hard to make the new South new _ now, lets make the new
South better.
   ``I am my party's conscience. By July, with your help, I want to
be its candidate.''
   Appearing with Jackson in the Capitol rotunda was Miss Carter,
the daughter of former President Jimmy Carter, who said she was
endorsing the civil rights leader and 1984 Democratic candidate
because of his ``pro-people'' stands.
   ``I have discussed this with my father, but you'll have to ask
him how he feels about it, not me,'' Miss Carter told the Marietta
Daily Journal.
   The former president, a ``superdelegate'' to the Democrats'
national convention in Atlanta this summer, remains uncommitted,
according to aides at the Carter Presidential Center.
   Jackson will be back in Georgia on Saturday for a debate with
the other Democratic hopefuls at the Georgia World Congress Center,
sponsored by The Atlanta Journal and The Atlanta Constitution.
   In a speech Friday to members of the Atlanta Bar Association,
Jackson asked the lawyers for help in assuring all Americans equal
access to the judicial system.
   ``We have a whole body of people denied equal protection under
the law'' because President Reagan has cut funding for legal help
for the poor and the nation's lawyers have failed to fill in the
gap, Jackson said.
   In response to a question about his religion and the presidency,
the Baptist minister vowed to keep church and state separate if he
is elected.
   But, he said, ``We should not keep morality and state separate.
... We must bring our values to high office. ... I'm not ashamed of
the gospel. That which makes us feed the hungry and clothe the
naked ... we must never apologize for that.''
</TEXT>
