<1ST_LINE>r w AM-RailMX     02-26 0475</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Rail MX,470</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Air Force Doing Environmental Study for Rail-Based MX Missiles</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NORMAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Air Force said Friday it had launched an
environmental impact study of bases that could be used as garrisons
for rail-mounted MX nuclear missiles.
   In conducting the study, the service said it would review a
number of deployment alternatives, including the fielding of 100 MX
missiles on rail cars instead of just 50 missiles.
   Defense Secretary Frank C. Carlucci disclosed recently the
administration would like to move the 50 MX missiles that Congress
already has approved for silo basing to rail cars along with a new
batch of 50 missiles.
   Congress has yet to approve any type of mobile deployment for
the 10-warhead MX, but it has provided research-and-development
funding since President Reagan unveiled the idea in December 1986.
   The Air Force announced a year ago it had selected F.E. Warren
Air Force Base in Wyoming to become the main operating base for any
rail-mounted MX missiles and 10 other bases for consideration as
additional ``rail garrisons.''
   The service said Friday that list had not changed, and that
special ``meetings to identify environmental issues'' would be
scheduled soon for residents living near each of those 11 bases.
   Besides F.E. Warren, the list includes Blytheville Air Force
Base, Ark.; Little Rock Air Force Base, Ark.; Whiteman Air Force
Base, Mo.; Barksdale Air Force Base, La.; Dyess Air Force Base,
Texas; Fairchild Air Force Base, Wash.; Grand Forks Air Force Base,
N.D.; Minot Air Force Base, N.D.; Malstrom Air Force Base, Mont.,
and Wurtsmith Air Force Base, Mich.
   The Air Force said it hoped to complete the impact study by late
this year and make the final selection of home bases.
   The Air Force envisions either 25 or 50 six-car trains, with
each train carrying two MX missiles. Each garrison could house
four, five or six trains.
   The missiles would be carried in specially modified cargo cars,
made to look like a regular boxcar. To launch the missile, the top
of the box car would open outward, allowing the missile to be
erected into a vertical position and fired.
   The trains would remain inside the heavily guarded garrisons
during peacetime, but could disperse onto the regular commercial
rail system in the event of an emergency. The Pentagon's goal would
be to have a mobile target that the Soviet Union could not destroy.
   The Air Force says it has made no decision on how many rail
garrison bases it needs out of the list of 10 besides F.E. Warren.
   The Air Force, which calls the MX the Peacekeeper missile, said,
``The proposed action is to deploy a total of 50 Peacekeeper
missiles on 25 Air Force trains with two missiles per train. But an
alternative action is to deploy 100 Peacekeeper missiles on 50
trains.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880226-0171 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-26-88 2105EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-NotKosher     02-26 0625</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Not Kosher,0642</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Companies Accused In Kosher Fraud Agree To Settlement</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM C. HIDLAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three companies accused of selling thousands of
pounds of non-kosher poultry as kosher to customers in up to 22
states have agreed in a legal settlement to get out of the kosher
business, officials said Friday.
   ``We wanted to make sure something like this never happened
again,'' said Rabbi Victor Segal, president of Goldman-Segal Kosher
Caterers of Chicago, which had accused the three companies of fraud
in a federal lawsuit. ``It was a nightmare.''
   Segal said it was the largest case of fraud involving
mislabeling of kosher foods, and potentially affected Jewish
families in 22 states where the companies' kosher poultry products
were sold.
   Jewish religious law restricts the type of meats that can be
eaten and mandates a ritual for butchering the meats and removing
as much blood as possible to make them kosher. ``The process is
lengthy and more expensive,'' Segal said.
   In mid-December, Segal's catering company sued the Chicago-based
companies _ United Poultry Inc., Aspen Foods Inc. and Shelat Kosher
Foods Inc. _ and two of their officers in federal court, accusing
them of false advertising, fraud and deceptive trade practices. The
catering company had bought kosher poultry products from United
Poultry, Segal said.
   A month earlier, the Illinois attorney general had filed a state
lawsuit against the companies, as well as Sheldon Terman, president
of the three firms, and Michael Terman, the companies' secretary,
for allegedly mislabeling their products as kosher.
   Cook County Circuit Judge Anthony Scotillo ordered a nationwide
recall on Nov. 5 of up to 376,000 pounds of poultry processed by
Shelat Kosher Foods and sold under the Shelat label.
   The judge also issued a temporary injunction shutting down
Shelat, a meat-processing firm that made specialty kosher poultry
products such as chicken kiev.
   On Nov. 24, Shelat admitted selling non-kosher poultry as kosher
in a court-issued consent decree and was permanently closed, said
William Sullivan, chief of the attorney general's consumer
protection division.
   The attorney general's office estimated that Shelat made about
$250,000 profit from selling cheaper non-kosher poultry at the
higher kosher prices.
   But Segal said his catering company was more concerned about the
possible violations of Jewish religious law. ``The mental anguish
that we had from the possibility of having defiled dishes and ovens
and flatware was awful,'' he said.
   The company also was ordered to pay $250,000 in restitution and
fines, and its president, Sheldon Terman, was ordered to sell his
stock in United Poultry, a company that distributed Shelat's
products and other kosher foods.
   Under Friday's settlement, United Poultry, which still was
distributing other kosher poultry products, must stop selling all
kosher foods by no later than Sept. 1, and the other two companies
are also ordered out of the kosher business, Segal said.
   It also specifies a monetary settlement which may not be
disclosed under terms of the settlement, Segal said.
   ``We have no complaints about the settlement,'' said Harvey
Silets, an attorney representing the companies and the Termans.
``We've agreed to it. This is merely a continuation of the matter
that was initiated by the attorney general.''
   Silets said the company officers accused in the suit would not
be available for comment.
   Shelat bought poultry from kosher butchering houses and then
processed it to make specialty items, such as boneless chicken
breasts stuffed with rice, Segal said.
   But a new employee at Shelat noticed that the company was
sending out more kosher-labeled products than the amount of
kosher-slaughtered chicken it received, Segal said.
   A surprise inspection by the Union of Orthodox Jewish
Congregations found that Shelat employees were placing the union's
kosher labels on poultry that was not kosher, Segal said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880226-0172 </DOCNO>
