<1ST_LINE>r i AM-UN-PLO     02-26 0384</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-UN-PLO,0396</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.N. Prepares For Emergency Session On U.S. Move To Close PLO
Mission</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VICTORIA GRAHAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United Nations prepared Friday for an
emergency session of the General Assembly next week to consider
U.S. plans to close the U.N. observer mission of the Palestine
Liberation Organization.
   The session by the 159-nation group begins Monday and is
expected to last at least three days.
   The dispute began after the U.S. Congress voted and President
Reagan approved an order last December to shut the PLO mission in
New York effective March 22.
   Following the congressional action the General Assembly voted
overwhelmingly to urge the United States to abide by its treaty
obligations and leave the mission alone.
   The United Nations resolution said the U.S. law violated the
1947 Headquarters Agreement, which obliges the United States to
allow U.N. missions to operate.
   Both the PLO and Arab League previously said they might seek to
move the General Assembly from New York to Geneva if the PLO office
is closed. They also have said they could seek a ruling by the
World Court in the Hague.
   The United Nations was awaiting word from U.S. Attorney General
Edwin Meese III on whether he would implement the law and close the
mission. In the past, he has said he intends to enforce the law.
   In Washington, U.S. Ambassador Vernon A. Walters, America's
permanent U.N. representative, told congressmen Thursday he was
``not optimistic about the outcome'' of the session.
   He made the comment after testifying that if the United States
continues to default on its U.N. budget dues, now $252.8 million in
arrears, it will lose influence and prestige in the international
body.
   A draft resolution approved Friday by the Arab League states
that the United States is legally obliged to let the PLO operate
its observer mission and calls the U.S. legislation ``a blatant
violation'' of the Headquarters Agreement.
   Last year, the State Department closed the PLO information
center in Washington, the only other PLO office in the United
States.
   The Headquarters Agreement provides for binding arbitration of
disputes between the United States and the United Nations. U.N.
Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar has invoked the
arbitration clause of the treaty, but said the United States had
not agreed to arbitration.
 
</TEXT>
