<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Congress-Panama     02-26 0612</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Congress-Panama,590</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Members of Congress Call for Trade Embargo of Panama</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-US-Panama Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Congressional foes of Panamanian strongman
Manuel Antonio Noriega urged the Reagan administration on Friday to
impose an immediate and total trade embargo to force him from power.
   Some said the administration should not rule out _ at least as
an option _ the use of military force to oust Noriega, the general
who heads Panama's defense forces.
   Noriega was indicted in the United States recently on charges of
taking millions of dolllars to turn Panama into a haven for drugs
and the profits they generate.
   Others said the United States should press the issue at the
Organization for American States and seek the widest possible
consensus in the Western Hemisphere for Noriega's removal and for
the restoration of democracy in Panama.
   But Senate Majority Leader Robert C. Byrd of West Virginia said
the United States needs to ``keep cool''as it reviews its options
in dealing with Noreiga, especially in light of the continuing U.S.
need to protect free passage through the Panama Canal.
   There was almost universal rejection on Capitol Hill of
Noriega's claim that the United States is attempting to use
corruption charges against him to renege on the U.S. committment to
turn the canal over to Panama by the year 2000.
   ``That statement by Gen. Noriega is piffle, pap, and political
flim flam intended to preserve his own interests,'' Byrd told
reporters.
   ``That is an absolute and total and complete fabrication,'' said
Sen. David Boren, D-Okla. ``... It's the old trick of when you get
caught with your hand in the till, of trying to raise some red
herring to draw attention from yourself ...''
   Sen. Alfonse D'Amato, R-N.Y., said he spoke to Panamanian
President Eric Arturo Delvalle by telephone at midday on Friday.
   ``He said to me he would be fully supportive of a trade
embargo,'' D'Amato told reporters. ``That would be the kind of
decisive action the United States should follow through on.''
   D'Amato said that while he does not believe the United States
should now intervene militarily, ``we should not preclude military
action if that is necessary to protect the vital interests of the
United States.''
   Sen. Edward M. Kennedy, D-Mass., said the United States should
press the Organization of American States (OAS) to accept the
credentials of a new ambassador sent by Devalle and cancel the
credentials of Noriega's ambassador.
   He said that would make clear where the democracies of the
hemisphere stand on the matter.
   ``The action that the OAS takes will speak volumes about whether
that is a meaningful organization or whether it should not be taken
seriously,'' Kennedy said.
   Sen. John Kerry, D-Mass., who heads a Senate Foreign Relations
Committee investigation into Noriega's alleged links to narcotics
racketeering and money laundering, said the United States should
consider suspending landing rights for Panamanaian aircraft and
stop the export of U.S. technology to that country.
   But he said that because Panama uses U.S. currency as legal
tender, the most telling step would be to suspend the transfer of
U.S. dollars to and from Panama.
   Sen. Alan Simpson, R-Wyo., the Senate's deputy GOP leader,
called for a bipartisan movement to deal ``with a squirrel like
Noriega who's got his mailed fist on the levers of the locks of the
canal.''
   ``I think you will find Noriega will leave once the United
States makes a flat-footed stand,'' said Sen. Jesse Helms, R-N.C.,
a leading critic both of Noriega and of the treaties which call for
the canal to be turned over to Panama in the year 2000.
   ``Just embargo Panama,'' Helms said.
</TEXT>
