<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Panama-Glance     02-26 0347</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Panama-Glance,0361</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>With Panama Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   These were the top developments involving Panama on Friday:
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   PANAMA CITY, Panama _ Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega accused the
United States of instigating the effort to end his military rule.
   President Eric Arturo Delvalle, ousted by the legislature after
trying to fire Noriega Thursday, insisted he was still the
president of Panama and called for a worldwide trade embargo
against his country.
   The Defense Forces, meanwhile, closed the headquarters of two
opposition groups.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   WASHINGTON _ President Reagan said he has no plan to intervene
militarily in Panama, and the State Department said the United
States will continue to recognize Delvalle as president.
   White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said the United States
wanted to see Noriega stand trial on the drug charges for which he
was indicted in Florida, and wants Panama to have a civilian
government, but ``we want to be careful not to unduly intrude upon
the affairs of Panama.''
   Vice President George Bush said the United States will do
``whatever is necessary'' to protect its vital interests, but
Reagan said he detected no ``appetite on the part of anyone there,
including Mr. Noriega, to take on our troops.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   WASHINGTON _ Sen. Alfonse M. D'Amato, R-N.Y., advocated a trade
embargo to press Noriega to step down while Sen. Jesse Helms,
R-N.C., called Noriega ``a bum'' who ``ought to be thrown out.''
Senate Majority Leader Robert C. Byrd, D-W.Va., said the United
States ``ought to keep cool'' and give the Panamanian people ample
time to decide Noriega's fate.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   WASHINGTON _ Jose I. Blandon, a onetime associate of Noriega,
said Delvalle anticipated that his attempted firing of Noriega
would fail but is confident that planned steps will lead to
Noriega's downfall within three weeks.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   WASHINGTON _ Panama's ambassador to Washington, Juan Sosa, said
he refused an order Friday by Noriega to resign and would continue
to serve as envoy under Delvalle. Sosa said a U.S. trade embargo
might be necessary to depose Noriega and acknowledged that Delvalle
has no support in the military.
</TEXT>
