<FILEID>AP-NR-02-26-88 2106EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-RacialAssault     02-26 0634</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Racial Assault,0654</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cuomo and Brawley Lawyer Trade Charges</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BAUDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Mario Cuomo on Friday criticized
lawyers for a black teen-ager who says she was assaulted by six
white men, accusing the lawyers of ``making up conditions'' that
have blocked her testimony.
   A lawyer for Tawana Brawley said Cuomo's remarks were ``down in
the gutter.''
   Meanwhile, an aunt of Miss Brawley's aunt was quoted in a
newspaper interview as saying the girl hadn't even talked about the
case with the lawyers who have refused to allow her to cooperate
with investigators.
   Miss Brawley, 16, was reported missing for four days in
November. She was found wrapped in a plastic garbage bag and
covered with feces, with racial epithets scrawled on her body. She
has said one of the men who assaulted her flashed a police badge
and had a holster.
   She and her family, of Wappinger's Falls north of New York City,
have refused to be questioned on the advice of attorneys C. Vernon
Mason and Alton Maddox Jr. of New York City, who have pressed for a
special prosecutor acceptable to them.
   ``They said they had reasons they could not cooperate. ... It's
clear now they don't really,'' Cuomo said, referring to the
lawyers. ``These conditions obviously don't mean anything. They
keep making up new conditions. What has become more and more
apparent is they simply don't want to cooperate for reasons that I
don't understand.''
   Cuomo said he was willing to do anything to help move the case
along, including meeting with Miss Brawley if her lawyers and the
special state prosecutor he appointed thought that might help. Her
lawyers have rejected that idea.
   At a news conference in Newburgh on Friday, Mason blasted
Cuomo's remarks and compared New York to ``Mississippi circa 1954.''
   ``I shudder to think how he would deal with Gorbachev. I shudder
to think how he would deal with the world's problems. I shudder to
think of how he would deal with leading the nation,'' Mason said,
referring to speculation about Cuomo as a potential presidential
candidate.
   He renewed his demand for a new and permanent special state
prosecutor for racial crimes to replace Cuomo's selection for the
Brawley case, state Attorney General Robert Abrams.
   Mason said that if Cuomo didn't replace Abrams, he would turn to
federal authorities for help.
   Mason and the Rev. Al Sharpton said a mass rally against racism
is planned for Saturday in Newburgh and neighboring Poughkeepsie.
   Cuomo stood behind Abrams, and rejected Mason's claim that the
attorney general was unable to handle the investigation.
   Abrams told an Albany news conference that he was pressing ahead
with the investigation. Miss Brawley's cooperation is ``critically
important'' to the investigation, he said, but he refused to say
the case couldn't be solved without her help.
   The Middletown Times Herald Record quoted Juanita Brawley, who
helped raise Tawana for eight years and who has spent time with the
girl since her attack, as saying she is the only one who knows
enough about the incident to keep the lawyers and the girl's mother
informed.
   ``I know a few things that no one else knows,'' the girl's aunt
said during an interview at her home. She said of Maddox, ``He has
not talked to Tawana. He does not need to talk to Tawana.'' She did
not elaborate.
   ``I'm not going to address it or dignify it,'' Mason said when
asked about the report.
   Miss Brawley has refused to talk to investigators since shortly
after she was found. The Dutchess County district attorney and a
special local prosecutor both withdrew from the case for
unspecified conflicts of interest.
   Miss Brawley's supporters, without providing specific evidence,
have charged that local law enforcement officials were somehow
involved in the attack.
</TEXT>
