<1ST_LINE>r a AM-VacationNightmare     02-26 0418</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Vacation Nightmare,0432</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cruise Ship Vacation Becomes Mutinous Mess, Passengers Say</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AUSTIN, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A pleasure voyage around Central America
turned into a seagoing nightmare when passengers encountered poor
food, a mutinous crew and fistfights, authorities say.
   The cruise brochure had promised passengers a ``friendly,
attentive crew'' and a chance to meet new friends around the pool,
or in the lounge or casino.
   On Friday, the last 90 passengers aboard the cruise ship Galaxy
got off the boat in Panama City, Panama, without completing the
last leg of the trip between Acapulco and Cancun, Mexico, said Ron
Dusek, spokesman for the Texas Attorney General's office.
   Texas Attorney General Jim Mattox had filed suit Wednesday
against Golden Cruisetours Inc. of San Antonio, which booked the
cruise, and two of its subsidiaries and the companies' owners.
   Mattox alleged that cruise customers were bilked of hundreds of
thousands of dollars when their trips were canceled and their money
not refunded. The pleasure cruises were advertised in an Austin
newspaper and 51 other newspapers across the country, Mattox said.
   The Galaxy is owned by Global Cruises, a Panamanian company
owned by the same people at Golden Gruisetours, said Dusek.
   Telephone calls placed Friday to Golden Cruisetours' office in
San Antonio went unanswered.
   The Galaxy cruise began Feb. 11 in Acapulco. Eighty-seven of the
250 passengers refused to go on the cruise because the food was
cold and the air conditioning broken, officials said.
   The next day, the crew mutinied, according to the U.S. State
Department. More passengers left the ship Feb. 18, before the ship
left from Punta Renas, Costa Rica.
   During a docking in Costa Rica, about 50 mutineers were removed
from the ship. That led to a dock rally sponsored by a local
workers' union which refused to supply replacement labor.
   When the ship docked in Panama City, the last 90 passengers on
the cruise disembarked, according to Dusek, who said he did not
know where the ship was.
   Passenger Sarita Anderson described an unsettling scene aboard
ship during a docking in Guatemala.
   ``As we started into the lounge, there was a fight going on,''
she told the Houston Chronicle. ``It was something to do with work
schedules.''
   The English-speaking Honduran crew supervisor was arguing with
the ship's staff chief, yelling that the Mexican crew members,
kitchen help and cabin boys, who had been hired only days earlier
in Acapulco, were being worked too hard, Ms. Anderson said.
   The two men then began a bloody fight, she said.
</TEXT>
