<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Swaggart-Prostitute     02-26 0304</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Swaggart-Prostitute,0314</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tabloid Say Woman Failed Lie Detector Test</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Will be topped following New Orleans TV station's interview
with woman, set for 6 p.m. EST</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The prostitute who claims to have posed nude
for evangelist Jimmy Swaggart failed a lie detector test, a
national tabloid reported Friday.
   The National Enquirer said Debra Murphree voluntarily took the
polygraph test it arranged, adding that it was administered by a
expert with 15 years' experience with the New York City Police
Department.
   The tabloid said in a news release that its expert concluded
Murphree failed to tell the truth on all key questions relating to
her statements.
   However, the statement did not say what the questions were and
gave no other details.
   Murphree saus she performed pornographic acts for Swaggart for
about a year but never had sex with him.
   After allegations of misconduct arose, Swaggart made a tearful
public confession of sin and faces a three-month suspension from
preaching recommended by the Louisiana Assemblies of God hierarchy.
   John Martinez, a companion of Murphree, told The Palm Beach Post
that Murphree visited Swaggart weekly for a year in New
Orleans-area hotel rooms at $50 per meeting.
   Martinez is now peddling Ms. Murphree's story. ``This is a shot
for me and a shot for her,'' he said Wednesday. ``It's the American
way _ see an opportunity and jump on it.''
   Martinez says he talked with the National Enquirer about a
$100,000 contract for Murphree's story and also contacted other
media.
   ``I don't want to see her end up with nothing and on the
streets,'' Martinez, 28, said in a telphone interview Thursday.
``She's not after the money, but I'm looking out after her future.''
   Enquirer president and editor Iain Calder said the tabloid was
talking with Martinez, but would say nothing more.
</TEXT>
