<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ClevelandTeachers     02-26 0322</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cleveland Teachers,0333</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Schools Closed As Teacher Strike Continues</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEPHANIE NANO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CLEVELAND (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Teachers in the state's largest school district
walked picket lines for a second day Friday as negotiators
continued to search for ways end their strike and resume classes
for 73,000 students.
   Adminstrators planned to teach classes for 3,600 seniors
starting Monday if the walkout continued.
   The Cleveland Teachers Union went on strike Thursday after
rejecting the school board's latest contract proposal. Negotiations
resumed Friday afternoon under the guidance of a federal mediator.
   ``I'm hopeful, and the parties seem resolved to try to make a
deal this weekend,'' said Craig M. Brown, the school district's
chief negotiator.
   Said Richard Farmer, the union's strike coordinator:``We would
hope they sit at the table until it's resolved. We don't want a
long strike.''
   The district canceled classes Friday because of the strike by
the 5,093-member union. Schools were closed Thursday because of bad
weather, although other area school systems remained open.
   The closure was viewed as an effort by school administrators to
give negotiators in marathon talks more time to reach a settlement.
   Schools spokesman John M. Hairston said the school board planned
to seek a court order to limit the number of pickets at the
district's buildings because of problems Friday. At Lincoln-West
High School, pickets prevented adminstrators from entering the
building to prepare for classes for seniors at that school Monday,
he said.
   The school board had offered a three-year package with a 3
percent pay raise retroactive to Sept. 1, and 5 percent increases
the next two years contingent on passage of a tax levy and a
voluntary ``career ladder'' in the third year, which would link pay
raises to performance evaluations.
   The school board also offered a one-year contract with a 3
percent raise.
   Cleveland teacher salaries range from $17,600 to $37,450,
depending on education and experience. The average teacher makes
$29,000 annually.
</TEXT>
