<1ST_LINE>r a AM-MissUSA-Furs     02-26 0474</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Miss USA-Furs,0490</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Animal-Rights Activist Disrupts Miss USA News Conference</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HOLDEN LEWIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>EL PASO, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A wild Miss USA pageant took a turn for
the wilder Friday when an animal-rights activist disrupted a news
conference by co-host Alan Thicke.
   Thicke, star of ABC's ``Growing Pains'' and host of the Saturday
morning children's show ``Animal Crack-Ups,'' replaced Bob Barker
as the pageant's host after Barker resigned last month to protest
the giving away of fur coats as prizes.
   It was just one in a series of bumps on the way to Tuesday's
nationally televised beauty contest.
   Miss Minnesota-USA and her runner-up dropped out after it was
disclosed they had been arrested on shoplifting charges. Another
contestant is awaiting trial on drunken-driving charges.
   And Thursday night, Thicke's co-host, actress Tracy Scoggins,
was attacked in a hotel elevator. She suffered bruises but no other
injuries and a suspect was charged with attempted sexual assault.
   Miss USA will be awarded cash and prizes including a full-length
mink coat and a mink jacket. The furs are worth $15,000.
   The Las Cruces, N.M., and El Paso chapters of Sangre de Cristo
Animal Rights plan to picket the El Paso Convention Center during
the pageant to protest the fur prizes. The activists say fur
farming and trapping are cruel activities that should be stopped.
   Bob Young, the picket organizer and president of the group's Las
Cruces chapter, has criticized Thicke for what he calls his
hypocrisy in hosting the pageant. Thicke ends each ``Animal
Crack-Ups'' show with the admonishment: ``Here's hoping you will be
kind to animals.''
   Thicke seemed eager to address the charges at Friday's news
conference. He said he prefers to work within the system instead of
causing ``more abrasion in what is potentially a conflictive
issue.''
   Referring to the pickets, Thicke said: ``I invite those people
to join any one of the eight groups that I am involved with and do
some of the things that we do, such as meet with lobbyists and
legislators.''
   At that point, Young stepped in front of Thicke and held up a
poster of a raccoon caught in a leg trap.
   ``Do your eight groups go along with this?'' Young said, holding
up the poster.
   ``I'm addressing all of that, sir,'' Thicke said.
   ``Your eight groups _ I'd like to know what those groups are,
and if they go along with this,'' Young said.
   ``I'm sure they would be happy to give you an opportunity to
speak when I'm done,'' Thicke said. ``As Mr. Reagan once said, I
paid for this microphone.''
   He did not name the eight groups.
   Thicke said he investigated the suppliers of the pageant's furs
before deciding to do the show to make sure they conformed with
U.S. animal-treatment standards.
   Pageant officials clearly were angry about the interruption, but
declined comment.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
