<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Noriega-LatinAmerica     02-26 0553</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Noriega-Latin America,0569</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>President's Attempt To Fire Strongman Could Erode Regional Support</HEAD>
<HEAD>With Panama, Bjt
^AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By REID G. MILLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Although President Eric Arturo
Delvalle could not dismiss the general who really runs the country,
his attempt will make it harder for other Latin American nations to
support Panama's government.
   Since that has long been a goal of Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega's
opponents, leading Panamanian dissidents and the U.S. State
Department were quick to cheer Delvalle's seemingly quixotic move.
   Its practical result was that Noriega stayed in his post as
military commander and the national legislature dismissed Delvalle,
althoguh he refused to relinquish the office and the United States
supported him.
   Delvalle's order to Noriega had the futility of tilting at
windmills because he had no way to back it up. Noriega, not the
civilian president, controls Panama's army, police, legislature,
and even the game wardens.
   It came as no surprise, therefore, that the commander of the
national police and the army's chief of staff quickly sided with
the general against the president.
   So, too, did the National Assembly, which is dominated by a
coalition of Noriega followers. In a 10-minute meeting early
Friday, it fired Delvalle and Vice President Roderick Esquivel.
   Delvalle said the assembly's action was unconstiutional, but his
only weapon against it is public opinion.
   Panama's Latin American neighbors have been slow to condemn
Noriega despite widespread allegations of involvement in drug
trafficking and other forms of corruption, even murder. The general
has denied all the charges.
   Noriega has drawn the United States as a straw man, accusing it
of trying to oust him and renege on a 1976 treaty turning the
Panama Canal to Panama at the turn of the century. Delvalle took
that stance himself before the change of heart.
   Latin American governments are reluctant to side with the United
States in any dispute involving a neighbor, if only to pacify their
own large numbers of left-leaning voters.
   But the spectacle of a legally sitting president firing his top
general, but being fired himself by the general's henchmen, is not
likely to sit well.
   ``This will isolate the government, no doubt,'' said Mario Luis
del Valle, vice president of the Panama Banking Association and a
member of the National Civic Crusade, which began clamoring for
Noriega's ouster last June.
   The Civic Crusade, a loose coalition of business, professional,
labor and political groups, has been trying for months to convince
other Latin American nations that Panama's government is not
legitimate.
   Aurelio Barria, president of the Chamber of Commerce and
Industry and an opposition leader, has carried that message
personally to the presidents of at least half a dozen Latin
American nations.
   Barria has obtained little support until now but the president,
or ex-president, predicted that soon would change.
   ``I think it will be another blow against Noriega and also
against Panama, which has had a terrible track record in recent
years,'' Delvalle said of his unsuccessful dismissal of the
general. ``I expect that the majority of the nations of this
hemisphere will be very reluctant to have relations with Panama.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   EDITOR'S NOTE: Reid G. Miller is roving correspondent in Central
America for The Associated Press. He has been based in San Jose,
Costa Rica, since January 1984.
</TEXT>
