<1ST_LINE>r a AM-NoriegaResponse     02-26 0385</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Noriega Response,0396</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Panamanian General Issues Assurance To American People</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Panama, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD COLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Panamanian strongman Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega
said Friday he's still a friend of the United States and U.S.
interests in his country ``shall remain intact, undisturbed and
unharmed'' despite a leadership struggle there.
   Noreiga's statement was issued by his Miami attorneys after
Panama's legislative assembly removed the president and vice
president early Friday. The president had tried to remove Noriega.
   ``These events are strictly internal to Panama,'' Noriega said.
   His attorneys declined to speculate as to whether Noriega would
step down.
   ``Our roles here are as lawyers, not as foreign policy or
domestic policy advisors,'' said Neal Sonnett, who read Noriega's
statement at a news conference.
   ``Conditions in Panama, as we understand it, are calm,'' Sonnett
said. ``That's a domestic political situation that's going on down
there.''
   Noriega was indicted three weeks ago by federal grand juries in
Miami and Tampa on charges of allowing drug traffickers to use his
country as a base for smuggling into the United States.
   Sonnett said he last spoke with Noriega about 10 days ago.
Friday's statement was issued after consultation between Noriega's
advisers and his defense team in Miami, Sonnett said.
   ``All American interests in the republic are and shall remain
intact, undisturbed and unharmed,'' the statement said. ``The
general reiterates that he is now, and has always been, a friend of
the United States of America. Those American politicians who have
suggested otherwise, and who advocate hysteria, act with a reckless
disregard for the truth.''
   Panama's legislative assembly removed President Eric Arturo
Delvalle and the vice president from office during an emergency
session. Its action followed Delvalle's order that Noriega step
down.
   Hours after Delvalle's announcement Thursday, Roberto Eisenmann,
exiled publisher of Panama's leading independent newspaper, La
Prensa, received word that soldiers had again closed the newspaper.
It was closed down last year for six months, reopening in January.
   Richard Gregorie, chief assistant U.S. attorney in Florida's
southern district, has said that if Noriega were to leave Panama,
``we would attempt to extradite him like any other dope dealer.''
   If Noriega were tried and convicted of all charges, he could
face up to 145 years in prison and fines of more than $1.1 million.
</TEXT>
