<1ST_LINE>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     02-26 0300</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0308</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Only Scattered Precipitation As Most Of Nation Gets Fair Weather</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The sky was clear over much of the nation Friday as two large
areas of high pressure over the Rockies and the Southeast swept
most clouds away.
   There were only a few areas of spotty precipitation.
   Light snow or flurries extended across eastern Upper Michigan,
northern New England, and western and upstate New York.
   Isolated showers dampened Arizona, New Mexico, western Texas and
northwestern Washington state.
   Southwesterly wind of 15 to 25 mph with gusts around 35 mph blew
up the middle Mississippi Valley as far as southern Michigan,
carrying warm air into the region and pushing temperatures into the
40s or 50s.
   The temperature hit 71 as far north as Emporia, Kan.
   Temperatures were mostly in the 20s across western and northern
Pennsylvania, New York state and northern New England, and a freeze
warning was issued overnight over parts of northeastern and
north-central Florida.
   Temperatures around the nation at 2 p.m. EST ranged from 16
degrees at Gunnison, Colo., to 83 at Palm Springs, Calif., and Gila
Bend, Ariz. The low for the day was 17 below zero at Gunnison.
   For Saturday, snow was forecast from the upper Ohio Valley
through New Jersey and New England. Scattered showers were forecast
over California, and from southern Texas across the central Gulf
Coast region.
   Highs in the 20s, 30s and 40s were predicted from North Dakota
across the northeastern quarter of the country; in the 40s in the
mountains of Colorado and western Wyoming; in the 70s across the
southern Plains, Louisiana and southern Florida; in the 70s and low
80s over much of California and the desert Southwest, and in the
50s or 60s over much of the rest of the nation.
</TEXT>
