<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Delvalle Bjt   02-26 0542</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Delvalle, Bjt,0556</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ousted President Gained Respect in Attempt to Oust Noriega</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Panama, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By REID G. MILLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eric Arturo Delvalle, called a puppet
of Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega a few days ago, may have lost the
presidency but he has gained respect.
   After 2{ years in the obscurity of Panama's presidency, he went
on television Thursday and ordered Noriega, the man who is really
in charge of the country, to leave his post as military commander.
   On one side of the contest was a man with high political office
but no power, on the other a man with no political office but
control of the army, navy, air force, police and national
legislature.
   A colonel Delvalle appointed to succed Noriega declined the job.
Other officers rallied around their boss. The National Assembly
convened for 10 minutes, long enough to declare Delvalle an
ex-president.
   The legislature's action was unconstitutional, Delvalle said,
and the United States continued to recognize him as president, but
it was clear that he had lost.
   Delvalle, 51, was the fifth president in six years of a nation
whose presidents serve at the pleasure of the military. He said he
would take his case to the Supreme Court, but acknowledged that his
chances there were ``very slim because it also is controlled by
General Noriega.''
   Even so, he refused to relinquish the office. ``I am the
president of Panama this morning,'' he said Friday.
   By Friday afternoon, the two remaining numbers to the five-line
telephone system to Delvalle's residence were answered by a
recording: ``Because of damage to the system, the number you have
dialed is being repaired.'' The other three lines were cut Thursday
night.
   Delvalle was vice president in the fall of 1985. Noriega moved
him up after dismissing President Nicolas Ardito Barletta for
recommending an independent investigation into the death of one of
the general's leading opponents, Hugo Spadafora.
   The dead man's relatives claim Noriega was behind the killing.
Spadafora's headless body was found stuffed in a canvas U.S. Mail
bag in Costa Rica.
   He had been threatening to offer proof of Noriega's involvement
in drug trafficking, the same charge on which two federal grand
juries in Florida indicted the general earlier this month.
   Before becoming vice president in the 1984 election that
opponents claim was rigged, Delvalle had not held public office. He
had spent most of most of his time since graduating from Lousiana
State University running a family sugar mill.
   When asked Friday whether he regretted getting into politics, he
said:
   ``No, not at all. I think when you have an opportunity to serve
your country and you believe you can, you have to take the risks
involved.
   ``I discussed it fully with my family before running for vice
president and we knew it would be a difficult task. But I thought
that I could help and maybe I could make the difference.''
   He shrugged and added: ``I couldn't.''
   Just last month, retired Gen. Ruben D. Paredes had urged
Delvalle to act. The former Panamanian military commander said the
president should ``look at the tomb of his father, be a man and do
his part to tell Noriega'' it was time to go.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880226-0196 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-26-88 1915EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-FALNSentences     02-26 0509</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-FALN Sentences,0527</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Four FALN Activists Sentenced In Escape Plot</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED WHITE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The leader of a Puerto Rican independence group
and three sympathizers who plotted to spring him from prison with
rockets, grenade and a helicopter were sentenced to prison terms of
up to 15 years Friday.
   ``Those who take up the sword, die by the sword,'' U.S. District
Judge William Hart said in sentencing FALN leader Oscar Lopez and
the others.
   Lopez, 45, drew 15 years in prison for masterminding the scheme
to free himself and another inmate from the federal prison at
Leavenworth, Kan., in 1986. The FBI infiltrated the plot almost
from the beginning and broke it up.
   Lopez's co-defendants received prison terms ranging from three
to five years.
   ``The conduct which has brought the defendants to this court is
not their political beliefs,'' the judge said.
   ``In this country political beliefs are protected by the
Constitution, but by planning a prison escape with explosives, such
conduct goes beyond that protection.''
   Lopez was convicted of conspiracy in December along with
Grailing Brown, a fellow inmate and murderer; Dora Garcia, Lopez's
former sister-in-law, and Jaime Delgado, a counselor at
Northeastern Illinois University.
   Prosecutors said the group conspired to use rockets, hand
grenades and a helicopter to free Lopez, who was serving a 55-year
sentence for a 1981 seditious-conspiracy conviction. He was
transferred to another prison.
   Brown was sentenced to five years in prison; Delgado, 34,
received four years, and Garcia, 37, three years. Lopez had faced a
maximum of 25 years in prison, Ms. Garcia and Delgado faced 15
years each and Brown five.
   Defense attorneys had denied their clients engaged in violent
acts.
   ``Lopez views himself as a freedom fighter above the law,''
Assistant U.S. Attorney Daniel Gillogly told the judge. ``He
provided the leadership and the direction of the conspiracy.''
   Lopez ``believes human life is expendable,'' said Assistant U.S.
Attorney Deborah Devaney.
   Lopez said Friday that authorities and inmates at Leavenworth
had made threats against his life.
   ``I do not deny that I love my people,'' he told the judge. ``I
love my country Puerto Rico. I will do anything necessary _ when an
injustice is committed _ to fight it.''
   Hart had planned to sentence the defendants at a closed hearing
in the federal Metropolitan Correctional Center because of
outbursts by Puerto Rican activists at the defendants' trial, but
later decided to do it in open court.
   Ms. Garcia made a plea for leniency Friday, but Ms. Devaney
dismissed her contention that she is ``generous and loving.''
   ``What compassion did she show for the guards at Leavenworth who
were going to be riddled with bullets?'' the prosecutor asked.
   FALN is a Spanish acronym for Armed Forces for National
Liberation. The group seeks independence for Puerto Rico. It has
been linked to more than 100 bombings or planned bombings since
1974 in Chicago, New York and elsewhere.
   Authorities say at least six people have died and 100 have been
injured in FALN violence in the United States.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
