<FILEID>AP-NR-02-26-88 1942EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Panama-Questions     02-26 0688</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Panama-Questions,0713</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Questions and Answers On Panama's Importance to the United States</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALINA GUERRERO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Following are questions and answers
about Panama's importance to the United States and the dispute over
the leadership of Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega:
   Q. Why is Panama important to the United States?
   A. Panama is vital to the United States, both because of the
Panama Canal, linking the Atlantic and Pacific oceans, and its
strategic location.
   Access to the S-shaped country is critical to control of the sea
lanes in the Caribbean as well as of links to South America and the
Far East. From Panama, forces can be quickly deployed to Central
and South American points.
   Q. Is it that vital?
   A. Yes. The United States helped create Panama by recognizing
its independence when it seceded from Colombia on Nov. 3, 1903, and
deployed the U.S. Navy to deter Colombia from reconquering it. The
United States financed and built the canal, owned it and ran it as
a wholly-owned U.S. government company until President Jimmy Carter
and Panamanian leader Omar Torrijos signed treaties in 1977 that
would hand ownership to Panama.
   Q. What is the canal's status now?
   A. Panama owns the canal, which is administered by a joint
U.S.-Panamanian commission. Complete administration, control and
defense of the waterway will be handed over to the Panamanians by
the year 2000.
   The Carter-Torrijos treaties also abolished the Panama Canal
Zone, a 10-mile strip of land flanking the waterway that had been
U.S. territory. U.S. military forces in the Southern Command are
allowed to remain in forts and bases to defend the zone.
   Q. What does the Southern Command do?
   A. The U.S. Southern Command has about 10,000 officers and
servicemen and coordinates all U.S. military activity from south of
the U.S.-Mexico border to Tierra del Fuego, in Argentina, and
Antarctica. Among other tasks, it does contingency planning for the
defense of Latin America, including training of Latin American
troops in anti-guerrilla warfare. Part of that is carried out under
provisions of the 1947 Inter-American Defense Treaty.
   Q. Will the United States turn the canal over to Panama?
   A. It has to, if the treaties are to be respected, although at
the time Carter signed the accords now President Ronald Reagan and
other conservatives in the Republican Party opposed the move.
   Q. Could current troubles affect operation of the canal?
   A. Since the unrest started last June, there has been no
disruption in operation of the canal. Officials say there is no
cause for concern.
   Q. Why is the United States opposed to Noriega's continued
leadership?
   A. He had been considered useful at times in some intelligence
operations, but the mounting controversy over his purported
involvement in illicit activities from drug trafficking to the
assassination of political opponents has lost him credibility in
Washington.
   His presence also runs counter to the trend toward civilian
governments in Latin America.
   The United States wants a functioning democracy in place when
the canal is turned over to Panama to help ensure its security.
Noriega maintains democracy already exists.
   Q. How was President Eric Arturo Delvalle ousted?
   A. Delvalle fired Noriega Thursday evening. Hours later the
legislature, dominated by Noriega supporters, deposed Delvalle in a
10-minute session. It claimed he acted unconstitutionally in firing
Noriega. The officer corps stood by Noriega.
   Q. Have relations between Panama and the United State been
strained before?
   A. Yes, several times. The last big confrontation was Jan. 9,
1964, when students rioted in a dispute over flying the Panamanian
flag alongside the Stars and Stripes in the Canal Zone. This led to
disputes over the then- existing treaties governing the zone, and
eventually to the Carter-Torrijos negotiations.
   Q. When did present tensions start?
   A. Last June, after Noriega's recently retired second in
command, Col. Roberto Diaz Herrera, went public with charges of
illicit activities. The allegations had circulated for a long time,
but were never on record before from one of Noriega's associates.
   Noriega denies the allegations and blames U.S. rightists who
oppose turning the canal over to Panama for provoking the problems.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880226-0198 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-26-88 0004EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-NevadaGOP     02-26 0342</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nevada GOP,320</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Republicans Revise Straw Poll Numbers In Nevada; Dole, Kemp
Benefit</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRENDAN RILEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CARSON CITY, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   State Republican Party officials
revised their Feb. 18 presidential straw poll numbers Thursday
after turning up 1,276 uncounted ballots, including some taken home
by a precinct meeting captain the night of the poll.
   After the revision, Vice President George Bush remained the
winner with 27 percent. But the undecided vote _ listed as 23
percent previously _ was revised downward to 22 percent. Kansas
Sen. Bob Dole, whose original tally was 22 percent, had 23 percent
after the revision.
   Rep. Jack Kemp moved ahead of former television evangelist Pat
Robertson, who dropped two points to 13 percent as Kemp rose one
point to 14 percent.
   The remaining 1 percent went to former Delaware Gov. Pete du
Pont and former Secretary of State Alexander Haig, both of whom
have dropped out of the race.
   The final numbers are: Bush, 1,672; Dole, 1,480; undecided,
1,391; Kemp, 875; Robertson, 846; du Pont, 42; Haig, 8.
   While the numbers and percentages changed slightly and
Robertson's official tally slipped below that of Kemp, Robertson
supporters were still claiming victory by combining undecided
ballots and votes for their candidate.
   Steve Wark, Robertson coordinator in Nevada, has said most of
the undecided votes were cast by Robertson supporters as part of a
strategy to control later voting for delegates to upcoming county
conventions.
   Asked what happened on the night of the straw poll, state GOP
Chairwoman Sally Vitkus-McKinney said, ``I really don't know.''
   Hal Steiner, state party vice-chairman who was in charge of the
ballot counting, said part of the problem was the number of
precinct captains involved in the counting process. He said there
were 50 captains in Clark County alone under pressure to get the
numbers in quickly.
   Asked about the fact that only 82 percent of the vote was in
while party leaders were claiming 100 percent, Steiner added, ``In
the scurry of things, it's hard to tell an exact percentage.''
</TEXT>
