<DOCNO> AP880226-0202 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-26-88 0150EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-KorbSuit     02-26 0566</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Korb Suit,550</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Raytheon Exec Sues Former Navy Secretary, Three Others</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NORMAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALEXANDRIA, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A defense contractor executive who lost
his job after criticizing the Pentagon's budget priorities filed
suit Thursday against the former secretary of the Navy and three
others, accusing them of having him fired.
   The suit by Dr. Lawrence J. Korb, filed in U.S. District Court
here, requests a jury trial and asks for a minimum of $500,000 in
compensatory damages as well as punitive damages for violating his
First Amendment right of free speech.
   The suit names as plaintiffs former Navy Secretary John F.
Lehman Jr.; a former top aide, Melvyn R. Paisley; Assistant Navy
Secretary Everett Pyatt, and Carl M. Smith, a staffer with the
Senate Armed Services Committee.
   The lawsuit alleges the four men, by complaining directly or
indirectly to Korb's bosses at the Raytheon Co., ``intended to and
did penalize Dr. Korb for exercising the right of free speech
guaranteed to him by the First Amendment of the Constitution ....''
   ``As a direct and proximate result of the defendants' acts, Dr.
Korb has sustained and will continue to sustain substantial
monetary losses and has suffered and will continue to suffer mental
and emotional pain, anguish and humiliation,'' the suit says.
   The suit was filed on Korb's behalf by the American Civil
Liberties Union, which in 1986 had asked then-Defense Secretary
Caspar W. Weinberger to fire Lehman and his aides for their conduct.
   Weinberger instead admonished the three.
   Efforts to contact Lehman and the other defendants Thursday were
unsuccessful.
   Korb, who worked for Weinberger for four years as the Pentagon's
assistant defense secretary for manpower, joined Raytheon _ a major
Navy contractor _ as a Washington vice president in 1985. With the
company's permission, he also joined the Committee for National
Security, a bipartisan group that seeks to encourage informed
debate on national security issues.
   In February 1986, Korb appeared with other group members at a
press conference and suggested the Pentagon could maintain its
strength with a smaller budget than that requested by President
Reagan.
   Following the news conference, Raytheon received phone calls and
letters from Paisley and Pyatt.
   The two Lehman deputies have acknowledged calling Raytheon and
suggesting Korb be told to stop speaking out against the
president's budget. The Pentagon's inspector general, in an earlier
investigation, concluded Lehman had not directed Pyatt and Paisley
to call Raytheon but clearly supported his deputies' actions.
   Korb's suit says Raytheon also was contacted about the same time
by Smith, a Senate committee staffer who oversaw missile budgets
affecting Raytheon.
   ``On information and belief, defendant Smith told them that
unless Raytheon silenced or removed Dr. Korb, he (Smith) would no
longer meet with anyone from Raytheon's Washington office,'' the
suit says.
   ``In direct and immediate reaction to the angry complaints and
explicit and implicit threats made by defendants Lehman, Pyatt,
Paisley and Smith, Raytheon terminated Dr. Korb as vice president
in charge of its Washington operations.''
   Korb is now the dean of the University of Pittsburgh's Graduate
School of Public and International Affairs.
   The suit filed Thursday is similar to one filed in December by
Korb against Raytheon. Ratheon has responded that it didn't fire
Korb, but offered him a transfer to another job that he declined to
accept. Korb has said he considered the offered job would have been
a demotion.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
