<1ST_LINE>u i AM-InheritedVillage 1stLd-Writethru a0765 02-26 0335</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Inherited Village, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0765,0339</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Man Inherits Village From Distant Relative He Hardly Knew</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: One graf SUBS for 8th graf pvs, Mrs. Borthwick-Norton ...
CORRECTING from Edward VII to Edward VIII. Picks up 9th graf pvs,
The new ...</NOTE>
<DATELINE>SOUTHWICK, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 52-year-old surveyor has inherited
30 farms and the entire village of Southwick, including two pubs,
two churches, a post office and 67 houses from a distant relative
he hardly knew, it was reported Friday.
   Robin Thistlethwayte said he was astonished when he was told
that Eva Borthwick-Norton, who died last week at the age of 96,
left him her 7,500-acre estate in Hampshire, about 60 miles
southwest of London near England's south coast.
   ``Although I had only met her a handful of times I think she
must have felt I was the best person to leave it to,''
Thistlethwayte was quoted as saying in today's Times of London.
   ``I have a lot of experience in running agricultural estates
with traditional standards of farming and I intend to continue with
the traditions as far as is possible in the 20th century,'' he said.
   The 300 residents of the pastoral village, nestling under the
slope of nearby Portsdown Hill, appeared delighted with her
decision.
   ``It seems she made sure the village will be preserved as it is,
which is wonderful news,'' Valerie Church, who runs the Red Lion
pub was quoted as telling the Today newspaper.
   The estate had been in the Thistlethwayte family for 250 years
until Lt. Col. Evelyn Thistlethwayte left it to his nephew, Hugh
Borthwick, in 1943. Following his death in 1950, his widow took
over its management.
   Mrs. Borthwick-Norton, a socialite who was friends with Wallis
Simpson, the American divorcee who forced the abdication of King
Edward VIII, had no children, and apparently decided to return the
estate to the Thistlethwayte family.
   The new owner, who lives in Banbury near Oxford, said he plans
to move to the village with his wife and three children.
</TEXT>
