<FILEID>AP-NR-02-26-88 2217EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-US-Panama 3rdLd-Writethru a0795 02-26 1211</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Panama, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0795,1,180</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Seeks to Minimize Talk of U.S. Intervention in Panama</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 2 grafs after 16th graf bgng, `He stopped,' to UPDATE
with Dole quotes</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan said Friday he has no plan to
intervene militarily in Panama, as U.S. officials scrambled to
assess ``a precarious position'' brought on in part by federal
drug-smuggling indictments of strong man Gen. Manuel Antonio
Noriega.
   But the State Department said the United States will continue to
recognize Eric Arturo Delvalle as president of Panama, despite a
parliamentary vote to oust him and replace him with Manuel Solis
Palma, who has been education minister.
   The National Assembly moved against Delvalle after he tried to
dismiss Noriega, who was indicted by federal grand juries in Miami
and Tampa, Fla., earlier this month.
   Amid the continuing political instability, Vice President George
Bush said the United States should do ``whatever is necessary'' to
protect American interests in the Central American country, which
include the militarily and economically vital Panama Canal.
   ``Noriega's gone bad, and he's proven he's trafficked in
narcotics,'' Bush said. ``... Noriega should go and in my view he
will go.''
   Reagan said he didn't think there was ``any appetite on the part
of anyone there, including Mr. Noriega, to take on our troops.''
   Responding to questions during a picture-taking session with
southern Republican Party leaders, the president said the United
States did not instigate Delvalle's move Thursday. But he also said
U.S. officials had been ``very much aware of it.''
   Asked whether the United States was contemplating military
intervention there, the president replied, ``No, I don't think
that's an answer.'' He declined to discuss other alternatives,
saying: ``We're not prepared to come up with any answers as yet.''
   Reagan said he thought ``there are some limits on what we can
do,'' but that ``we're looking at that situation, and our people
are meeting on it to see if there's anything we can do.''
   White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said earlier there was no
administration interest in a proposal by Sen. Alfonse D'Amato,
R-N.Y., to impose trade sanctions against Panama.
   Late Friday, following a series of meetings involving national
security officials, Fitzwater issued a statement saying that ``we
condemn all efforts to perpetuate military rule in Panama,
including efforts to remove President Delvalle from office.''
   The statement said ``we have also initiated a series of
consultations to learn the views of other countries in in the
hemisphere with regard to this situation.''
   Bush, campaigning to succeed Reagan, seemed to take a harder
line during a talk to a Greenville, S.C., audience.
   He told the South Carolina Press Association: ``We will do
whatever is necessary to protect American interests in Panama.
We've got treaty interests on the (Panama) Canal. I don't want to
rattle any sabers ....''
   ``But we would obviously as the United States, and I would,
reserve the right to do whatever is necessary, including military
force, to protect America's sacred interest in that region of the
world,'' Bush said.
   He stopped short of calling for military intervention, however,
saying the United States' past history of intervention in Latin
American affairs is ``what's hurting us in some areas now.'' Some
10,000 American troops are stationed in Panama.
   One of Bush's rivals for the Republican nomination, Senate
Minority Leader Bob Dole of Kansas, said during a campaign stop in
St. Louis that, ``The United States has had enough of Noriega and
will have nothing to do with any phony civilian, Noriega-puppet
government.''
   Dole warned the Panamian strong man: ``If you think you can put
the heat on us by meddling around with the canal _ we will do
whatever is necessary, including the use of military force, to
protect our security interests and the lives of American citizens.''
   From Capitol Hill, the administration got conflicting advice on
how to handle the situation.
   Senate Democrats urged caution, while D'Amato advocated the
trade embargo and Sen. Jesse Helms, R-N.C., called Noriega ``a
bum'' and said ``he ought to be thrown out.''
   Senate Majority Leader Robert C. Byrd, D-W.Va., said the United
States ``ought to keep cool'' and ``make haste slowly'' to give the
Panamanian people ample time to decide Noriega's fate.
   Sen. David Boren, D-Okla., chairman of the Senate Intelligence
Committee, said Washington should proceed with ``great caution,''
in consultation with neighboring nations, to protect U.S. national
interests in Panama.
   Rep. Dante Fascell, chairman of the House Foreign Affairs
Committee, said the United States should strongly support Delvalle
and that other nations in the region should do the same.
   Fascell, D-Fla., said the United States should increase
diplomatic pressure immediately, and added: ``At this point, we
certainly should be reviewing our options in the economic area.''
   Fitzwater confirmed that Delvalle had held talks at the U.S.
Embassy in Panama City before moving to oust Noriega on Thursday,
but he denied that the administration had lent any encouragement to
the Panamanian president.
   ``There's not a lot that we can say about impressions,'' the
spokesman said. ``The United States has a large interest there,
obviously. But we have tried to walk the line between what's
appropriate and what's not appropriate.''
   ``We have a precarious position,'' Fitzwater added. ``Yes, we
want him (Noriega) to stand trial (on the Miami indictment). Yes,
we want civilian government in Panama. But we want to be careful
not to unduly intrude upon the affairs of Panama.''
   At the State Department, spokeswoman Phyllis Oakley reiterated
what she termed ``our support for the supremacy of civilian
constitutional rule'' and said ``we continue to recognize President
Delvalle as the president of Panama.''
   Asked to describe the legal grounds for such recognition, she
said, ``I don't think it's for us to interpret their constitutional
law. We had regarded him as the president, we still regard him as
the president.''
   Mrs. Oakley also said the United States continues to recognize
Juan B. Sosa as Panama's ambassador in Washington. Sosa has
supported Delvalle, and he said he planned to remain in his post,
although Noriega told him by telephone Friday morning that he would
be replaced.
   Mrs. Oakley said Elliott Abrams, the assistant secretary of
state for Inter-American affairs met with Sosa on Friday, but she
wouldn't reveal details of the discussion.
   Asked if the United States had been in contact with Noriega, she
said, ``Not that I'm aware of.''
   ``Many people knew that we had been aware of the actions that
President Delvalle was contemplating doing,'' the spokeswoman said.
``We had been informed that the decision was President Delvalle's
own to make.''
   Reagan canceled a scheduled weekend visit to his Camp David,
Md., mountaintop retreat, but Fitzwater said it was because of a
scheduled social event at the White House on Sunday afternoon and
not because of the Panamanian crisis.
   Fitzwater said that while Delvalle had been in contact with
State Department officials before Thursday's ill-fated attempt to
oust Noriega, ``we did not urge him to take this action. He did it
on his own.''
   The spokesman also said he saw no immediate need for any
dramatic moves by the United States to protect citizens and
military forces in Panama.
   ``Panamanian authorities advise us there is no threat to
Americans in that country,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
