<2ND_LINE>AM-Smiling Shooter, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0793,0259</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Say Woman Waited, Then Opened Fire on Officer</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with two grafs to delete extraneous `Friday' in lead,
move up reference to car stopped in intersection. PICKS UP 2nd graf
pvs, `Evans and ...'</NOTE>
<DATELINE>ARLINGTON, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman out looking for a policeman to
shoot stopped in an intersection and waited Friday for one to find
her, then smiled as she fired point-blank into the officer's chest,
police said.
   Officer Buddy Evans, who had approached the car at 5 a.m.
because it appeared stranded, was saved by his bullet-proof vest,
said police spokesman Dee Anderson.
   Evans and another officer managed to subdue the woman, who was
sitting on the passenger side of an idling station wagon, he said.
   ``She has given us information that this was premeditated. She
was driving around looking for a police officer to shoot for some
time, then she decided to stop and let the officer come to her,''
he said.
   ``She turned around and smiled and then shot him,'' he said.
   The woman, Pamela Diane Takhar, 33, was arrested for
investigation of attempted capital murder and was held in Arlington
City Jail on $250,000 bail, Anderson said.
   Officers said the woman was ``not real lucid or coherent,'' said
Anderson.
   ``She thought by shooting a policeman and being put in jail, she
would be an example to other people not to do it,'' Anderson said.
   Officers said Evans was taken to Arlington Memorial Hospital for
an examination and was released.
</TEXT>
