<FILEID>AP-NR-02-26-88 0148EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Afghanistan     02-26 0357</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Afghanistan,0367</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Afghans Say Rebel Interim Government a `Dream'</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Retransmitting a0850 to restore keyword</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SCHEHEREZADE FARAMARZI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Afghanistan's Communist government
said Thursday a guerrilla proposal for an interim government while
Soviet troops withdraw was a ``hysterical'' dream, but a U.S. envoy
called it a good idea.
   Undersecretary of State Michael Armacost, visiting Pakistan,
said the plan announced this week by the seven-party guerrilla
alliance was a ``very welcome step toward the resolution of the
Afghan problem.''
   The alliance, led by Yunis Khalis and based in Pakistan,
proposes an executive council of all seven guerrilla leaders to
preside over a 28-member Cabinet of rebels, Afghan refugees and
``Moslems presently living in Kabul.''
   Soviet military forces entered Afghanistan in December 1979 and
an estimated 115,000 now are in the country helping fight the
guerrillas.
   About 3.5 million Afghans have fled to neighboring Pakistan.
Most live in border cities and camps that serve as bases and supply
points for the guerrillas.
   Thursday's editions of the Afghan Communist Party newspaper Anis
said the plan ``resembles more a hysterical and disturbed dream,''
Kabul radio reported.
   ``It is clear that this void and unfounded plan has no
legitimacy and therefore is unacceptable,'' the paper said, adding
that the insurgent proposal was like the ``story of sharing the
wolf's prey.''
   The radio also broadcast a Foreign Ministry statement that
``there is only one legal government in Afghanistan, which has been
recognized by 80 countries in the world.''
   Armacost arrived Wednesday to discuss progress toward Soviet
withdrawal. He met with President Mohammed Zia ul-Haq, and a U.S.
Embassy official said he also had ``frank and open'' discussions
with leaders of the Moslem guerrillas.
   Mikhail S. Gorbachev said Feb. 8 that Soviet troops will start
pulling out May 15 if U.N.-sponsored talks in Geneva between
Afghanistan and Pakistan bring a settlement by March 15, and
complete the withdrawal in 10 months. The talks are to resume
Wednesday.
   Pakistan demands a military settlement be accompanied by a
political one to ensure transitional stability. Washington, which
supports the guerrillas, has devoted most of its effort to
obtaining a withdrawal.
</TEXT>
