<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Salvador-Fighting     02-26 0311</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Salvador-Fighting,0324</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Salvador Rebels Lift Transport Ban</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANNIE CABRERA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leftist guerrillas called an
end to their transportation ban Thursday. At least three civilians
were killed and eight wounded during the three days it lasted,
police said.
   The guerrillas announced Monday on their clandestine Radio
Venceremos that all vehicles defying the ban risked attack.
   Police said guerrillas damaged four vehicles and a gasoline
station during the ban.
   The five leftist guerrilla groups which form the Farabundo Marti
National Liberation Front denied responsibility for civilian
casualties in a statement broadcast over Radio Venceremos.
   They blamed the U.S.-supported government of President Jose
Napoleon Duarte, saying the dead and injured were part of ``an
orchestrated campaign ... with the brutal intention of
incriminating'' the guerrillas for civilian casualties.
   The broadcast claimed the guerrillas sabotaged 30 electrical
distribution structures and killed or wounded 45 soldiers during
the transport ban.
   A land mine exploded Thursday as an army patrol sought to
dismantle a barricade on the Pan American Highway, wounding five
farmers and one soldier, according to judicial sources in Ilobasco,
about 35 miles northeast of the capital.
   City and rural traffic returned to normal Thursday. Dozens of
trucks, waiting at the Guatemalan and Honduran borders until the
ban ended, entered El Salvador, customs and migration officials
said.
   Police sources, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said
earlier this week that three workers were killed and five wounded
when guerrillas attacked a bus on a highway 10 miles northeast of
San Salvador.
   Police reported that in another incident, on the south side of
the capital, three civilians were injured when suspected guerrillas
ordered passengers off a minibus defying the ban and then tossed a
grenade into it.
   The rebels have called transportation bans regularly as part of
their economic sabotage campaign during the 8-year-old civil war.
</TEXT>
