<2ND_LINE>AM-Bus Shooting,0275</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Four Wounded In Gang Shooting On Crowded Bus</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A gunman wounded four people on a crowded
city bus and fled Thursday in an outbreak of the gang violence
gripping South Central Los Angeles, police said.
   Gang challenges were shouted back and forth on the bus before
the assailant shot one gang member in the chest with a .45-caliber
automatic handgun, said Lt. Bruce Hagerty. ``Then he shot
indiscriminately,'' Hagerty added.
   Three of the victims were teen-agers and one was an adult,
police said. Two of the wounded were believed to be gang members,
said police Lt. Fred Nixon.
   Two 15-year-old boys were taken to Martin Luther King Jr.
Medical Center, one in guarded condition with a chest wound, the
other in serious condition with a wound in the lower abdomen, said
spokeswoman Paula Wauls.
   A 15-year-old boy was in stable condition at California Medical
Center with a gunshot wound to the upper thigh, said hospital
spokeswoman Jane Twomey.
   The condition of the wounded adult was not immediately known.
   The shooting occurred in an area of the city plagued by gang
violence. More than 300 gang-related killings occurred in Los
Angeles County last year, many of them in the neighborhoods of
South Central.
   About 200 people gathered near the shooting scene. ``This is
every day,'' said Mary James, a bystander. ``I wouldn't mind seeing
the National Guard around here.''
   Earlier this week county Supervisor Kenneth Hahn suggested
National Guardsmen be used to quell the gang violence. Sheriff
Sherman Block said people wouldn't like the idea of troops in the
street.
</TEXT>
