<1ST_LINE>r a AM-PalisadesDrilling     02-26 0325</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Palisades Drilling,0333</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Rejects Environmentalist Appeal On Drilling</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB EGELKO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A major obstacle to oil and gas drilling
below the scenic bluffs at Pacific Palisades on the Los Angeles
coast was removed Thursday when the state Supreme Court rejected an
appeal by environmentalists.
   The unanimous vote of the six justices participating clears the
way for Occidental Petroleum Corp., which first applied for a
permit in 1970, to begin exploratory drilling within a few months
unless another court intervenes.
   ``Occidental is obviously very pleased,'' said Arthur Groman,
senior member of the company's board. ``This field, which we think
may be as much as 60 million barrels of oil, is a vital resource of
the United States.''
   Attorney Roger Diamond, who represented two residents
challenging the drilling and is a board member the environmental
group No Oil Inc., said opponents will ask a Los Angeles judge next
week to block the drilling while a challenge to the project's
Coastal Commission permit is pending.
   ``The (Supreme) Court now is less environmentally concerned than
it used to be,'' said Diamond, noting that the court had blocked a
version of the Palisades project in 1974.
   The court refused to hear an appeal of a lower-court ruling
upholding the city's 1985 approval of the drilling project. Justice
Stanley Mosk, whose son, Richard, is one of Occidental's lawyers,
did not participate in the ruling.
   Occidental plans to seek quick city approval of a water drainage
system to stabilize the cliffs, site of a destructive 1957
landslide. Drilling could then begin.
   Opponents suffered a setback Monday when a Los Angeles City
Council panel voted 3-2 against withdrawing city approval of the
project.
   Occidental has estimated that 25 million to 60 million barrels
of oil and 50 billion to 120 billion cubic feet of natural gas can
be found 10,000 feet below ground at the site. Opponents have
called the estimates inflated and speculative.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
