<HEAD>Arizona Senate Kills King Holiday Proposal</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Arizona Senate on Thursday rejected a
proposal to let voters decide whether to create a holiday honoring
the Rev. Martin Luther King Jr.
   The 15-12 vote against a referendum clears the way for the
Legislature to decide the matter for itself.
   The Republican-controlled Legislature has killed such holiday
proposals for many years, citing the cost of another paid holiday
for state workers.
   But Democratic Gov. Bruce Babbitt ended his term in 1986 by
creating a paid holiday by executive proclamation in honor of the
slain civil rights leader.
   Babbitt's successor, Republican Evan Mecham, rescinded the order
in 1987, triggering international boycotts of the state by
musicians and convention groups.
   Mecham has since been impeached on charges that he tried to
conceal a campaign loan, and also awaits criminal trial on similar
allegations.
</TEXT>
