<FILEID>AP-NR-02-26-88 1124EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a i PM-LifeAbroad-Polygamy Adv03   02-26 0943</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Life Abroad-Polygamy, Adv 03,0975</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv03</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Thurs PMs March 3 or Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>LIFE ABROAD: Ivory Coast _ Polygamy Persists Despite Ban</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto</NOTE>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   This is one of a series of periodic reports by
Associated Press correspondents around the world on the way of life
in other countries.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>BY PETER CHILSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ABIDJAN, Ivory Coast (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Polygamy was banned in this West
African country more than 20 years ago, but it persists for much of
the population because it makes life easier _ at least for the men.
   ``One woman is not enough for an African man,'' said Soumahoro
Mekinhui, a 64-year-old retired civil servant who has four wives
but is not sure how many children he has. ``Every woman has her
role. They clean house, wash clothes, prepare food, and care for
the children.''
   While the government doesn't try to enforce its ban on polygamy,
debate erupts every year over the practice and it always ends up
inconclusive.
   But there's no debate in Mekinhui's home. He is a Moslem and his
religion permits him to have four wives. The only question is the
number of children.
   ``I don't know how many there are exactly, perhaps 24,'' he said
one recent evening, relaxing in a stuffed vinyl chair at home.
``They are too numerous.''
   Large families are traditional in many parts of Africa because
children, preferably males, can help support the family and
perpetuate the husband's name.
   As Mekinhui spoke to a reporter, a 2-year-old boy wandered into
the room in his underwear and climbed onto his father's lap. His
wife Bakayoko, 38, the fourth and youngest of the four, sat in a
chair across from him, breast-feeding a year-old son, Chialo, in
one arm and holding a sleeping 2-year-old in the other.
   She was the only one of the wives at home. The others were
visiting their families, and Bakayoko was left to do the work of
all of them.
   Her day began at 4:30 a.m., which she said is her usual waking
hour even when the other wives are home to help with the work.
   She had prepared the family's food and washed the clothing. She
spent part of the day selling fruit at the market, but at noon and
in the evening she was home to prepare meals and look after her
children.
   ``This is a woman's life,'' she said. ``There's never a dispute
between me and the other wives. I do what work I have to do. It's
not too much for me.''
   ``My women are good,'' Mekinhui said. ``There are those in other
households who are impatient and always fight. But not in my
house.''
   Marie Antoinette Aoulou, producer on an Ivorian television show
on women, said that because women outnumber men by a large margin
in the country, many women could not marry unless they agree to a
polygamous marriage.
   As such marriages remain outside the law, the wives' only
recourse in marital disputes is to leave, said Yves Roux, chief
lawyer at the Ministry of Justice.
   ``We Africans like to live in community,'' Roux added.
``Children are a gift of God, a source of wealth. They play an
important economic role for the family.''
   He said the government banned polygamy mainly because costs of
living rose as the country developed.
   ``The government wanted families to adapt to the new economic
situation, to restrain spending.''
   Polygamy also runs counter to efforts at population control and
has the potential to cause friction between religious groups.
   In nearby Nigeria, black Africa's most populous nation, Roman
Catholics criticized a recent population-control policy limiting
women to four children each. Church leaders said this would permit
the polygamous Moslem population to expand at the expense of
monogamous Christians.
   About one-third of Ivory Coast's 10 million people are
Christians. The rest are Moslems or animists, both of whom practice
polygamy.
   Roux estimates that more than half the nation practices
polygamy, but exact numbers of polygamists are not known. Roux
added that some men call their additional wives mistresses,
clouding even more any attempt to determine the fullest extent that
polygamy is practiced.
   He said the Ivory Coast government has been concerned about
disturbances caused by disputes in polygamous families.
   In interviews here, children of polygamous marriages complained
of families divided by jealous wives, and of nasty disputes among
children.
   ``There are always personality problems between the women, and
often the disputes are uncontrollable,'' said Ramatou Traure, an
unmarried seamstress in Abidjan, whose father had three wives.
``The worst is when the women use black magic against each other.''
   Nonetheless, some Ivorians believe the ban on polygamy should be
lifted or at least modified to give people a choice.
   Once a year, at least, the polygamy ban comes up for debate with
people discussing it in the streets, in offices, on the radio and
the television, and in the newspapers.
   ``Polygamy is still common in the cities and villages,'' wrote
Narcisse Haquat, a professor at the national university, in the
official newspaper, Fraternite Matin. ``To legalize polygamy would
be to take into account the sociological reality.''
   Reality includes the rising costs of maintaining multiple wives.
   ``It ruins the household ecomony,'' said Ibrahim Diallo, a
Moslem cafe owner in Abidjan. ``The man is always paying for food
and supplies for his women and children.''
   Mekinhui, who said he lives on a monthly pension the equivalent
of $175, acknowledged that it is difficult to make ends meet. But
he added that the burden is an honor, a man's responsibility.
Besides, he observed, his older sons help support him.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Thurs PMs March 3</NOTE>
</DOC>
