<1ST_LINE>a i PM-India-GoldenTemple Adv04   02-26 0787</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-India-Golden Temple, Adv 04,0812</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv04</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Fri PMs March 4 or Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Sikh Radicals Again Control Golden Temple</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DILIP GANGULY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AMRITSAR, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   No sand-bag bunkers bar the way, and Sikh
radicals aren't waving rifles and submachine guns menacingly. But
inside the Golden Temple, bearded young men look as determined as
nearly four years ago when Indian troops stormed Sikhism's holiest
shrine to dislodge militants.
   Today, Sikh radicals are again in control of the 17th-century
sanctuary, the seat of Sikh temporal power which has served as the
base for their six-year campaign for a separate nation in the
Indian state of Punjab.
   Police in Amritsar estimate that 100 to 200 Sikh radicals, most
of them armed, are inside the shrine at any given time, slipping in
and out almost at will.
   ``They are a determined lot, ruthless killers. We are up against
very nasty people,'' said Mohammad Izhar Alam, the Amritsar
district police chief.
   Again, the radicals are vowing to resist intrusion. But now they
say they will carry the battle well beyond the walled temple
complex.
   ``We have arms and very, very committed men,'' said Nirvar
Singh, one of the top Sikh militant leaders in Punjab. ``This time
if we are attacked, the army will have to fight us all over
northern India.
   ``It will be real bloodbath in true Sikh tradition.''
   As he spoke during an interview with The Associated Press in a
windowless room of the temple, about 20 young Sikhs looked on.
   ``Warriors of the faith,'' Singh called them.
   ``Each of these men can die for the faith and we have thousands
of them all over northern India.''
   The evidence is that, despite 35,000 police and 50,000
paramilitary troops in Punjab, the militants operate freely in the
northern state bordering Pakistan.
   They have been blamed for about 300 deaths in the state since
January. In the same period last year, 135 slayings were reported.
   At least 17 visitors to the Golden Temple, including a woman,
have disappeared this year. All are believed to have been killed by
the militants on suspicion of being police spies.
   A classified police document shown to The Associated Press says
the militants in Punjab have at least 200 AK-47 assault rifles,
1,000 Thompson submachine guns, 1,200 sten guns, 50 self-loading
rifles, 10 light machine guns, 250 Enfield rifles, 800 revolvers,
and a large number of hand grenades.
   In almost every Sikh home, too, is a 3-foot sword, kept shining
and sharp under a religious obligation of the martial faith founded
about 500 years ago as an alternative to the era's warring Hindus
and Moslems.
   Alam, the police chief, said authorities could clear the shrine
of militants if necessary, but he questioned the costs.
   ``We can storm the shrine, but it has to be a political decision
because the consequences will be far-reaching,'' he told a reporter.
   Sikhs, who make up 2 percent of India's 780 million people, have
traditionally been the sword-arm of the Indian army. Many consider
it a sacrilege for security forces to enter their shrines.
   The 1984 assault on the Golden Temple left 1,200 people dead,
most of them Sikhs. It so angered two Sikh bodyguards of Prime
Minister Indira Gandhi that they assassinated her five months later
in New Delhi.
   S.S. Virk, the senior paramilitary officer in Amritsar, also
expressed fear that driving Sikh radicals from the temple could
backfire and build support for them.
   ``Clearing the Golden Temple of the terrorists is not a very
difficult task, but after that what?'' said Virk, who is the deputy
director general of the Central Reserve Police Force.
   Forty miles to the north, in the village of Haruwal, a young
Sikh ventured an answer: ``If police enter the Golden Temple we
will declare a war.''
   He refused to give his name, but declared: ``Seven of us from
this village have been to Pakistan and we have enough arms to
strike at will.''
   The village is a half mile from Pakistan, which denies India's
repeated charges that it is supporting the Sikh rebels.
   To the south at Fattu Bheela village, where the radicals
recently killed three members of one family, Sikh farmer Gurven
Singh said he knew the militants were killing innocent people.
   ``But I cannot support police entering our shrines to get them.''
   In Amritsar, a spokesman for the Panthic Committee, an umbrella
group of radicals, vowed to kill ``any enemy'' entering the Golden
Temple.
   ``We have a hit list. If and when anyone from that list comes
here, we kill them,'' said Giani Jagir Singh. ``We will kill them
with our bare hands, so much is our anger.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Fri PMs March 4</NOTE>
