<1ST_LINE>a e PM-APonTV-DaybyDay Adv29   02-26 0849</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-AP on TV-Day by Day, Adv 29,0868</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv29</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Monday PMs, Feb. 29</NOTE>
<HEAD>NBC Gives Unusual Premiere to New Series, `Day by Day'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHRYN BAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oh, yes, NBC wants you to spend a half hour in a
roomful of tots, not once but three times this week as part of the
unusual premiere schedule for ``Day by Day,'' a new comedy from the
creator of ``Family Ties.''
   Preview episodes air tonight and Thursday. The series premieres
in its regular time period on Sunday, in place of ``My Two Dads,''
which will move around the schedule during the ``Day by Day''
spring tryout.
   Thanks to witty writing and a pleasant disposition, ``Day by
Day'' proves a lot easier to take than the 30 minutes of darling
dialogue and squeaky tricycles the premise would seem to suggest.
   Linda Kelsey and Doug Sheehan star as Kate and Brian Harper, a
successful couple who have dropped out of the rat race to spend
more time with their infant daughter by running a day-care center
for toddlers in their home.
   The series premise is based on ``Family Ties'' creator Gary
David Goldberg's similar real-life experience.
   ``Day by Day'' has the same gentle humor as ``Family Ties'' and
is in many ways also reminiscent of ``Growing Pains.'' There's even
a kind of Michael J. Fox-Kirk Cameron stand-in _ C.B. Barnes as
15-year-old Ross, the Harpers' older son.
   In the first episode, Ross, who apparently heretofore had little
use for little ones, gets uncharacteristically interested in the
kiddie-minding business to impress Kristin, the Harpers' beautiful
assistant.
   Kristin: ``There's something so attractive about a man holding a
small child.''
   Ross (suddenly bolting after a romping child): ``C'mere!''
   There's ample opportunity for cheap sentimentality when Ross
promises little Justin that the boy's father will be at his
birthday party, not knowing Justin's parents are divorced.
   But as in ``Family Ties,'' the writing only flirts with
corniness: Ross launches into a speech about resenting his own
father's absence when he was a child. Brian counters that he's
given everything up now to be with his children. ``But I'm 15
now,'' Ross says. ``I resent you being around.''
   Added to the mix of not-too-cute tykes is Brian's self-involved
former co-worker, Eileen, still enthusiastically working her way up
the corporate ladder. She drops by to say she saw some children
playing and was moved by the sight.
   Eileen: ``I said, `Eileen, you've got a biological clock, but
your finger's on the snooze alarm.' Shouldn't there be some little
Eileens?''
   Kate: ``Eileen! I never knew you felt that way!''
   Eileen: ``I do, and coming over here always seems to cure me of
it.''
   ``Day by Day'' is the first of a number of new series premiering
in March. By the middle of the month, the networks' schedules will
little resemble the lineups they started with last fall.
   This week NBC adds ``The Highwayman,'' an action-adventure
series starring Sam Jones as a ``Road Warrior'' kind of character,
and featuring Jacko, the Australian ex-football player so popular
in the battery commercials; it will be the new lead-in for ``Miami
Vice.'' The ratings for that 4-year-old series have been so-so this
season. NBC will announce in March after watching its performance
following ``The Highwayman'' whether it will be back for a fifth
year. ``Sonny Spoon'' was recently added to the schedule following
``Vice.''
   ABC is adding ``Probe'' for a trial run. Parker Stevenson and
Ashley Crow star in the series based on an idea by Isaac Asimov
about crime-fighting scientists. The network is also launching
``Supercarrier,'' apparently hoping to reap the benefits of the
popular movie ``Top Gun.''
   The ABC comedy ``The Wonder Years'' also premieres this month in
its regular time period on Tuesday.
   CBS is adding a bunch of sitcoms to its drama-heavy schedule. On
Monday is ``Eisenhower & Lutz,'' about a one-man Palm Springs law
firm. The network will put three new comedies on Tuesday: ``Trial
and Error,'' about mismatched roommates; ``The Dictator,'' with
Christopher Lloyd as a deposed despot living in Queens, N.Y.; and
``Coming of Age,'' with Paul Dooley as a retired airline pilot
living in an Arizona retirement community.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Elsewhere in television:
   FROM HARD ROCK TO THOSE IN HARD TIMES _ Dan Aykroyd as Elwood
Blues of ``The Blues Brothers'' will be host of a live television
special _ no network as yet _ broadcast from one of the Hard Rock
Cafes _ no base city yet _ to benefit the homeless. What is known
is that Coca-Cola is sponsoring the event and it will be aired
sometime this year. Also, ``Saturday Night Live'' executive
producer Lorne Michaels will produce it. ...
   RAQUEL REDUX _ Raquel Welch, who played against type as a
professor with a degenerative disease in the NBC movie ``Right to
Die,'' takes another stretch next season in a new NBC movie, ``The
Education of Leda Beth Vincent.'' She plays a small-town cocktail
waitress who takes on the local school board to get an anti-Semitic
teacher fired.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Mon PMs, Feb. 29</NOTE>
