<DOCNO> AP880226-0226 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-26-88 1343EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a i AM-LinkingJapan Adv04   02-26 0902</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Linking Japan, Adv 04,0925</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv04</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Fri AMs, March 4, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Massive Projects Finally Link Japan's Main Islands</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By IRENE M. KUNII</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HAKODATE, Japan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   For the first time in their history, the
Japanese will be able to travel across the nation's four main
islands without taking a boat or a plane.
   Scheduled for opening soon is a transportation project that has
been likened to the opening of the transcontinental railroad in the
United States on May 10, 1869.
   The Japanese project includes the world's longest underwater
tunnel and a mammoth bridge system.
   But it has its critics and doubters who contend the project is
unnecessary and is going to cost more than Japan will be able to
afford in the years ahead.
   In March, the 33.4-mile Seikan Undersea Tunnel will replace an
80-year-old ferry service when it goes into operation as a railroad
line running under the Tsugaru Strait between Aomori on the main
island of Honshu and Hakodate in southern Hokkaido.
   In April, the Seto Ohashi, or Great Bridge, comprised of six
suspension bridges reaching five small islands in the Seto Inland
Sea, will open to both rail and vehicle traffic between Honshu's
Okayama region and Shikoku Island in southern Japan.
   For the first time, Japanese will be able use ground transport
to go from the northern island of Hokkaido to the main island of
Honshu, and on to Kyushu or Shikoku.
   The two projects represent the largest engineering schemes ever
attempted by Japan and each is a major technological feat in itself.
   Yet critics question the investment of more than $17 billion in
public money on what they contend is an outdated mode of
transportation _ the railroad _ at a time when Japan's rapid rate
of growth is slowing.
   Kyohei Kakumoto, a director of the Japan Transport Economics
Research Center and commentator on transportation issues, said the
projects were given the go-ahead by politicians in the 1960s, at
times of rapid economic growth and when forecasters predicted major
increases in rail use.
   ``The key point here is that even though planners were aware
they erred in their original forecasts, construction was still
allowed to proceed,'' Kakumoto said. ``And now that these projects
are complete the people are finding themselves concerned about the
lack of advantages.''
   The expressway portion of the bridge system is expected to
recover costs, which ran up to $8.7 billion over the 10-year
construction period, if tourism reaches projected levels. But
transportation officials acknowledge that the rail lines will
operate in the red in the tradition of the formerly state-operated
Japan National Railways (JNR), where the blueprints for the two
major projects originated.
   The Seikan Tunnel, tailored for 2.3 million rail passengers and
some 5 million tons of cargo each year, carries a price tag of $8.5
billion in overall construction outlays, $16.2 million in annual
maintenance costs and a yearly operating deficit of at least $23.1
million.
   A Seikan tunnel official, Mitsuaki Tanaka, argued that the
tunnel is justified because cargo and passengers will be
transported safely, regardless of weather conditions.
   It now takes travelers four hours to cross the strait by ferry
boat on waters that claimed the lives of more than 1,100 passengers
in a 1954 accident. When rail service starts up March 13, the
journey time will be cut by half.
   Kakumoto, a former Japan National Railways official who has
observed work on the both the tunnel and bridge since the start,
claimed the system will never be cost effective.
   ``The longer that tunnel is used, the larger the deficit will
become,'' he said. ``If the ferries had been allowed to continue
service we could have gotten by with keeping the deficit at its
present level and still have met the needs of the locals.''
   But Taizo Omiya, an engineer from Aomori who spent 10 years
working on the main Seikan tunnel, said the project should be
backed as a national undertaking.
   ``Compared to the defense budget the cost of the tunnel is
minimal. ... If it brings prosperity to the region many people here
feel it should backed by the government.''
   Thirty-four laborers lost their lives in the 16 years it took to
build the tunnel.
   Shikoku Island residents, responding to recent survey, were
divided in their opinions on the Seto Bridge, the first of three
scheduled causeways to connect Shikoku with Honshu. While 45
percent were listed as saying the new bridge to would improve local
lifestyles and spur development, 44 percent replied they were
unsure or that they expected the effects to be detrimental.
   Residents said they feared an influx of tourists would cause
problems for their underdeveloped rail and road system.
   In Aomori, businessman-historian Masao Mizuta echoed the local
view that only politicians wanted Japan's famed ``shinkansen''
(bullet-train) line to extend up from Morioka in neighboring Iwate
Prefecture.
   ``Actually the people here are more concerned about how the
disappearance of the ferries, which have been the center of life in
Aomori, will effect the region,'' Takada said. ``Even if the
shinkansen comes through the only direct benefits will be some ski
slopes and golf courses.''
   Both the tunnel and the bridge were built to accommodate the
bullet train, and local officials insist that the new line will
spur economic development in the backward regions of Aomori,
Hokkaido and Shikoku.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Fri AMs March 4</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880226-0227 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-26-88 1652EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a e AM-APArts:GlasnostTheater Adv29   02-26 0832</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-AP Arts: Glasnost Theater, Adv 29,0852</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv29</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Mon AMs, Feb 29 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Moscow Theater Makes a Splash in Munich</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERRENCE PETTY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MUNICH, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After years of Kremlin-imposed
restrictions on artists, Soviet drama director Genrietta Yanovskaya
finally knows she has the talent to please audiences abroad as well
as at home.
   ``The audiences here have been tremendous,'' Yanovskaya said
after her Moscow Youth Theater performed a long-banned work,
``Heart of a Dog,'' to sell-out Munich crowds.
   The audience was still shouting ``bravo'' and clapping
enthusiastically as Yanovskaya's cast made its seventh curtain call.
   Her troupe was one of six from the Soviet capital that performed
in the ``Moscow in Munich'' theater festival, whose West German
backers say reflects the sweeping Soviet reforms under Mikhail S.
Gorbachev.
   ``At last we (Soviet artists) have an opportunity to do the
things we want to do, to do the things we dream about,'' Yanovskaya
said in a backstage interview.
   Her long-time artistic collaborator, scriptwriter Alexander
Chervinsky, agreed. ``Before Gorbachev, we (artists) were punished
very badly'' by severe creative restrictions, he said.
   Gorbachev's reforms have made it possible not only for Soviet
theaters to stage controversial works but for the six Moscow
theaters to bring their shows to Munich.
   The Jan. 14-Feb. 6 festival showcased works that two years ago
would have never made it past Soviet officials because they focus
on such topics as the repression of past Kremlin regimes.
   Yanovskaya's troupe of young thespians staged a play based on
Mikhail Bulgakov's 1925 novel, ``Heart of a Dog,'' with a script by
Chervinsky.
   At the start of the play, shabbily dressed actors and actresses
stand at the edge of the stage screaming in dramatized terror
because of political repression in the 1920s and showing mock pain
because of Moscovites' hunger at the time.
   The satirical novel, in which a dog is surgically transformed
into a brutish low-level Soviet official who turns on his creator,
was banned by Soviet authorities until 1987. The novel has been
widely read in the West.
   That same year, the 47-year-old Yanovskaya received permission
to stage Chervinsky's version of Bulgakov's novel. Muscovites
packed her theater in the Soviet capital to see the performances.
   ``When we first got approval to do this play in Moscow,
everybody had forgotten about our theater because nothing that was
permitted was what people wanted to see,'' said Yanovskaya, who has
been in professional theater since the 1960s. ``Not even the taxi
drivers knew their way to the theater. Now everyone in Moscow
knows.''
   But Yanovskaya says that because people in her country were for
years harshly restricted in what they could perform, write or
otherwise create, the Soviet reforms are putting artists to an
unexpected test.
   ``Glasnost gave us more freedom in choosing what to do. But that
does not mean we always know how to make the right artistic
decisions. This is a real challenge,'' she said in Russian, with
Chervinsky translating her remarks into English.
   West German theater producer Jochen Hahn thought up the idea for
the ``Moscow in Munich'' theater festival and flew to Moscow to try
to put it together.
   The Union of Theater Producers of the Soviet Union, an
unofficial organization founded in 1986, put up half the $1.4
million cost for the Munich festival, Hahn said. The remainder came
from West German federal and local government grants, as well as
private and corporate sources, he said.
   ``We were interested in how theater people are working with
glasnost and perestroika,'' Hahn said, referring to the Russian
words for, respectively, openness and restructuring.
   ``We watched about 30 plays (in Moscow), and were surprised
about the openness'' displayed by theaters in dealing with
controversial topics, he said.
   Hahn says he had no problem getting official approval for his
proposal, ``despite the nightmare rumors I had heard about the
Soviet Union. It was just the right moment (because of Gorbachev's
reforms) for this happen.''
   However, that's not to say that theaters have been given carte
blanche in what they can stage and in how they do it. Theaters are
still required to get permission from the authorities before going
on with a show.
   Theater professionals in the Soviet Union also would like the
opportunity to do more performances in the West.
   ``I would love to play in New York some day. I would like to see
how I would be received by audiences in still other parts of the
world,'' said one young Soviet actress who performed in Munich,
speaking on condition that her name not be mentioned.
   Yanovskaya says Bulgakov's ability to find comedy in the
bleakest of circumstances is a trait she and her colleagues also
relied on heavily in the pre-glasnost days.
   ``You should not be too serious about yourself in this world. To
make it, you have to understand comedy. Comedy is the only thing
that helped us (artists) to survive,'' she said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Mon AMs, Feb. 29</NOTE>
