<1ST_LINE>r f PM-BusinessHighlights 2Takes   02-26 0545</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Highlights, 2 Takes,0568</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. economy expanded at a 4.5 percent
annual rate from October through December, the fastest pace in
almost two years, the government said.
   The growth in the gross national product was revised Thursday up
from an original estimate of 4.2 percent made a month ago.
   Three-fourths of the growth last quarter came from a buildup of
business inventories which was occurring at the same time that
consumer spending was plunging 3.1 percent.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Getty Petroleum Corp. has joined the brewing
contest over Texaco Inc., announcing it has bought $14 million
worth of Texaco stock and is seeking to acquire more.
   Getty Petroleum, which sprang from Texaco's 1984 takeover of
Getty Oil Co., said Thursday it would ask the Federal Trade
Commission to let it buy more than $15 million of Texaco's stock.
   Takeover strategist Carl C. Icahn, Texaco's biggest shareholder,
is attempting to win five seats on the company's board of
directors. Fellow takeover artist T. Boone Pickens has disclosed
plans to acquire a major Texaco stake and says he supports Icahn's
move.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>IRVINE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   AFG Industries Inc., which has made
unsuccessful bids for two other companies in recent years, has
agreed to be taken private by its chairman in a $940.5 million plan.
   The board of AFG, one of North America's leading glassmakers,
said Thursday it had signed a definitive agreement to support
Clarity Holdings Corp. offer to pay $33 a share for 94 percent of
its common shares, or $883.4 million.
   Clarity, headed by AFG founder R.D. Hubbard, would acquire the
rest of the stock for $33 a share in preferred stock or a
combination of cash and stock for a total of about $57.1 million.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Campeau Corp. has increased its hostile tender
offer for Federated Department Stores Inc. to $66 a share from $61,
and said it would consider sweetening the bid again if necessary.
   The move Thursday by Campeau _ which previously had offered $66
a share, about $5.84 billion, only as part of a negotiated merger
agreement _ came as Federated's board of directors met to consider
Campeau's offers and its own takeover alternatives.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   USG Corp. is keeping quiet about a Texas
partnership's $1.96 billion takeover offer for the nation's largest
producer of gypsum.
   ``At this time, we have nothing to say on any aspect of this,''
Paul Colitti, a spokesman for Chicago-based USG, said Thursday.
   The group led by oilmen Cyril Wagner Jr. and Jack E. Brown said
Wednesday it would pay $42 a share in cash for at least 21.5
million common shares, or less than half the total shares
outstanding. The group said it would exchange securities for the
rest of the stock.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BLOOMINGTON, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Northwest Airlines and flight
attendants were bargaining to avert a weekend strike, but a union
representing the workers said a walkout appeared likely.
   ``There's a 100 percent chance of a strike,'' William Genoese,
director of the International Brotherhood of Teamsters Airline
Division, said Thursday. ``As far as I'm concerned we're on a
collision course with Northwest Airlines to strike.''
   Flight attendants were preparing to strike at midnight tonight
if an agreement wasn't reached.
</TEXT>
