<1ST_LINE>r f PM-BusinessHighlights 1stAdd   02-26 0523</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Highlights, 1st Add,0545</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>HIGHLAND PARK, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chrysler Corp.'s possible sale of
its parts-making division prompted demonstrations outside corporate
headquarters by hundreds of angry workers shouting for a strike.
   ``You do whatever you need to do _ and you know what to do,''
United Auto Workers union Vice President Marc Stepp told more than
1,000 workers who marched Thursday in windy, 20-degree weather for
more than two hours.
   Chrysler says it is considering selling its 28,000-worker, $1
billion Acustar Inc. parts-making subsidiary. Stepp said the sale
threatens the job security of all Chrysler workers.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The railroad industry is riddled with workers
who drink large amounts of beer or use marijuana and other drugs on
the job, according to two Conrail crewmen involved in last year's
fatal Amtrak crash.
   Engineer Ricky L. Gates told a Senate committee Thursday that he
believed 10 percent or 20 percent of rail workers drink or use
drugs on duty. Brakeman Edward W. Cromwell guessed the figure was
more like 40 percent or 50 percent.
   The two men told the Senate Commerce Committee that when they
began their railroad careers 14 years ago, up to 80 percent of
their fellow employees used drugs or alcohol during working hours.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bank of New York Co. has tightened the noose
around Irving Bank Corp., winning government approval to proceed
with its $1.08 billion hostile bid and moving to oust the rival's
directors if they don't capitulate.
   The Federal Reserve Board and New York State Banking Board
concluded Thursday that a shotgun marriage of the two large New
York banks wouldn't hurt competition in the nation's biggest
financial center.
   The approvals were significant because they could signal more
hostile takeover attempts of banks, which have been rare.

</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Federal Communications Commission has
signaled to foreign governments that the United States remains
concerned about markets that have been closed or severely limited
to U.S. telecommunications manufacturers.
   The FCC stopped short Thursday of taking action that would
reciprocally exclude or limit foreign-owned companies from
participating in the U.S. market.
   However, Chairman Dennis R. Patrick said such measures ``are
still very much open, very much alive'' at the commission.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The British government said it would proceed with
the huge privatization of the state-owned electricity industry of
England and Wales, which is expected to raise $47.5 billion.
   The complicated sale, which the Cabinet approved Thursday, is
expected to take two or three years and would be the biggest of the
government's privatizations since Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher
came to power in 1979.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices fell Thursday as an afternoon selling wave wiped
out strong early gains. The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials, up
about 27 points at its midsession high, closed down 22.38 at
2,017.57.
   The dollar was mixed in narrow trading. Gold prices edged higher
in New York after falling sharply in Europe.
   Bond prices fell after a volatile session.
   Coffee futures prices fell sharply, reversing a five-month trend
on speculation that a tight supply situation may soon ease.
</TEXT>
