<1ST_LINE>r f PM-OilPrices     02-26 0333</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Oil Prices,0346</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fall Amid Oversupply Fears</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Crude oil prices have dipped below $16 for the
first time since December, reflecting worries about overproduction
and higher inventories.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange Thursday, contracts for
April delivery of West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark U.S.
crude, closed at $15.92 per 42-gallon barrel, down 54 cents from
Wednesday.
   It was the first time the near-month crude contract closed below
$16 since Dec. 21, when it settled at $15.16.
   Among March contracts for refined products, wholesale heating
oil closed at 45.22 cents a gallon, down 1.18 cents from Wednesday,
while unleaded gasoline settled at 45.37 cents per gallon, 0.98
cent lower.
   Analysts said technical factors and a report showing
larger-than-expected U.S. inventories helped to send prices lower
Thursday.
   The catalyst of the decline was a federal Energy Information
Administration report, issued Wednesday night, that showed U.S.
crude inventories up by 8.5 million barrels last week, said William
Byers, an analyst at Bear, Stearns & Co.
   That figure, much greater than the 1.88 million-barrel increase
reported Tuesday by the American Petroleum Institute, a
Washington-based trade organization, shook the market, which was
already edgy over continuing reports of growing production and
inventories.
   The market's confidence was shaken further when the near-month
crude contract broke below $16.37 in early trading. That had been
viewed as an important support level on the, they said.
   Declining prices on the London oil market overnight also
contributed to the tone of Thursday's market in New York, said
Donald Morton, vice president for energy futures at the Boston
office of Prudential-Bache Securities, Inc.
   ``Psychology in the market was already very weak, very
negative,'' he said. ``So it gave ground and just broke. It seemed
like everyone lined up on the sell side all day long.''
   But behind the recent trend lay one underlying cause, he said:
``There weren't any new rumors. There weren't any new reasons.
There weren't any new excuses. It was the same old reason:
oversupply.''
</TEXT>
