<1ST_LINE>r f PM-DollarAnniversary Bjt   02-26 0347</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dollar Anniversary, Bjt,0363</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Reached Its Peak Three Years Ago Today</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three years ago today, American tourists were
flaunting dollars in Paris and Tokyo while bargain-priced West
German cars rolled off arriving cargo ships.
   Feb. 26, 1985, marked the dollar's highest point of the 1980s _
a level that economists say will probably never be seen again.
   The strong dollar made Americans rich in the eyes of the world,
but contributed to a huge trade deficit and damage to American
industries unable to compete with a flood of inexpensive imports.
   Since then the dollar has lost roughly half its value against
the currencies of Japan, West Germany and some other trading
partners.
   Against the Japanese yen, for example, the dollar has fallen
from a little more than 260 yen to a little less than 130.
   The dollar has fallen less against the currencies of Canada,
South Korea and Taiwan, though, and is actually stronger now
against the currencies of Mexico and Brazil.
   The cheaper dollar has brought about an export boom and the
trade deficit has begun to shrink, although more slowly than almost
anyone had predicted.
   Meanwhile, the dollar has flattened out in recent months,
pinched between speculators who expect it to rebound and others who
say it has further to drop.
   The dollar's stability makes for boredom at the banks and
securities firms that specialize in trading currencies, where
volatility is crucial to lock in profits.
   ``This week has been about the deadest it's been,'' James
Hohorst, managing director for foreign exchange at Manufacturers
Hanover Trust Co., said Thursday.
   Currency traders are confident that the action will pick up,
though, because governments can't agree on the coordination of
economic policies that would allow for stable exchange rates.
   Hohorst, 33, recalls once worrying about whether to commit his
life to trading currencies because of the danger that governments
would agree on fixed exchange rates.
   ``But then I realized fixed exchange rates would depend on
responsible governments,'' he said. ``So I stopped worrying about
it.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
