<FILEID>AP-NR-02-26-88 0726EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Texaco-Getty Bjt   02-26 0558</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Texaco-Getty, Bjt,0577</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cousin of Texaco-Pennzoil Battle Now Wants Chunk of Texaco</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN C. GIVEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gasoline retailer Getty Petroleum Corp., cousin
of a Texaco Inc. takeover four years ago that later would bring
Texaco to its knees, has now joined the contest for buying chunks
of the troubled oil giant.
   Getty announced Thursday that it has bought $14 million worth of
Texaco shares and is seeking government permission to acquire more.
   The Jericho, N.Y.-based company, born of Texaco's 1984 takeover
of Getty Oil Co., said it would ask the Federal Trade Commission to
let it buy more than $15 million of Texaco's stock, in accordance
with government regulations.
   Getty is the third party holding _ or in the process of lining
up _ a large block of Texaco stock. But analysts said Getty was not
large enough to harbor any notions of swallowing Texaco.
   Rosario Ilacqua, an industry analyst at Nikko Securities Co.
International Inc., said ``$15 million is peanuts'' when it takes
$42 million to buy roughtly 1 million of Texaco's 243 million
shares.
   He suggested Getty might be hoping to make money on its stock,
or perhaps negotiate its holding into some Texaco assets in the
future _ either with the company or some other party or parties.
   George Friesen, who watches oil companies for the Dean Witter
Reynolds Inc. securities firm, also held that view.
   ``I suspect we'll have a number of smaller predators circling
the prey and relying on the bigger predators to do the job for
them,'' he said. ``I can't imagine Getty becoming a big player.''
   Last Friday, T. Boone Pickens, a takeover strategist who
controls Mesa Limited Partnership, an oil and gas concern, also
expressed interest in buying Texaco shares. He joined fellow raider
Carl C. Icahn, Texaco's biggest shareholder.
   Getty spokesman Stephen Salzman said that his company had not
been in contact with either Icahn or Pickens and was unwilling to
say if it would join Icahn's effort to gain a greater voice in
running Texaco.
   In late trading on the New York Stock Exchange Thursday, Texaco
stock stood at at $42.87{ per share, up 62{ cents.
   ``We believe that Texaco is an excellent company which is
substantially undervalued,'' Leo Leibowitz, Getty's president, said
in a statement. ``We are purchasing shares of Texaco for investment
purchases at this time.''
   Getty is one of the nation's largest independent marketers of
gasoline and refined products, doing business in 11 states in the
Northeast and Mid-Atlantic regions. Getty was known as Power Test
Corp. until January 1985, when it acquired Getty Oil's retail
operation and the Getty name.
   Getty's interest in Texaco coincides with Texaco's effort to
exit the refuge of federal bankruptcy court, sought nearly a year
ago because of a $10.53 billion judgment held against it by
Pennzoil Co.
   The judgment stemmed from a Houston jury's ruling that Texaco
had illegally interfered with move by Pennzoil to acquire Getty Oil
and bought Getty itself.
   In December, Texaco agreed to pay Pennzoil $3 billion in cash to
settle the dispute as part of an overall plan to reorganize and
emerge from bankruptcy.
   Shareholders are voting whether to approve that plan, with the
results due to be announced at a March 22 hearing in U.S.
Bankruptcy Court in White Plains, N.Y., Texaco's corporate home.
</TEXT>
