<FILEID>AP-NR-02-26-88 0829EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Chrysler-Acustar     02-26 0368</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Chrysler-Acustar,0380</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Angry Workers Demonstrate To Protest Possible Acustar Sale</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JANET BRAUNSTEIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Auto Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HIGHLAND PARK, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United Auto Workers union is
stepping up pressure aimed at discouraging Chrysler Corp. from
selling its $1 billion Acustar Inc. parts-making arm.
   More than 1,000 angry workers gathered outside Chrysler
headquarters in below-freezing temperatures Thursday chanting
``Strike! Strike!'' to protest the proposed sale of the
28,000-worker subsidiary, which represents nearly a fifth of
Chrysler's worldwide operations.
   ``You do whatever you need to do _ and you know what to do,''
UAW Vice President Marc Stepp told the demonstrators, which
followed a special meeting of the 140-delegate Chrysler bargaining
council representing the company's 49 UAW locals.
   Although the union can't legally call a national strike against
Chrysler over Acustar, Stepp said he will give local UAW unions
permission to strike on a plant-by-plant basis over unresolved
issues such as health-and-safety grievances.
   A series of local strikes at key Chrysler plants could shut down
the company nationwide just as easily.
   At least seven Chrysler locals have voted to seek strike
authorization and one, a key 4,000-worker stamping plant in
Sterling Heights, should receive authorization as early as next
week, Stepp predicted.
   Acustar, which has plants in Mexico and Canada as well as the
United States, represents nearly a fifth of Chrysler's worldwide
operations, already the leanest among the Big Three U.S. automakers.
   Chrysler has said it may sell Acustar because it doesn't want to
invest in the research needed to upgrade some operations. Chrysler
already buys 70 percent of its parts elsewhere.
   ``The potential sale of Acustar would generate funds for future
investments but the primary reason we would sell Acustar is
because, long-term, we want to concentrate our resources on new
product and powertrains rather than components,'' the company said
in a statement.
   ``Acustar's best chance to progress may be to operate as an
independent company free to pursue business opportunities beyond
Chrysler,'' the statement said.
   Workers say they are angry at the possible sale because they
made concessions and helped Chairman Lee Iacocca win loan
guarantees from the federal government to rescue the company from
the verge of bankruptcy at the beginning of the decade.
</TEXT>
