<FILEID>AP-NR-02-26-88 0831EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Switzerland-US     02-26 0246</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Switzerland-US,0254</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Bank Investigators Cut Short Swiss Trip As Row Flares</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BERN, Switzerland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four U.S. Congressional bank
investigators cut short a trip to Switzerland after being warned
that some of their alleged activity could constitute economic
espionage, Swiss authorities said Friday.
   Switzerland had allowed the staffers from the House Committee on
Energy and Commerce to hold talks earlier this month with
authorities and banks about Swiss rules on judicial assistance and
insider trading probes, foreign ministry official Alexei Lautenberg
said.
   The visit followed signing of a Swiss-U.S. agreement designed to
speed up cooperation in such cases last November. The committee
oversees the U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission.
   Several days into the visit, a Geneva bank alerted Swiss
authorities that the U.S. investigators allegedly overstepped their
mandate, demanding details on a possible Swiss link to a major
insider trading case involving Wall Street dealer Dennis Levine,
Lautenberg said.
   He said authorities warned the Congress staffers about Swiss
laws on economic espionage and banking secrecy and told them a
Swiss official would accompany them for their remaining interviews.
Thereupon the U.S. investigators left abruptly.
   Switzerland's ambassador in Washington, Klaus Jacobi, meanwhile
has tried to smooth the affair in talks with Rep. John Dingell, a
Michigan Democrat who heads the committee.
   Bern and Washington had lengthy diplomatic rows over exchange of
information in the Dennis Levine case and another U.S. probe in the
early 1980s involving Marc Rich, a commodities trader now based in
Switzerland.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
