<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Volcker     02-26 0410</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Volcker,0426</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Volcker Says Tax Increase May Be `Best Medicine' For Economic Woes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN ANTONIO, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A ``broad-scale consumption tax of
some sort'' may be the best medicine for the nation's economic
woes, former Federal Reserve Board head Paul Volcker says.
   ``I don't think we are approaching Doomsday,'' he said, speaking
Thursday before a seminar held by the National Association of
Industrial and Office Parks. ``I do not think we face inevitable
recession or inevitable inflation or a combination of the two.''
   ``I think we are in control of our destiny, but I don't think we
can take the future for granted,'' he said.
   New York stock traders blamed Volcker's remarks for helping kill
a morning stock rally Thursday, although he has publicly advocated
tax increases before.
   To alleviate the nation's trade deficit, foreign debts and
declining dollar, Volcker said, ``We need to start with the federal
budget deficit.''
   ``I think there's some amount of wishful thinking about the
budget deficit,'' he said. ``I'd like to think we can solve it all
by a little spending restraint, but I don't think that's possible.
   ``Certain elements of spending are going to increase, and you
know it,'' he said.
   A combination of spending cuts and tax increases are needed to
cure the deficit, he said.
   The newly reformed income tax structure should be left alone and
``given a chance to work,'' Volcker said. Instead, he recommended a
``consumption tax'' to raise revenue.
   As an example, Volcker cited ``a very sizeable increase in the
gasoline tax, which by world standards is relatively low. Is it
really so impossible to add 10 or 15 cents to the gasoline tax?''
   ``I do not think this problem is insoluble,'' Volcker said of
the budget deficit. ``I think it's quite readily soluble.''
   At a press conference after his speech, Volcker said the
``political pressure'' of this year's presidential campaign is
discouraging a meaningful discussion on the nation's large budget
and trade deficits.
   ``The tendency in democracies is to wait for a crisis,'' Volcker
said in his speech. ``It is terribly important that we put a sense
of reality in this situation and ... get this issue before the
American public in a way that the political campaign does not
undermine.''
   Both the federal government and American businesses must wean
themselves away from their dependence on foreign capital, Volcker
said.
   ``People are not going to lend us money indefinitely to finance
the deficit,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
