<2ND_LINE>PM-Wall Street 10am,0317</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market edged upward today, steadying
after Thursday's late selloff.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials rose 3.65 to 2,021.22 in
the first half hour of trading.
   Gainers outnumbered losers by about 4 to 3 in the overall tally
of New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 602 up, 459 down and
432 unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 25.32 million shares as of 10
a.m. on Wall Street.
   Analysts said many traders were disappointed at the market's
inability to surpass its early-January highs, as measured by the
Dow Jones industrial average.
   The average seemed to be headed for into new-high territory for
the year Thursday morning, but the advance gave way to selling.
   While evidence continues to accumulate that the economy hasn't
yet suffered any severe effects from last fall's market crash,
brokers say confidence remains fragile.
   The Labor Department's report this morning that the consumer
price index rose 0.3 percent in January was in line with advance
estimates, and had little evidence impact on the market.
   Federated Department Stores rose 1} to 64~ on news that the
company, which has been fighting a takeover bid by Campeau Corp. of
Toronto, was negotiating with Campeau on a proposed purchase at $68
a share.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks
gained .30 to 147.60. At the American Stock Exchange, the market
value index was up .05 at 283.34.
   On Thursday the Dow Jones industrial average, up about 27 points
at its midsession high, closed with a 22.38 loss at 2,017.57.
   Declining issues outnumbered advances by more than 8 to 7 on the
NYSE, with 689 up, 802 down and 473 unchanged. Big Board volume
totaled 213.49 million shares, against 212.73 million in the
previous session.
