<1ST_LINE>u f PM-EconomyRdp 1stLd-Writethru f0005 02-26 0672</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Economy Rdp, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0005,0688</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Stronger Economic Expansion Doesn't Impress Wall Street</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Tops with 10 new grafs with January consumer prices, spending
and personal income. Picks up 3rd graf pvs bgng, The Dow Jones ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Consumer prices rose 0.3 percent in January, matching 0.3
percent increases in American's personal incomes and consumer
spending for the same month, the government reported today.
   The rise in the Labor Department's Consumer Price Index was
larger than the 0.2 percent rise in December and matched November's
0.3 percent rise. The gain in December was revised from the
previously reported 0.1 percent.
   Pacing the January increase in consumer prices were widespread
gains across a range of goods and services, including a 0.3 percent
gain in food prices.
   Energy prices, however, fell 0.7 percent after a 0.8 percent
drop in the preceding month, the report said.
   The overall increase in January prices was equivalent to an
annual rate of inflation of 4.2 percent, compared with the 4.4
percent rise for all of 1987.
   The January gains reported by the Commerce Department in
personal income and consumer spending were less than half the gains
posted in December.
   The department said the 0.3 percent seasonally adjusted increase
in incomes followed a 0.7 percent rise in December and was the
slowest income gain since a 0.4 percent decline in November.
   The 0.3 percent rise in spending represented a slowdown from a
0.7 percent December advance. Spending had risen 0.5 percent in
November after falling 0.7 percent in October, reflecting a decline
in auto purchases that month.
   The reports came a day after the government reported that
economic expansion at the end of 1987 reached the fastest level in
almost two years.
   The Commerce Department's announcement Thursday that the economy
grew at a 4.5 percent annual rate in the last three months of last
year initially rallied Wall Street but stocks later fell sharply.
Bond prices and the dollar also fell.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials, up about 27 points at
its midsession high, closed with a 22.38-point loss at 2,017.57,
most of it in the last hour of trading.
   ``There is a considerable amount of confusion in the financial
markets'' about the strength of the economy, said Jack Barbanel,
senior vice president at Gruntal & Co. in New York.
   The growth in the gross national product, the broadest measure
of the economy, was revised up from an original estimate of 4.2
percent made a month ago.
   The Reagan administration said the growth rate showed the
economic recovery, now in its sixth year, a record for peacetime,
was suffering no ill effects from the October stock market
collapse. However, private economists said they were still
concerned about the one-sided nature of the growth.
   The rapid expansion in the fourth quarter occured without a
pickup in inflation. A price index tied to the GNP rose at an
annual rate of 3.7 percent from October through December, little
changed from a 3.4 percent increase in the third quarter.
   Three-fourths of the growth last quarter came from a buildup of
business inventories, occurring at the same time that consumer
spending was plunging 3.1 percent, the biggest spending drop in
more than seven years.
   The last such sharp drop in consumer spending occurred in 1980
during the recession that year which helped doom President Jimmy
Carter's re-election bid.
   Some analysts said the revisions made in the new GNP report made
them more confident that a recession can be avoided. Others said
they were encouraged because the report showed that consumer
spending, while falling sharply, was not as weak as previously
believed. The report also increased the estimate of business
investment spending, another area of expected strength.
   The fourth-quarter gain boosted growth for the year to 3.9
percent, when measured from the end of 1986, up slightly from the
3.8 percent estimate made a month ago. Growth when all four
quarters of the year are averaged together showed a 2.9 percent
increase in 1987, the same as 1986.
</TEXT>
