<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Northwest-Strike     02-26 0667</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Northwest-Strike,0690</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Union: Strike By Flight Attendants Imminent</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TONY KENNEDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BLOOMINGTON, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Northwest Airlines and its flight
attendants are on a ``collision course'' and a strike by the
attendants appears to be imminent, according to a Teamsters union
official.
   Several dozen flight attendants demonstrated Thursday night
outside the Eagan, Minn., home of Northwest Chief Executive Officer
Steven Rothmeier. The home was watched by private guards and Eagan
police.
   ``Mr. Rothmeier has been traveling around the circuit all of
this week, visiting all of our flight attendant bases; we thought
it was only polite to return the favor,'' flight attendant Dottie
Malinski told WCCO-TV.
   It was not known if Rothmeier was home at the time.
   Talks continued Thursday as flight attendants prepared to walk
off their jobs at 11:01 CST tonight.
   ``There's a 100 percent chance of a strike,'' William Genoese,
director of the Teamsters' airline division, said at a morning news
conference Thursday. ``As far as I'm concerned we're on a collision
course with Northwest Airlines to strike.''
   But Redmond Tyler, a spokesman for the airline, said progress
was being made on some of the major contract issues. The two sides
have been meeting steadily since Tuesday at Northwest's
headquarters in Eagan with the assistance of a federal mediator,
Tyler said Thursday.
   Seniority wage scales, pensions and work rules are among the
major issues in the dispute. Former Republic Airlines flight
attendants have been working under their old contract since
Northwest acquired Republic in 1986. The company is trying to bring
the workers under one contract.
   ``We believe we're making substantial progress at the bargaining
table,'' Tyler said. ``We're not Jimmy the Greek, but we continue
to believe that we will get this resolved without a strike.''
   Flight attendants have voted overwhelmingly to strike if a
contract agreement isn't reached by the 11 p.m. CST deadline. The
national president of the International Association of Machinists
has vowed his union's support, but the telegram that contains the
message stops short of saying machinists would honor picket lines.
   Officials at national and local IAM offices did not return a
reporter's phone calls Thursday.
   Tyler said the machinists are under a contract that forbids them
to strike in sympathy with another union. ``We expect our
machinists to honor their contract,'' he said.
   Pilots are barred from sympathy strikes under provisions of the
Railway Labor Act, Tyler said.
   Asked if those workers would be locked out if they walk off
their jobs in sympathy with the flight attendants, Tyler said, ``We
won't address that because we don't want to play that `what if?'
game.''
   Genoese said flight attendants would have the full backing of
the international Teamsters, which could result in delays of supply
shipments from truckers.
   ``We're putting all our power together in the next 24 hours,''
Genoese said. ``We would like to put them (Northwest) at 10 to 20
percent'' of operations if there is a strike.
   Genoese said he is hopeful that pilots would honor picket lines,
but Jim Halverson of the Air Line Pilots Association said pilots
would not decide until today.
   Tyler said the airline is armed with about 2,000 management
workers who are certified as flight attendants to step in if the
6,700 union flight attendants strike.
   The machinists union represents about 20,000 airline mechanics,
baggage handlers, aircraft cleaners, ticket and reservation agents
and clerical workers at Northwest.
   Genoese said Thursday the Teamsters are researching the
possibilities of an employee-led leveraged buyout of Northwest and
other airlines to protect the long-term interests of workers.
   He said his union has talked with Salomon Brothers Inc. and
other Wall Street investment firms to consider financing
arrangements. However, Robert Salomon, managing director and chief
spokesman of the firm, said he is unaware of any contact between
the Teamsters and his company on the issue.
   Genoese said discussions of a possible leveraged buyout of
Northwest could help the bargaining position of flight attendants,
but he said the talk was not a ploy.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
