<HEAD>Soybean Futures Retreat; Grains Mostly Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soybean futures prices retreated and grain
futures were mostly lower in early, choppy trading today at the
Chicago Board of Trade.
   Follow-through selling from Thursday pressured the markets,
while a flurry of buying by big professional traders helped offset
losses, analysts said.
   Continued heavy rains in Brazil, which have eased dry,
crop-threatening conditions, and other outside factors added a
negative tone to the market, said Victor Lespinasse, an analyst
with Dean Witter Reynolds Inc.
   ``It's mostly a technical trade, no big surprises,'' Lespinasse
said.
   In early trading, wheat was \ cent to } cent lower, with the
contract for delivery in March at $3.17{ a bushel; corn was \ cent
lower to \ cent higher, with March at $1.98{ a bushel; oats were \
cent to { cent lower, with March at $1.90} a bushel; and soybeans
were 2 cents to 3 cents lower, with March at $6.18 a bushel.
   Futures prices for cattle and pork bellies advanced while hog
futures were mixed at the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   In early trading, live cattle were .20 cent to .28 cent higher,
with the contract for delivery in April at 72.60 cents a pound;
feeder cattle were .08 cent to .33 cent higher, with March at 81
cents a pound; hogs were .2 cent lower to .18 cent higher, with
April at 44.10 cents a pound; and frozen pork bellies were .03 to
.25 cent higher, with March at 52.60 cents a pound.
   Cattle futures were choppy but ended higher Thursday, while pork
futures rallied.
</TEXT>
