<FILEID>AP-NR-02-26-88 1307EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-China-Chrysler Bjt   02-26 0512</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-China-Chrysler, Bjt,0526</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Chrysler Says It Wants To Produce in China</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM ABRAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chrysler Corp. hopes to add passenger cars to the
line of Jeeps it already produces in China, a top official of the
automaker said Friday.
   Gerald Greenwald, head of the Chrysler Motors division of
Chrysler Corp., said in an interview that his company was
negotiating with First Automotive Works of Changchun, in northeast
China, to produce upscale autos for use as official cars and taxis.
   First Automotive hopes to begin construction by the end of the
year on a plant that initially would produce 30,000 cars a year,
with potential capacity of 150,000, Greenwald said.
   If successful, Chrysler would be the first American automaker to
set up passsenger car production in China, and the third foreign
company. Peugeot has a small joint venture in Canton, and
Volkswagen produces about 10,000 vehicles a year at its Shanghai
plant.
   China produced about 400,000 motor vehicles last year, almost
all trucks and buses. Only about 20,000 passenger cars were built.
   Chrysler inherited a stake in China last year when it took over
American Motors Corp., which produces Cherokee Jeeps as part of a
joint venture known as Beijing Jeep Co.
   Beijing Jeep has had a rocky road since it began as a
much-heralded Sino-American joint venture in 1984. Two years ago,
the plant shut down for two months because it ran out of foreign
currency to import the parts it needed to stay in operation. The
Chinese government finally agreed to provide financial support
after exacting promises that the plant would use more domestically
produced components.
   Greenwald said that currently about 18 percent of parts are made
locally. He said the process to increase the local percentage will
take years, but that eventually, as production climbs from the
current 4,000 vehicles a year to 30,000-40,000 vehicles,
localization of parts could top 50 percent.
   ``We have an excellent start with the two projects'' with Beijin
Jeep and First Automotive, Greenwald said. ``We want to move ahead
at a faster pace.''
   Greenwald said he did not know what other companies were bidding
for the passenger-car contract, but Chrysler is thought to have an
edge because it signed a deal with First Automotive last July to
supply technology for four-cylinder engines to the company. The
Chinese company is to produce 150,000 engines under the initial
stage of the agreement with Chrysler.
   At the end of last year, the Chinese government sent a
high-level delegation to the United States to seek a partner in a
major auto production joint venture. Chrysler is believed to have
an advantage because of its previous activities in China, although
General Motors Corp. sold an engine assembly line to China last
month in what it said was a first step toward eventual
co-production.
   Greenwald said the 2.2-liter engine to be produced in Changchun
could be used in First Automotive's envisioned car, giving the
company a needed boost in its drive to cut back on foreign currency
spending by relying on domestically produced parts.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
