<2ND_LINE>BC-Britain-Stocks, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0024,0191</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>London Shares Drop</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: RECASTS throughout to UPDATE with trading activity, closing
index; No pickup</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices dropped on the London Stock Exchange
Friday as investor sentiment turned sour and trading volume thinned.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index was down 15.9
points, or 0.9 percent, at 1,766.5 at the close. The index's low
for the trading session was 17.8 points down.
   Volume fell to a light 350.2 million shares from 510.1 million
on Thursday.
   A strong rally earlier this week seemed to run out of steam as
the index approached strong technical resistance at the 1,800-point
level, dealers said.
   In addition, losses on Wall Street Thursday and sharp declines
on the London stock futures market took their toll on British
stocks, they said.
   ``It's amazing how quickly confidence can change, showing we're
still very nervous'' in the wake of October's stock crash, one
dealer said.
   However, the market still views the British economy as sound,
and a string of company earnings results this week indicated that
corporate profits are being maintained despite the crash, dealers
said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880226-0259 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-26-88 1759EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Mexico-Debt     02-26 0395</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mexico-Debt,0410</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mexico to Give Responses to Bond Bids by March 4</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ANDERSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government will announce by March 4 its
response to foreign banks' secret bids for bonds offered by Mexico
in an innovative plan to reduce its $105 billion in foreign debt,
the Treasury Department said.
   Mexico's approximately 560 creditor banks had until 4 p.m. EST
Friday to submit their sealed bids under the plan, devised by the
Mexican and U.S. governments.
   New York-based J.P. Morgan & Co., exchange agent for the deal,
refused to disclose details of the bids.
   Over the next week, Mexican officials will consider how much
debt would be cleared and service cost reductions in determining
whether to accept each bid, the Treasury Department said in a
statement.
   The plan involves exchanging some of the debt Mexico owes
foreign commercial bankers for new, 20-year bonds to be issued by
the government.
   The bonds, backed by $10 billion worth of special U.S. Treasury
securities, will carry a higher interest rate than Mexico is paying
on the old debt.
   Mexico's potential savings ``will be in proportion to the offers
that are accepted,'' the department said in a statement carried by
the government newspaper El Nacional.
   In addition to the bond scheme, the government ``will present
other options and programs'' to its creditors to reduce the
country's debt burden, the Treasury statement added.
   It refused to predict how much principal and interest the
government might save under the bond program, saying each bank bid
must be analyzed first. But Mexican officials previously have
warned that if the offers are not attractive enough, they may
reject all of them.
   Participating banks sought to get as much money as they could
for their old loans, while Mexico wants to buy the debt cheaply.
   Most analysts expected bidders to offer discounts of between 30
cents and 40 cents to the dollar. Mexican debt paper sold for 48
cents to the dollar in early February.
   Observers doubted the government could market the entire $10
billion package. Mexican officials, they said, would consider at
least $3 billion in securities sales to be acceptable.
   The Treasury Department said that at the least, the Mexican bond
scheme had achieved a ``formal recognition'' by Mexican creditors
of the difference between the debt's book value and that commanded
on secondary markets.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880226-0260 </DOCNO>
