<2ND_LINE>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0194</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soybean Futures Advance; Grains Mixed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soybean futures prices advanced and grain futures
were mixed in trading Friday at the Chicago Board of Trade.
   A wave of buying by big professional traders sparked a rally in
soybeans and also helped support corn futures, analysts said.
   Jitters early in the trading session over crop-bolstering rains
in Brazil's soybean region subsided later in the day, and traders
discounted that as a negative factor, said Victor Lespinasse, an
analyst with Dean Witter Reynolds Inc.
   ``Big professional buying late in the day helped the beans to
rally to new highs,'' he said.
   Technical rather than outside factors had the biggest influence
on the markets, he said.
   At the close, wheat was unchanged to 2\ cent lower, with the
contract for delivery in March at $3.15{ a bushel; corn was \ cent
higher to 2\ cents higher, with March at $2.00} a bushel; oats were
} cent lower to 1 cent higher, with March at $1.90\ a bushel; and
soybeans were 3 cents to 5} cents higher, with March at $6.25 a
bushel.
</TEXT>
