<FILEID>AP-NR-02-26-88 1538EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f BC-Europe-Takeover     02-26 0425</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Europe-Takeover,0443</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Shares of Societe Generale Frozen as Takeover Battle Rages</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Brussels Stock Exchange officials
suspended trading in Societe Generale de Belgique SA for a second
straight day Friday, as soaring demand for the stock highlighted
the intense battle for control over Belgium's biggest holding
company.
   Societe Generale shares opened with offers hitting a record
8,060 francs, or $230.30 per share, up 15 percent over Thursday.
   On Thursday, Italian investor Carlo De Benedetti had doubled his
original offer to 8,000 francs, or $228.60.
   De Benedetti claims to control 45 percent of Societe Generale
stock. He wants 7 more percent to counter an alliance of French,
Belgian, Luxembourg and Swiss investors, which claims it controls
52 percent of Societe Generale shares.
   De Benedetti disputes that claim.
   Societe Generale management, which supports the alliance, denied
reports of a rift within the group on Friday.
   ``There are accords between different partners to be sure this
majority exists,'' said Etienne Davignon, a Societe Generale
director.
   The Italian financier has said he wanted to expand Societe
Generale's holdings throughout Europe by 1992, when the European
Economic Community expects to have removed all internal bariers to
trade among the 12 EEC nations.
   The alliance opposing De Benedetti wants the 166-year-old
company to remain anchored in Belgium.
   Trading in Societe Generale was first halted Thursday, after the
share price rose to a record 7,010 francs, or $200, shortly after
the stock exchange opened.
   The stock closed at 6,100 francs, or $174.29, Wednesday and at
5,350 francs, or $152.86, Tuesday. It stood at 2,155 francs, or
$61.58, last October, when hints of the looming takeover battle
began to appear.
   On Friday, a new freeze forced any trading in the share off the
exchange to the unofficial market.
   This market has accounted for millions of transactions on given
days over the course of the last few months, but has largely dried
up in recent days to the lack of available shares.
   ``We had offers as high as 10,000 francs (or $285) per share but
had no paper for them,'' said one dealer at a major brokerage firm.
   The alliance battling De Benedetti is formed around the French
firms Compagnie Financiere de Suez, an investment firm, Compagnie
Generale d'Electricite, an industrial company, and Societe
Financiere et Industrielle Gaz et Eaux.
   Together they control 36 percent while an international group
around Belgium's biggest insurance company, Groupe AG, controls
another 16 percent.
   The 166-year-old Societe Generale has interests in some 1,400
firms world-wide and in about half of Belgium's top 50 companies.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
