<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Ponderosa     02-26 0258</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Ponderosa,0267</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Metromedia Acquiring Ponderosa Steakhouse Chain</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SECAUCUS, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Metromedia Co. has signed a definitive
agreement to acquire the Ponderosa Inc. restaurant chain for an
undisclosed amount, the company announced Friday.
   Metromedia, a privately-held telecommunications and technology
holding company, said it planned to keep Ponderosa management in
place and anticipated no changes in the company's operation.
   Ponderosa, which was taken private in a $331 million buyout led
by New York investor Asher B. Edelman in January 1987, is one of
the nation's largest steakhouse chains, with annual sales of $500
million.
   The Dayton, Ohio-based company owns and operates 400 restaurants
nationwide and franchises another 280 in the United States and
Canada, and has a meat processing and distribution operation
through its ESI Meats Inc. unit.
   After Edelman acquired the company he sold off a number of
assets, including most of its Casa Lupita restaurants and a
meat-processing company, to help pay off debt used to finance the
buyout.
   ``We believe that Ponderosa is an outstanding company: it is
strong and well-positioned with excellent management and great
potential for growth and expansion,'' said Stuart Subotnick,
Metromedia executive vice president and general partner.
   Metromedia formerly was the nation's biggest independent
television and radio broadcasting company. John Kluge, who owns 97
percent of the present company, liquidated most of its holdings
after taking Metromedia private in 1984.
   Kluge has said he planned to use Metromedia as the vehicle for a
broad-based investment program. In addition to long-distance
telephone operations, the company owns robotic painting and
computer software companies.
</TEXT>
