<FILEID>AP-NR-02-26-88 2245EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Brokers-NYSE     02-26 0234</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brokers-NYSE,0242</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Another Specialist Withdraws Voluntarily</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   For the fifth time since the October stock
market crash, a stock specialist firm has agreed to give up its
role as a market maker in a New York Stock Exchange issue, the
exchange said Friday.
   The NYSE said Wagner, Stott & Co. had voluntarily withdrawn as
the specialist in the stock of Carter-Wallace Inc., a drug and
consumer products company based in New York.
   The exchange said in a news release that the stock would be
reallocated to another specialist firm March 10.
   Catherine Maroney, a NYSE spokeswoman, said the exchange would
not disclose the reason for the reallocation. The press release
said the exchange had been reviewing the performance by Wagner
Stott on Oct. 20, the day after the historic market collapse.
   The NYSE is investigating several cases in which its 53
specialists failed to maintain orderly trading in stocks they
controlld. The specialist firms control the rights to market
certain issues and are required to keep order by setting opening
prices and covering trades when there are too few buyers or sellers.
   Previously, Spear, Leeds & Kellogg surrendered its franchise in
J.P. Morgan & Co. stock; M.J. Meehan & Co. withdrew its rights to
Gould Inc.; Lawrence, O'Donnell & Co. gave up Neiman-Marcus Group
Inc.; and LaBranche & Co. agreed to drop E.F. Hutton Group Inc. and
A.G. Edwards Inc.
</TEXT>
