<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Federated-Campeau 1stld-Writethru   02-26 0662</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Federated-Campeau, 1st ld - Writethru,0680</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Campeau, Federated Negotiating for Merger</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBs 7th graf Federated stock...to UPDATE with closing stock
price.</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserGraphic planned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN NOLAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After a month of public discord, Campeau Corp.
and Federated Department Stores Inc. announced Friday they had
opened negotiations on a $6.1 billion merger agreement.
   Federated's board of directors, which met in regular session
Thursday, authorized the merger talks, in which Campeau proposes to
pay $68 in cash for each share of Federated.
   The proposal, which followed Campeau's pledge to sell off its
Brooks Brothers division to help finance the merger, is to be
presented to the Federated board Monday, the companies said in
their joint announcement.
   ``No assurance can be given that a definitive agreement will be
reached,'' the companies said.
   It was the first sign of a softening in Campeau's month-long,
increasingly hostile campaign to buy Federated. The
Cincinnati-based Federated had $11 billion in sales last year. The
Toronto-based Campeau, a development company, bought Allied Stores
Corp. in December 1986.
   ``Sixty-eight dollars per share is a good price. The
shareholders should be happy,'' said Monroe H. Greenstein, an
analyst with the Bear Stearns firm in New York City.
   Federated stock rose $1.50 to $64.50 a share in late New York
Stock Exchange trading Friday.
   The merger proposal is separate from Campeau's latest hostile
takeover offer, its $66-per-share tender bid made Thursday, Campeau
spokeswoman Joele Frank said Friday in New York City. That offer
was improved from a previous $61-per-share proposal.
   Federated has 90.4 million common shares and equivalents
outstanding. In addition to acquiring the company's 88.5 million
outstanding shares, Campeau would pay about $100 million to buy up
outstanding Federated stock options.
   ``What's new about this is that negotiations are under way and
that the price has been agreed on,'' Ms. Frank said.
   Greenstein predicted that Campeau Corp. would _ if it buys
Federated _ sell off some Federated holdings, including
non-department store assets and underperforming department store
groups.
   Greenstein said those groups might include I. Magnin in San
Francisco, Lazarus in Cincinnati and Abraham & Straus in New York.
``All these have been known to be under-performers in recent
years,'' he said.
   Thursday, the Canadian company increased its tender offer to
Federated from $61 to $66 per share and said it would consider
making a higher bid if necessary. Campeau has been bidding to buy
Federated since Jan. 25.
   Federated's board said Friday it has deferred until 11:59 p.m.
EST Monday implementation of a ``poison pill'' shareholder rights
measure designed to make a takeover of Federated more difficult.
The board said it could later decide to further delay the measure's
implementation.
   Federated has rejected previous Campeau takeover bids,
questioning whether Campeau had obtained the necessary financing.
Campeau chairman Robert Campeau says he has the financing and would
be willing to match offers by other bidders for Federated.
   Campeau said Thursday it would raise a substantial amount of
equity for its proposed buyout by selling the Brooks Brothers
division of its Allied Stores Corp. unit to Britain's Marks and
Spencer PLC for $770 million. The Brooks Brothers sale was
conditioned on Campeau acquiring Federated.
   The Brooks Brothers sale also could preempt antitrust concerns
raised by Sen. Howard Metzenbaum, D-Ohio, in connection with the
proposed Federated acquisition. Metzenbaum is concerned that a
Campeau purchase of Federated could hurt competition in some U.S.
markets, such as New York and Miami, where both Allied and
Federated operate stores.
   Federated's board has previously rejected offers of $66 and $47
per share. The company has been considering alternatives, such as
selling some of its non-department store assets or having
management buy the company and convert it to private ownership.
   Federated operates 650 stores nationwide. Its holdings include
the New York chains Bloomingdale's and Abraham and Straus, Filene's
of Boston, Burdines of Miami, Rich's in Atlanta, Bullock's and
Bullocks Wilshire in Los Angeles, I. Magnin in San Francisco and
Lazarus in Cincinnati.
</TEXT>
