<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Dart-Stop&Shop     02-26 0373</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dart-Stop & Shop,0384</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dart Calls for Stop & Shop Shareholder Meeting</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LANDOVER, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dart Group Corp. announced Friday that it
passed another hurdle in its attempt to oust the board of directors
of Stop & Shop Cos. Inc. in its $1.03 billion hostile takeover bid
for the supermarket chain.
   Dart said its 95 percent-owned affiliate, Jefferson Partnership,
submitted to Stop & Shop applications from holders of more than 10
percent of Stop & Shop's outstanding shares calling for a special
shareholders meeting on March 30, according to Dart spokesman
Stanley Rubenstein.
   Dart says the meeting, which is being demanded under
Massachusetts' Business Corporation Law, is to consider replacing
Stop & Shop's board with Jefferson's nominees and adopting related
resolutions.
   Stop & Shop spokeswoman Aileen Gorman declined to comment on
Dart's latest announcement.
   Stop & Shop, based in Braintree, Mass., on Feb. 12 filed a
federal suit to block Dart's $37-a-share offer. Stop & Shop claimed
that Dart failed to register as an investment company with the
federal Securities and Exchange Commission and failed to disclose
details of its past takeover attempts.
   Dart responded with a countersuit, claiming that Stop & Shop
illegally withheld corporate information. U.S. District Judge Rya
Zobel ruled Dart must file its claim in Norfolk Superior Court in
Massachusetts.
   As of Wednesday, Jefferson Partnership had acquired more than
73,000 shares of Stop & Shop, about 2.7 percent of the company's
outstanding shares.
   Stop & Shop operates 113 Stop & Shop supermarkets and 169
Bradlees discount department stores from Maine to North Carolina.
   Speculation mounted Friday that Stop & Shop could soon be sold
to an outside bidder.
   One union representing Stop & Shop workers said Thursday it
wanted to be included in any sale negotiations, said Robert
Petronella, international vice president and New England regional
director for the United Food and Commercial Workers Union, which
represents about 20,000 Stop & Shop employees.
   Recently, UFCW union leaders agreed to take a strike vote if
there was not a new contract for Stop & Shop employees by March 6.
   Dart, based in Landover, owns Crown Books and Trak Auto Parts.
It has mounted other hostile takeover attempts targeting retail
chain Dayton Hudson Corp., Safeway Co. and Supermarkets General.
</TEXT>
