<DOCNO> AP880226-0281 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-26-88 2003EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-MarksandSpencer 1stLd-Writethru f0144 02-26 0847</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Marks and Spencer, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0144,0872</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Big British Retailer Nears Major U.S. Beachhead</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto planned</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: SUBS 3rd graf to CORRECT that sale is conditioned on Campeau
acquiring Federated; Brooks Brothers is owned by Campeau, not
Federated; picks up 4th graf pvs bg'ng, Campeau and Federated ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By COTTEN TIMBERLAKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Marks and Spencer PLC, where Prime Minister
Margaret Thatcher shops, is poised to establish a major U.S.
beachhead with its planned purchase of the preppy clothier Brooks
Brothers.
   ``Marks and Sparks,'' as the 550-store chain is affectionately
known among rhyme-loving Londoners, has been seeking to expand in
the United States for more than a year as part of its strategy of
becoming a global retailer.
   Marks and Spencer announced Thursday it had agreed in principle
to buy Brooks Brothers for $770 million from Campeau Corp., the
Canadian retailing and real estate company, if Campeau acquired
Federated Department Stores Inc. of Cincinnati.
   Campeau and Federated disclosed Friday they were negotiating a
$6.1 billion merger but said there was no guarantee they would
reach a definitive merger agreement. Federated already has rejected
several lower offers from Campeau.
   Marks and Spencer has grown in 104 years from a market stall to
a favorite store of the average Briton. It's also where Mrs.
Thatcher buys her underwear because, she says, it is well made.
   The retailer hopes to get Brooks Brothers' flagship store on New
York City's Madison Avenue, its 46 other U.S. stores and 12
joint-venture outlets in Japan.
   British retailers have boomed in recent years on strong spending
by consumers and their increased use of credit. This has prompted
some retailers to ponder expansion outside Britain, which they now
see as too small a market.
   ``Marks and Spencer needs to become a global retailer and to a
certain extent hey do need to get into the U.S. market to fulfill
that ambition,'' said Charles Allen, an industry consultant with
the investment firm Wood Mackenzie and Co.
   Other British retailers that have expanded into the United
States by acquisition or opening of new stores include Storehouse
PLC, owner of the Conran's home furnishing stores, Dixons Group
PLC, owner of the Silo electric appliance chain, and the jeweler
Ratners PLC.
   But reaction to Marks and Spencer's plans were mixed in the
City, London's financial district.
   Marks and Spencer fell 4.5 pence, about 8 cents at current
exchange rtes, to 176 pence, or $3.12, a share late Friday on the
London Stock exchange after falling the same amount on Thursday.
   Analysts agreed the retailer should target the United States but
were divided about whether the acquisition of Brooks Brothers was
the right choice and whether Marks and Spencer agreed to pay too
high a price.
   Some also expressed concern that Marks and Spencer was
establishing its beachhead in a portion of the U.S. market that
might be softening.
   Wood Mackenzie's Allen said the company agreed too quickly to
something that wasn't a sure deal.
   Marks and Spencer's pre-tax profit growth will slow to 5 percent
from 10 percent in its new fiscal year beginning April 3 because of
the acquisition, Allen predicted.
   But Paul Backhouse, a retail analyst with the investment firm
Morgan Grenfell and Co., said: ``This is a long-term move for Marks
and Spencer.''
   Analysts also noted that although many foreigners view the U.S
market as uniform, it has regional differences that make marketing
products challenging.
   Marks and Spencer stated Thursday: ``The acquisition of Brooks
Brothers would represent a substantial opportunity for Marks and
Spencer to enter the U.S. retail clothing market through a major
long-established business with a high reputation for quality.''
   Marks and Spencer said it wants to use its retailing expertise
to boost Brooks Brothers' business.
   Brooks Brothers and Marks and Spencer are similar in that they
both sell durable, quality merchandise under their own brand name
and they stick with classic designs.
   But there are some big differences. Brooks Brothers caters to a
small clientele of the well-to-do; Marks and Spencer markets huge
volumes to the middle class.
   Marks and Spencer also sells more than clothes. It sells food
under its St. Michael brand name, and home furnishings.
   Marks and Spencer ventured into the U.S. market last year by
opening four women's clothing stores in upstate New York under the
name D'Allaird's.
   A Marks and Spencer spokeswoman, who did not want to be named,
declined to detail how the stores were faring but said the company
remained optimistic about their prospects.
   Marks and Spencer has had mixed results with its efforts to
expand into other foreign countries.
   Profits for its 11 stores in the rest of Europe jumped 25
percent in its most recent fiscal year. But in Canada, where it
operates 260 stores, its profit sank 61 percent.
   The company plans to open a store under its own name in Hong
Kong in May.
   Marks and Spencer's pre-tax profit jumped 18 percent to 432
million pounds, about $765 million, in the year ended March 1987 on
a 13.5 percent revenue gain to 4.2 billion pounds, $7.4 billion.
</TEXT>
