<DOCNO> AP880226-0284 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-02-26-88 2051EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Japan-Markets     02-26 0236</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Japan-Markets,0245</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Japanese Share Prices Continue To Rise</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japanese share prices posted modest gains at the
start of half-day trading in Tokyo Saturday following an overnight
rise on Wall Street, and analysts predicted a 13th consecutive day
of gains in a market intent on recouping its losses after the
October crash.
   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, the Nikkei stock average of 225
selected issues, which gained 64.52 points Friday for the 12th
straight trading day, gained another 5.74 points, or 0.02 percent,
in the first 15 minutes of trading to rise to 25,170.92.
   ``It's the 13th day of straight gains and the market is
definitely headed for a rally ... it's 100 percent sure,'' said a
trader with Nikko Securities, one of Japan's four largest
brokerages.
   The index stood at 25,746.56 points just before the mid-October
crash when it lost nearly 4,000 points in one trading day. It was
the largest single day drop for the Nikkei.
   The trader, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said Tokyo
trading opened on a positive note, taking the lead from moderate
gains in New York Friday, and then shot up by some 40 points by
mid-morning.
   Trading companies and supermarket issues were winners, he said.
   Other notables included precision machine makers such as as
Olympus and Ricoh, as well as pulp and paper, transportation and
nonferrous metals.
   The Tokyo foreign-exchange market is closed on Saturdays.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
